{"title_page": "Joschka Fischer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Joschka Fischer\n|image          = Joschka Fischer 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|caption        = Fischer on 14 September 2014\n\n|office         = [[Vice Chancellor of Germany]]\n|chancellor     = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n|term_start     = 27 October 1998\n|term_end       = 22 November 2005\n|predecessor    = [[Klaus Kinkel]]\n|successor      = [[Franz M\u00fcntefering]]\n\n|office1        = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|Federal Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n|chancellor1    = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n|term_start1    = 27 October 1998\n|term_end1      = 22 November 2005\n|predecessor1   = [[Klaus Kinkel]]\n|successor1     = [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]\n\n|office2      = Member of the [[Bundestag]] <br> for [[Hesse]]\n|term_start2  = 16 October 1994\n|term_end2    = 1 September 2006\n|constituency2= [[Electoral system of Germany|Alliance '90/The Greens List]]\n\n|term_start3  = 6 March 1983\n|term_end3    = 31 March 1985\n|predecessor3 = [[Electoral system of Germany|The Greens List]]\n\n|office4        = [[Politics of Hesse|Deputy Minister President of Hesse]]\n|primeminister4 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start4    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end4      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor4   = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]]\n|successor4     = Rupert von Plottnitz\n\n|office5        = [[Politics of Hesse|Hessian Minister of Environment and Energy]]\n|primeminister5 = [[Holger B\u00f6rner]]\n|term_start5    = 12 December 1985\n|term_end5      = 9 February 1987\n|predecessor5   = Position established\n|successor5     = Armin Clauss {{small|(Acting)}}\n\n|primeminister6 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start6    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end6      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor6   = Karlheinz Weimar\n|successor6     = Rupert von Plottnitz\n\n|office7        = [[Politics of Hesse|Hessian Minister of Federal Affairs]]\n|primeminister7 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start7    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end7      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor7   = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]] {{small|(Agent of Federal Affairs)}}\n|successor7     = Rupert von Plottnitz\n\n|birthname      = Joseph Martin Fischer\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1948|4|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Gerabronn]], [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden]], [[Allied-occupied Germany]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Alliance '90/The Greens]]\n|spouse       = Edeltraud Fischer {{small|(1967\u20131984)}}<br />Inge Peusquens {{small|(1984\u20131987)}}<br />Claudia Bohm {{small|(1987\u20131998)}}<br />Nicola Leske {{small|(1999\u20132003)}}<br />Minu Barati-Fischer {{small|(m 2005)}}\n|children     = David<br />Lara\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Martin \"Joschka\" Fischer''' (born 12 April 1948) is a [[Germany|German]] politician of the [[Alliance '90/The Greens]]. He served as [[Foreign Minister of Germany|Foreign Minister]] and as [[Vice Chancellor of Germany]] in the cabinet of [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] from 1998 to 2005. Fischer has been a leading figure in the German Greens since the 1970s, and according to opinion polls,<ref>{{cite web |title=Weiterhin gro\u00dfe Unzufriedenheit mit den Spitzenpolitikern |date=4 July 2003 |url=http://tsarchive.wordpress.com/2003/07/04/meldung330600/ |language=de |accessdate=24 April 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://tsarchive.wordpress.com/2003/07/04/meldung330600/ |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> he was the most popular politician in Germany for most of the government's duration. Following the [[2005 German federal election|September 2005 election]], in which the Schr\u00f6der government was defeated, he left office on 22 November 2005. In September 2010 he supported the creation of the [[Spinelli Group]], a europarliamentarian initiative founded with a view to reinvigorate efforts to federalise the European Union.\n\n==Early life==\nFischer was born in [[Gerabronn]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], the third child of a butcher, whose family had lived in [[Budakeszi]], [[Hungary]], for several generations. Fischer's family had to leave Hungary in 1946 after it was occupied by the [[Soviet Union]], and [[Germans of Hungary|ethnic Germans]] were persecuted and expelled by the authorities. His nickname ''Joschka'' is derived from the Hungarian ''J\u00f3ska'', diminutive of Joseph (Hungarian ''J\u00f3zsef''). He was brought up Catholic and served in his childhood as an altar boy in his parish in [[Oeffingen]].<ref>{{cite news|author=M. Drobinski |url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/leben/prominente-ministranten-vor-dem-altar-gestaehlt-fuers-leben-1.985487|title=Vor dem Altar gest\u00e4hlt f\u00fcrs Leben }}</ref> Fischer dropped out of high school in 1965, and started an apprenticeship as a photographer, which he quit in 1966. Because Fischer never gained a school-leaving certificate, he never attended a university or a college. He neither did compulsory military service nor the alternative civilian service for conscientious objectors, because he failed his physical examination due to poor eyesight.<ref>{{cite news|author=Christoph Schult |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0,1518,128137,00.html |title=Zivildienst: Hat sich Joschka Fischer gedr\u00fcckt? |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0%2C1518%2C128137%2C00.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Left-wing militant==\nIn 1967, he became active in the [[German student movement]] and [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] movement (post-) 1968 (the so-called ''Spontis''), first in [[Stuttgart]] and after 1968 in [[Frankfurt am Main]]. For his regular income, Fischer took several low-wage jobs, such as working in a left-wing bookstore in Frankfurt. During this period, he began attending university events, including lectures organized by left-wing revolutionary students by [[Theodor W. Adorno]], [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]] and [[Oskar Negt]].<ref>Paul Hockenhos, ''Joschka Fischer and the Making of the Berlin Republic,'' Oxford University Press, 2007, p 86</ref> He studied the works of [[Karl Marx|Marx]], [[Mao Zedong|Mao]] and [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]] and became a member of the militant group, ''Revolution\u00e4rer Kampf'' (Revolutionary Struggle). Fischer was a leader in several street battles involving the radical ''[[Putzgruppe]]'' (literally \"cleaning squad\", with the first syllable being an [[acronym]] for ''Proletarische Union f\u00fcr Terror und Zerst\u00f6rung'', \"Proletarian Union for Terror and Destruction\"), which attacked a number of police officers. Photos of one such brawl in March 1973, which were later to haunt Fischer, show him clubbing policeman Rainer Marx,<ref name=NYT_Firebrand>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Roger|title=Germany's Foreign Minister Is Pursued by His Early Firebrand Self|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C00EEDD123DF936A25752C0A9679C8B63|date=15 January 2001|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=24 April 2008}}</ref> to whom he later publicly apologized.\n\nFischer is a close friend of [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], whom he met during that time. In 1971, he began working for the car manufacturer [[Opel]] and attempted to organise his fellow workers for the coming communist revolution. (This was not organising on behalf of a regular labour union: the vast majority of Opel's workers had already been organised for decades by [[IG Metall]], the German metalworkers' union.) This resulted in his dismissal from the company after six months. Fischer then continued making a living with unskilled work while continuing his activism. He worked as a taxi driver from 1976 to 1981 and later in a bookstore in Frankfurt.\n\nIn the ''Deutscher Herbst'' ([[German autumn]]) of 1977, Germany was rattled by a series of left-wing [[terrorism|terrorist]] attacks by the [[Red Army Faction]] (RAF) and [[Revolutionary Cells (RZ)]]. According to Fischer's own account, witnessing these events, particularly the kidnapping and murder of [[Hanns-Martin Schleyer]] and the [[Operation Entebbe|Entebbe hijacking]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/27/books/review/27hari.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1|newspaper=The New York Times|title=The Red and the Green|first=Johann|last=Hari|date=27 November 2005|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Michael |date=14 February 200 |url=http://www.postwritersgroup.com/archives/kell0211.htm |title=Who is Joschka Fischer? |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525141300/http://www.postwritersgroup.com/archives/kell0211.htm |archivedate=25 May 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> made him renounce violence as a means for political change. Instead, he became involved in the [[new social movements]] and later in the newly founded [[Alliance '90/The Greens|Green Party]], mainly in the state of [[Hesse]]. Nevertheless, in 1978 he said he did not mourn the killings of Schleyer, [[Siegfried Buback]] and [[J\u00fcrgen Ponto]] by the RAF.<ref>Jochen B\u00f6lsche: [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-18370244.html ''Die verlorene Ehre der Apo.''] in: ''[[Der Spiegel]].'' No. 5, 29. January 2001.</ref>\n\nIn May 1981, the Hessian Secretary of Commerce [[Heinz-Herbert Karry]] was murdered with a firearm that in 1973 had been transported in Fischer's car, along with other weapons stolen from an American army base.<ref>{{cite news |last=Karacs |first=Imre |date=3 August 1998 |title=Kohl turns his fire on the Greens |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/kohl-turns-his-fire-on-the-greens-1169537.html |accessdate=July 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525141300/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/kohl-turns-his-fire-on-the-greens-1169537.html |archivedate=25 May 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Fischer maintained he had given the car to the later terrorist [[Hans-Joachim Klein]] solely for the purpose of having Klein fit it with a new engine. Only later had Fischer learned that his car had been used to transport stolen weapons.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nAs Foreign Minister, Fischer apologised for the violence of his ''Putzgruppe'' days, without disassociating himself from the radical movement. Some critics continue to charge that Fischer was the leading figure of a 1976 discussion that led to the use of [[Molotov cocktail]]s in an upcoming demonstration in support of RAF member [[Ulrike Meinhof]]. Fischer was arrested on 14 May 1976 as a suspect in the Molotov cocktail attacks on police, but was released after two days. Fischer stated that he never used Molotov cocktails against the police. The firebombing of policeman [[J\u00fcrgen Weber]]'s police car left Weber with burns over 60% of his body.<ref name=NYT_Firebrand/>\n\n==Green politician==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F065084-0014, Bonn, Pressekonferenz der Gr\u00fcnen, Bundestagswahl.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Joschka Fischer on 17 February 1983]]\n\nFrom 1983 to 1985, Fischer was a member of the [[Bundestag]] for the Green party. His stint in federal parliament saw him frequently engage in a frank and confrontational debating style, exemplified by an incident on 18 October 1984, when he addressed [[Richard St\u00fccklen]], then vice president of the parliament, with the words: \"If I may say so, Mr. President, you are an asshole\" (German: \"Mit Verlaub, Herr Pr\u00e4sident, Sie sind ein Arschloch.\"). In 1985, Fischer became Minister for the Environment in the [[Landtag of Hesse]] in the first governmental [[Red-green alliance|Red-Green coalition]] between the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) and the Greens. Fischer caused a stir when he appeared at his oath of office ceremony wearing [[Athletic shoe|trainers]]. These sneakers are now part of the shoe collection at the [[German Leather Museum|German Leather and Shoe Museum]] in [[Offenbach, Hesse]].\n\nFischer also expressed his thoughts very frankly in the periodical of the Hessian Green party \"Stichwort Gr\u00fcn\". In an interview with ''[[Bunte]]'' magazine published on 27 July 1989, he rejected [[German reunification]] and demanded that the [[reunification clause]] be deleted from the preamble to the [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany]]. Even after the growth of the wave of the refugees from [[East Germany]], Fischer on 20 September 1989 demanded that the Federal Republic renounce reunification. In a column for ''[[Die Tageszeitung]]'' published on 17 November 1989, eight days after the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], he predicted that reunification would not happen. On 1 October 1990, Fischer said he refused to celebrate reunification.<ref name=kas>{{cite web|title=Schlaglichter der deutschen Einheit. Eine kommentierte Chronik(1987-1990)|url=https://www.kas.de/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=b766e451-ebe2-cbd4-72f0-a1824f960320&groupId=252038|website=kas.de|publisher=[[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]]|author=Michael Borchard|pages=17, 20, 22, 23, 28, 48|date=1 October 2008|language=de}}</ref>\n\nFischer was again environment minister in Hessen from 1991 to 1994 and then became co-chairman of the Greens' parliamentary faction in the Bundestag. Fischer was respected for his oratory skills, as well as for his charisma on the political stage. For a large part of the 1990s, with the social democrats languishing in the opinion polls, Fischer's admirers referred to him as the \"real\" leader of the opposition.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} He parlayed his clout into political success, as he moved the Greens to the centre ground of German politics, paving the way for their first participation in the nation's federal government.\n\n==Foreign Minister==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin 13 February 2001-2.jpg|thumb|Fischer with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] on 13 February 2001]]\n\nIn September 1998, the Social Democratic Party of Germany, led by Gerhard Schr\u00f6der, defeated the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] government of [[Helmut Kohl]]. The SPD's 41% and the Greens' 7% of the vote set the two parties on a possible path to government through a coalition. Schr\u00f6der stated his preference for a red-green coalition, as did an overwhelming majority of SPD members.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} After several weeks of negotiations, a SPD-Green government took power on 27 October 1998, with Fischer appointed as Minister of Foreign Affairs. By 2005, he was the second longest-serving foreign minister in German postwar history (after [[Hans-Dietrich Genscher]]).\n\nIn mid-April 1999, Germany came up with the first peace plan, when Fischer produced a proposal, notably including Russia, that would have rewarded the beginning of a Yugoslav pullout from Kosovo with a bombing pause.<ref>Warren Hodge (4 June 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/04/world/crisis-balkans-memo-continent-europeans-impressed-their-own-unity.html Europeans Impressed By Their Own Unity] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In May 1999, however, an antiwar protester flung a bag of red paint at Fischer during a party convention debating [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|NATO\u2019s airstrikes on Yugoslavia]] in the war over Kosovo; Fischer suffered a perforated eardrum.<ref>Tony Czuczka (23 September 2010), [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-09-23/green-party-s-trittin-hit-in-yoghurt-attack-at-hanover-anti-nuclear-event German Greens\u2019 Trittin Hit in Yoghurt Attack, Police Says] ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.</ref>\n\nIn an effort to make it easier for antiwar critics to back Schr\u00f6der\u2019s decision to send German [[Bundeswehr]] troops to [[Afghanistan]] in 2001, Fischer and Development Minister [[Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul]] announced a 256 million marks ($115 million) humanitarian-aid package for Afghan refugees.<ref>William Boston (15 November 2001), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1005774857206960440 Germany's Schroeder Presses Coalition To Back Him With Vote of Confidence] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> In late 2001, Fischer hosted \u2013 under the auspices of the [[United Nations]] \u2013 a ten-day conference at the German [[Hotel Petersberg|government guesthouse]] above the Rhine River, where delegates from four Afghan factions signed the [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)|Bonn Agreement]] establishing a transitional government for the country to replace the deposed [[Taliban]] regime.<ref>Peter Finn (28 November 2001), [http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2001-11-28/news/0111280283_1_northern-alliance-pashtun-delegates Afghan Delegates At U.N. Talks In Germany Urge Tolerance] ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''.</ref> At the time, Germany's longstanding links to Afghanistan and its 2001 chairmanship of the Afghanistan Support Group of countries pledging humanitarian and reconstruction aid for the country, were the reasons it was picked to host the meeting.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/a/a-13-a-2001-11-22-14-afghan-66423982/550167.html Afghan Conference Switched to Bonn for Security Concerns] ''[[Voice of America]]'', 22 November 2001.</ref>\n\nIn September 2001, Fischer summoned Ahmad Azizi, the Iranian ambassador to Germany, for urgent talks after several reformist intellectuals \u2013 including [[Akbar Ganji]], [[Mehrangiz Kar]] and [[Ezzatollah Sahabi]] \u2013 were given prison sentences of between four and 10 years for participating in a [['Iran After the Elections' Conference|2000 academic and cultural conference]] sponsored by the [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation]] in [[Berlin]] in late 2000.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1116536.stm Germany's 'concern' at Iran verdicts] ''[[BBC News]]'', 14 January 2001.</ref>\n\nIn 2005, critics charged that Fischer's relaxing of controls on visa regulations for [[Ukraine]], would allow illegal immigrants to enter [[Germany]] with fake identities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/64507/ |title=Germany's Fischer preps Kyiv students for future |newspaper=[[Kyiv Post]] |date=21 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100422232033/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/64507/ |archivedate=22 April 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> A parliamentary committee was established to examine the case, and unlike in other such committee hearings, Fischer's statement (and that of other top officials) was shown live on public television. Fischer's appearance before the committee lasted twelve hours. (See [[German Visa Affair 2005]]).\n\nFischer represented the German government at the funeral services for [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Foreign Minister]] [[Anna Lindh]] of [[Sweden]] on 19 September 2003 in [[Stockholm]]; [[Pope]] [[List of dignitaries at the funeral of Pope John Paul II|John Paul II]] on 8 April 2005 in [[Rome]]; and former [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|UK Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]] on 12 August 2005 in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/cook-funeral-hears-blair-s-moral-failure-criticised-1.1181252 Cook funeral hears Blair's 'moral failure' criticised] ''[[Irish Times]]'', 12 August 2005.</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat of the coalition government in the [[2005 German federal election|2005 election]], Fischer announced that he would retire to the backbench. \"After 20 years of power, now I want my freedom back\", Fischer said.<ref>Yassin Musharbash, [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/fischers-bedingter-abschied-ich-will-die-freiheit-zurueck-a-375678.html \"Fischers bedingter Abschied: 'Ich will die Freiheit zur\u00fcck'\"], ''Spiegel Online'' 20 September 2005.</ref> On 13 October 2005, it was announced that [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] of the SPD would succeed Fischer as foreign minister.\n\n===Western Balkans policy===\nIn 1999, Fischer supported German military participation in the [[Kosovo War]]. This proved to be a highly controversial position since Fischer's plan not only clashed with the largely [[pacifism|pacifist]] philosophy of The Greens, but because it also supported for the first time since [[World War II]] active participation of German soldiers in combat. Fischer justified this military involvement with allegations that [[Serbia]] was planning to commit [[genocide]] against the Kosovo [[Albanians]].\n\nFischer represented the German government at the funeral services for [[Prime Minister of Serbia|Prime Minister]] [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]] of [[Serbia]] on 16 March 2003 (alongside Development Minister [[Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul]])<ref>Jos\u00e9 Comas (16 March 2003), [http://elpais.com/diario/2003/03/16/internacional/1047769221_850215.html Belgrado vive su mayor funeral desde Tito] ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''.</ref> and [[President of Macedonia|President]] [[Boris Trajkovski]] of [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] on 5 March 2004 in [[Skopje]].\n\n===Transatlantic relations===\n[[File:Fischer und Paul Wolfowitz.jpg|thumb|Fischer and [[Paul Wolfowitz]] at [[the Pentagon]] on 19 September 2001.]]\nOn fundamental issues like the [[International Criminal Court]], the [[Kyoto Protocol]], and the crisis in the Middle East, Fischer was openly differing with the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]].<ref>Steven Erlanger (21 July 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/21/weekinreview/the-world-america-the-invulnerable-the-world-looks-again.html The World; America the Invulnerable? The World Looks Again] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, both Fischer and Justice Minister [[Herta D\u00e4ubler-Gmelin]] appealed for [[clemency]] for the [[LaGrand case|LaGrand brothers]], two German citizens sentenced to death in [[Arizona]]. According to the German government, the LaGrands had been denied their rights as German citizens because prosecutors did not inform the German consulate of the brothers' arrest in 1982 until a decade later. However, both were put to death in a cloud of [[cyanide]] gas.<ref>Roger Cohen (5 March 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/05/us/us-execution-of-german-stirs-anger.html U.S. Execution of German Stirs Anger] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In response, the European Union submitted an anti-death-penalty resolution to the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>Elizabeth Olson (28 March 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/05/us/us-execution-of-german-stirs-anger.html U.S. Execution of German Stirs Anger] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nAlthough Fischer was in favour of stationing German troops in [[Afghanistan]], he advised chancellor Schr\u00f6der not to join the war in [[Iraq]]. Fischer famously confronted [[United States Defense Secretary]] [[Donald Rumsfeld]] at the 39th [[Munich Security Conference]] in 2003 on the secretary's purported evidence for Iraq's possession of [[weapons of mass destruction]] (''\"Excuse me, I am not convinced\"'').\n\n===Middle East policy===\nFischer has been criticized for attending a 1969 conference of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], where [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] leader [[Yasser Arafat]] called for an all-out war on [[Israel]] \"until the end\".<ref>Paul Berman, ''Power and the Idealists'' (NY: Soft Skull Press, 2005), pp. 9-10, and Chapter 1, ''passim''.</ref>\n\nDuring their time in government, both Fischer and Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der were widely considered sincerely, if not uncritically, pro-Israeli.<ref>Steven Erlanger (7 April 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/07/weekinreview/the-world-the-jewish-question-europe-knows-who-s-to-blame-in-the-middle-east.html The World: The Jewish Question; Europe Knows Who's to Blame in the Middle East] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In 1999, Fischer led a delegation including [[European Commissioner]] [[Manuel Mar\u00edn]] and the European Union\u2019s Special Envoy to the Middle East [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Moratinos]] on a visit to Jerusalem and the [[Palestinian territories]], but also to a range of other countries which have a crucial role in the peace process, including Lebanon, Syria, Jordan and Egypt.<ref>[http://www.politico.eu/article/eu-strives-to-keep-middle-east-peace-talks-alive/ EU strives to keep Middle East peace talks alive] ''[[European Voice]]'', 3 February 1999.</ref> By 2001, he emerged as a pivotal figure in the hopes for the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process]], in part because he helped bring about a lull in the violence after the [[Dolphinarium discotheque massacre]] in June 2001. His intervention led to an announced cease-fire arranged by [[George Tenet]], the [[Director of Central Intelligence|United States Director of Central Intelligence]]; Fischer had been in Tel Aviv at the time of the blast.<ref>Deborah Sontag (3 June 2001), [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/03/world/arafat-calls-for-cease-fire-deploring-tel-aviv-attack.html Arafat Calls for Cease-Fire, Deploring Tel Aviv Attack] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Fischer later brokered a meeting between Arafat and the Israeli foreign minister, [[Shimon Peres]], to discuss how to implement the cease-fire.<ref>[[Clyde Haberman]] (22 August 2001), [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/22/world/new-middle-east-peace-bid-brokered-by-german-envoy.html New Middle East Peace Bid Brokered by German Envoy] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, Fischer presented a proposal that calls for Arafat to appoint an interim prime minister. After the vote, the proposal said, elected officials could continue democratic reforms leading to a provisional Palestinian state by the end of 2003 and to final borders by 2005.<ref>[[Todd S. Purdum]] (12 July 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/12/world/bush-s-mideast-consultations-proceed-quietly.html Bush's Mideast Consultations Proceed, Quietly] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> He represented the German government at the funeral services for Arafat on 12 November 2004 in [[Cairo]] and at the inauguration of the new Holocaust Memorial Museum at [[Yad Vashem]] in March 2005.<ref>Steven Erlanger (16 March 2005), [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/16/world/middleeast/new-museum-putting-a-human-face-on-the-holocaust-opens-in.html New Museum, Putting a Human Face on the Holocaust, Opens in Israel] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n===European integration===\nIn a direct challenge to nation states in Europe, Fischer in May 2000 proposed the creation of a [[United States of Europe|European federation]] with a directly elected president and parliament sharing real executive and legislative powers. Fischer proposed the eventual enactment of a constitutional treaty that would set out which powers were to be shifted to the new European executive and parliament, and those that remained at national level.<ref>Roger Cohen (15 May 2000), [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/15/world/german-urges-europe-create-central-body-for-governing.html German Urges Europe Create Central Body For Governing] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In response, [[President of France|President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] of France urged Germany in June 2000 to join France in spearheading a core group of European Union countries that would move faster than others toward political and economic union.<ref>[[Suzanne Daley]] (28 June 2000), [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/28/world/french-leader-in-berlin-urges-a-fast-track-to-unity-in-europe.html French Leader, in Berlin, Urges A Fast Track to Unity in Europe] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn October 2002, Fischer was appointed by the German government to the [[Convention on the Future of Europe]], replacing [[Peter Glotz]]. Fischer had expressed a keen interest in taking part in the Convention during the coalition talks with Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der following the [[2002 German federal election|2002 elections]].<ref>Martin Banks (23 October 2002), [http://www.politico.eu/article/mixed-reaction-to-convention-role-for-fischer-2/ Mixed reaction to Convention role for Fischer] ''[[European Voice]]''.</ref> In a paper jointly signed by Fischer and his French counterpart, Foreign Minister [[Dominique de Villepin]], in November 2002, Germany and France pushed for a [[Defense pact|mutual defence commitment]] to be part of the constitution.<ref>Dana Spinant (12 March 2003), [http://www.politico.eu/article/does-eu-need-a-mutual-defence-pact/ Does EU need a mutual defence pact?] ''[[European Voice]]''.</ref> In 2004, he was one of the [[signatories to the Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]].\n\n====Relations with Russia====\nFischer has long been critical of Russia, especially on human rights.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14041654 Joschka Fischer v Gerhard Schr\u00f6der] ''[[The Economist]]''.</ref> However, during his time as foreign minister, Germany\u2019s relations with Russia were primarily guided by Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der. In 2004, Fischer called on Ukraine to hold a recount of the [[2004 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential elections]] after Putin-backed candidate [[Viktor Yanukovich]] was the first to declare his victory despite mass protests in Kyiv.<ref>Arkady Ostrovsky (24 November 2004), [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/597ac7d8-3dbe-11d9-abe0-00000e2511c8.html Vote's outcome seen as defining moment for Moscow] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Life after politics==\nFrom September 2006 until 2007, Fischer was a senior fellow at the [[Liechtenstein Institute on Self-Determination]], and as a visiting professor co-taught with [[Wolfgang F. Danspeckgruber]] at [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]], both at [[Princeton University]]. He has also spoken at other American universities on various topics in foreign affairs and international relations.\n\nIn addition, Fischer joined various non-governmental organizations, including:\n* [[Arab Democracy Foundation]], Founding Member of the Board of Trustees (since 2007)\n* [[Council on Foreign Relations]], Member<ref>Victor Homola (28 July 2006), [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/28/world/europe/28briefs-007.html Germany: Farewell to German Politics] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* [[European Council on Foreign Relations]] (ECFR), Founding Co-Chairman of the Board (alongside [[Martti Ahtisaari]] and [[Mabel van Oranje]])<ref>[http://www.ecfr.eu/about About Us] [[European Council on Foreign Relations]] (ECFR).</ref>\n* United Nations Association of Germany (DGVN), Member of the Presidium<ref>[http://www.dgvn.de/structure-of-una-germany/presidium/ Presidium] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918015652/http://www.dgvn.de/structure-of-una-germany/presidium/ |date=18 September 2016 }} United Nations Association of Germany (DGVN).</ref>\n* [[Meridiam]], Member of the Supervisory Board (since 2012)<ref>[http://www.meridiam.com/en/team Supervisory Board] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601174003/http://www.meridiam.com/en/team |date=1 June 2016 }} [[Meridiam]].</ref>\n* [[Institut f\u00fcr die Wissenschaften vom Menschen|Institute for Human Sciences]] (IWM), Member of the Board of Patrons<ref>[http://www.iwm.at/the-institute/boards/ Board of Patrons]</ref>\n* [[Roland Berger|Roland Berger Human Dignity Award]], Member of the Awards Committee<ref>[http://m.rolandbergerstiftung.org/en/the-foundation/the-committees/?tx_lombperson_pi2%5Bgremium%5D=3&tx_lombperson_pi2%5Baction%5D=detail&tx_lombperson_pi2%5Bcontroller%5D=Committee&cHash=b471bf28758cc4f8d667a13dfb11ef27 Member of the Awards Committee] Roland Berger Foundation.</ref>\n\nSince 2008, Fischer has been Senior Strategic Counsel at [[Albright Stonebridge Group]], Washington, DC, consulting firm led by [[Madeleine Albright]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thealbrightgroupllc.com/Who_We_Are.htm |title=Albright Group |accessdate=27 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.thealbrightgroupllc.com/Who_We_Are.htm |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In this capacity, has in the past been advising [[Siemens]], [[BMW]] and [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse]].<ref>[https://www.handelsblatt.com/unternehmen/management/vom-gruenen-zum-berater-fuer-diese-firmen-arbeitet-joschka-fischer/3901594.html F\u00fcr diese Firmen arbeitet Joschka Fischer] ''[[Handelsblatt]]'', 4 March 2011.</ref><ref>[http://boerse.ard.de/aktien/deutsche-boerse-kaempft-weiter100.html Deutsche B\u00f6rse k\u00e4mpft weiter] ''[[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]]'', 23 December 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Fischer took a post as adviser to the [[Nabucco pipeline]] project, in which the German RWE company is also involved. According to media reports, the \"six-digit salary\" consultancy contract has already been signed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wsws.org/articles/2009/jul2009/fisc-j03.shtml |author=Ulrich Rippert |title=Joschka Fischer takes post as Nabucco pipeline adviser |publisher=[[World Socialist Web Site]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.wsws.org/articles/2009/jul2009/fisc-j03.shtml |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 September 2010 Fischer supported the new initiative [[Spinelli Group]], which was founded to reinvigorate efforts towards federalisation of the European Union (EU). Other prominent supporters are: [[Jacques Delors]], [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Andrew Duff]], [[Elmar Brok]].\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2002 \u2013 Honorary doctorate of the [[University of Haifa]]\n* 2003 \u2013 [[Buber-Rosenzweig-Medal|Buber Rosenzweig Medal]] (awarded by [[Paul Spiegel]])\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Gottlieb Duttweiler Institute|Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize]] (awarded by [[Micheline Calmy-Rey]] and [[Jean-Claude Juncker]])<ref>Jacob Greber (4 May 2004), [http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/joschka-fischer-wins-gottlieb-duttweiler-prize/3887864 Joschka Fischer wins Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize] ''Swissinfo''.</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 Honorary doctorate of [[Tel Aviv University]]\n* 2009 \u2013 [[Leo-Baeck-Medal|Leo Baeck Medal]] (awarded by [[James Wolfensohn]] and [[Henry Kissinger]])\n* 2012 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[University of Michigan]]<ref>[http://www.ur.umich.edu/update/archives/121015/honorary Six to receive honorary degrees at Winter Commencement] ''University of Michigan''.</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 Medal for Extraordinary Merits for Bavaria in a United Europe\n\n==Personal life==\nPrior to the [[German Visa Affair 2005]], Fischer was a popular politician, \"loved by an entire nation.\" Writing in ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', journalist Charles Hawley opined that since 1998, \"Joschka Fischer's popularity has been virtually unassailable: The icon of the environmentally minded Green Party could, it seemed, do no wrong. Indeed, Fischer was so popular in 2002 that Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder largely based his early election campaign on the fact that Fischer would remain at his side at the helm of Germany's political leadership.\"<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">\"[http://www.spiegel.de/international/political-scandal-joschka-fischer-with-his-back-against-the-wall-a-343108.html Political Scandal: Joschka Fischer with His Back Against the Wall]\" ''Der Spiegel'', 22 February 2005</ref> As Germany\u2019s Foreign Minister, Fischer\u2019s popularity soared when he opposed the [[Iraq War]], and his very public struggle with his weight endeared him to many Germans.\n[[File:Joska fischer wappen.png|thumb]]\n\nUp until 1996, Fischer was a [[bon vivant]], and often spoke openly about his love for good wines and food despite his \"chunky\" figure.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/> As he ascended to the Foreign Ministry, Fischer decided to lose weight, transforming his body almost overnight by refraining from alcohol and becoming a vegetarian. In 2000, he covered the topic of his weight loss by writing the book ''My Long Race Towards Myself'' on his experience, which became an immediate [[bestseller]] in Germany.\nHalf a year before becoming foreign minister, he had his marathon debut at the 1998 [[Hamburg Marathon]] (clocking 3:41)<ref>{{cite web |author=Herbert Seffrey |url=http://www.herbertsteffny.de/percoach.htm |title=Personal Trainer |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.herbertsteffny.de/percoach.htm |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> As minister, he finished [[New York City Marathon|New York]] in 1999 (3:55)<ref>{{cite news |author=Gisela Oswald |title=New York Marathon: Fischer im Ziel |trans-title=New York Marathon: Fisher in target |work=Spiegel Online |url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/new-york-marathon-fischer-im-ziel-a-51392.html |date=11 August 1999 |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/new-york-marathon-fischer-im-ziel-a-51392.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Berlin Marathon|Berlin]] in 2000 (3:55)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/joschka-fischer-auf-rang-8919-1.1539566 |title=Joschka Fischer auf Rang 8.919 |language=de |publisher=RP Online |date=9 October 2000 |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.rp-online.de/sport/joschka-fischer-auf-rang-8919-aid-1.1539566 |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAfterwards, he reduced training and during the months preceding the [[Iraq War]], Fischer began putting on weight again.\n\nFischer was married to [[Germans|German]]-[[Iran]]ian film producer and screenwriter [[:de:Minu Barati|Minu Barati]] in 2005. It is his fifth marriage. His two children with his previous partner and eventual wife, Inge Vogel (to whom he was married from 1984-1987), were born in 1979 and 1983, respectively. At the time of his wedding with Barati in 2005, she was mother to a six-year-old daughter from a previous relationship, while Fischer's children were 23 and 26 of age at the time. The couple lives with Barati's daughter.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Print.aspx?storyid=125719 |title=Fischer marries for fifth time |newspaper=[[Gulf Daily News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Print.aspx?storyid=125719 |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he commissioned German heraldist [[Dieter Krieger]] to produce a [[coat of arms]], which was registered to the Rhein-Main [[Roll of arms|Wappenrolle]] ( <nowiki>http://RMWR.dieter-krieger.de</nowiki> ). The arms are a type of a \"[[Canting arms]]\"; [[Division of the field#Common divisions of the field|party per fesse]] silver and gules, in chief crossed axes with red blades and black handles, in base, a fish in the first. [[Crest (heraldry)|Crest]] of the red eagle's wings, [[mantling]] red doubled silver.<ref>{{cite news |author=Franziska v. Mutius |url=https://www.welt.de/print-welt/article330518/Joschka_Fischer_setzt_auf_Tradition_und_kauft_ein_Familienwappen.html |title=Joschka Fischer setzt auf Tradition und kauft ein Familienwappen |newspaper=[[Die Welt]] |date=27 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.welt.de/print-welt/article330518/Joschka_Fischer_setzt_auf_Tradition_und_kauft_ein_Familienwappen.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.schloss-alsbach.org/rolle1.htm ''Bundesau\u00dfenminister a. D. Joschka Fischer erh\u00e4lt Wappenbrief der Rhein-Main-Wappenrolle''] (with Picture) on Website of [[Schloss Alsbach|Schlosses Alsbach]]</ref>\n\nHe describes himself as Catholic, but not very religious.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dennis Kremer|url=https://www.welt.de/fernsehen/article1246648/Joschka-Fischer-und-die-sieben-Todsuenden.html|title=Joschka Fischer und die sieben Tods\u00fcnden|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=10 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Paul Berman: ''Idealisten an der Macht. Die Passion des Joschka Fischer.'' Siedler, M\u00fcnchen 2006, {{ISBN|3-88680-846-7}}.\n* J\u00fcrgen Schreiber: ''Meine Jahre mit Joschka. Nachrichten von fetten und mageren Zeiten.'' Econ, Berlin 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-430-30033-9}}.\n* Christian Y. Schmidt: ''Wir sind die Wahnsinnigen. Joschka Fischer und seine Frankfurter Gang.'' Verbrecher Verlag, Berlin 2013.\n* Interviews\n* [[Gero von Boehm]]: ''Joschka Fischer. 31. August 2010''. Interview in: ''Begegnungen. Menschenbilder aus drei Jahrzehnten''. Collection Rolf Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2012, {{ISBN|978-3-89910-443-1}}, S. 678\u2013692\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Joschka Fischer|Joschka Fischer}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Britannica|208420}}\n*{{HessBib PPN|116465336}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130122073751/http://bostonreview.net/BR29.3/hockenos.html Boston Review article reviewing Fischer's biography]\n*[http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/biografien/FischerJoschka/index.html Biography at the German Historic Museum] {{in lang|de}}\n*[http://www.dhm.de/ausstellungen/spuren_der_macht/fischer_index.htm Photographs of Joschka Fischer 1991 - 1998 at the German Historic Museum] {{in lang|de}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721193118/http://citron-vert.info/article.php3?id_article=669 Joschka Fischer, la retraite ou pas ?] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721193220/http://citron-vert.info/article.php3?id_article=674 Joscka Fischer : les discours d\u2019un Vert aux affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://archive.is/20080119011546/http://prok.princeton.edu/2-1/interview Interview with Joschka Fischer] After moving to Princeton University, Fischer gives an in-depth interview about security and globalization for [[Princeton Report on Knowledge]].\n*[http://www.project-syndicate.org/columnist/joschka-fischer Joschka Fischer's monthly syndicated commentary series, \"The Rebel Realist\", from Project Syndicate]\n\nThe following sources reflect the views of U.S. adversaries of Fischer and his policies, especially Germany's decision not to participate in the 2003 U.S.-led invasion of Iraq.\n*[http://slate.com/id/2078560 ''Why Germany Isn't Convinced]'' by [[Paul Berman]] in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''\n*''Power and the Idealists : Or, The Passion of Joschka Fischer, and Its Aftermath'' by Paul Berman. {{ISBN|1-932360-91-3}} (Originally appeared as a 25,000 word essay in ''[[The New Republic]]'', 3 September 2001)\n*[http://www.signandsight.com/features/380.html ''The last rock 'n' roller of German politics''] In an interview with the taz given in September 2005, Fischer reflects on what his coming retirement means for his party, his country and himself. At signandsight.com\n\nJoschka Fischer writes a monthly commentary series, \"The Rebel Realist\", for Project Syndicate, a non-profit association of newspapers around the world.\n*[http://www.project-syndicate.org/series/38/description The Rebel Realist]\n\nJoschka Fisher speaks to Leadel.NET, an online Jewish media portal, in a video interview\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081202114943/http://leadel.net/]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Klaus Kinkel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice-Chancellor of Germany|Vice Chancellor of Germany]]|years=1998\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Franz M\u00fcntefering]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]|years=1998\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker at the [[College of Europe]] Opening Ceremony|years=2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{BRDFMs}}\n{{GermanViceChancellors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fischer, Joschka}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Alliance 90/The Greens politicians]]\n[[Category:Foreign Ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:German Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Hesse]]\n[[Category:People from Gerabronn]]\n[[Category:People of Hungarian German descent]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Hesse]]\n[[Category:21st-century German politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag 2005\u20132009]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Joschka Fischer\n|image          = Joschka Fischer 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|caption        = Fischer on 14 September 2014\n\n|office         = [[Vice Chancellor of Germany]]\n|chancellor     = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n|term_start     = 27 October 1998\n|term_end       = 22 November 2005\n|predecessor    = [[Klaus Kinkel]]\n|successor      = [[Franz M\u00fcntefering]]\n\n|office1        = [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|Federal Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n|chancellor1    = [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]]\n|term_start1    = 27 October 1998\n|term_end1      = 22 November 2005\n|predecessor1   = [[Klaus Kinkel]]\n|successor1     = [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]\n\n|office3        = [[Politics of Hesse|Minister of the Environment and Energy of Hesse]]\n|primeminister3 = [[Holger B\u00f6rner]]\n|term_start3    = 12 December 1985\n|term_end3      = 9 February 1987\n|predecessor3   = Position established\n|successor3     = [[Armin Clauss]] {{small|(Acting)}}\n|primeminister4 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start4    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end4      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor4   = [[Karlheinz Weimar]]\n|successor4     = [[Rupert von Plottnitz]]\n\n|office2        = [[Politics of Hesse|Deputy Minister President of Hesse]]\n|primeminister2 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start2    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end2      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor2   = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]]\n|successor2     = [[Rupert von Plottnitz]]\n\n|office5        = [[Politics of Hesse|Minister of Federal Affairs of Hesse]]\n|primeminister5 = [[Hans Eichel]]\n|term_start5    = 5 April 1991\n|term_end5      = 5 October 1994\n|predecessor5   = [[Wolfgang Gerhardt]] {{small|(Agent of Federal Affairs)}}\n|successor5     = [[Rupert von Plottnitz]]\n|birthname      = Joseph Martin Fischer\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1948|4|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Gerabronn]], [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden]], [[Allied-occupied Germany]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Alliance '90/The Greens]]\n|spouse       = Edeltraud Fischer {{small|(1967\u20131984)}}<br />Inge Peusquens {{small|(1984\u20131987)}}<br />Claudia Bohm {{small|(1987\u20131998)}}<br />Nicola Leske {{small|(1999\u20132003)}}<br />Minu Barati-Fischer {{small|(m 2005)}}\n|children     = David<br />Lara\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Martin \"Joschka\" Fischer''' (born 12 April 1948) is a [[Germany|German]] politician of the [[Alliance '90/The Greens]]. He served as [[Foreign Minister of Germany|Foreign Minister]] and as [[Vice Chancellor of Germany]] in the cabinet of [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] from 1998 to 2005. Fischer has been a leading figure in the German Greens since the 1970s, and according to opinion polls,<ref>{{cite web |title=Weiterhin gro\u00dfe Unzufriedenheit mit den Spitzenpolitikern |date=4 July 2003 |url=http://tsarchive.wordpress.com/2003/07/04/meldung330600/ |language=de |accessdate=24 April 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://tsarchive.wordpress.com/2003/07/04/meldung330600/ |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> he was the most popular politician in Germany for most of the government's duration. Following the [[2005 German federal election|September 2005 election]], in which the Schr\u00f6der government was defeated, he left office on 22 November 2005. In September 2010 he supported the creation of the [[Spinelli Group]], a europarliamentarian initiative founded with a view to reinvigorate efforts to federalise the European Union.\n\n==Early life==\nFischer was born in [[Gerabronn]] in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], the third child of a butcher, whose family had lived in [[Budakeszi]], [[Hungary]], for several generations. Fischer's family had to leave Hungary in 1946 after it was occupied by the [[Soviet Union]], and [[Germans of Hungary|ethnic Germans]] were persecuted and expelled by the authorities. His nickname ''Joschka'' is derived from the Hungarian ''J\u00f3ska'', diminutive of Joseph (Hungarian ''J\u00f3zsef''). He was brought up Catholic and served in his childhood as an altar boy in his parish in [[Oeffingen]].<ref>{{cite news|author=M. Drobinski |url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/leben/prominente-ministranten-vor-dem-altar-gestaehlt-fuers-leben-1.985487|title=Vor dem Altar gest\u00e4hlt f\u00fcrs Leben }}</ref> Fischer dropped out of high school in 1965, and started an apprenticeship as a photographer, which he quit in 1966. Because Fischer never gained a school-leaving certificate, he never attended a university or a college. He neither did compulsory military service nor the alternative civilian service for conscientious objectors, because he failed his physical examination due to poor eyesight.<ref>{{cite news|author=Christoph Schult |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0,1518,128137,00.html |title=Zivildienst: Hat sich Joschka Fischer gedr\u00fcckt? |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0%2C1518%2C128137%2C00.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Left-wing militant==\nIn 1967, he became active in the [[German student movement]] and [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] movement (post-) 1968 (the so-called ''Spontis''), first in [[Stuttgart]] and after 1968 in [[Frankfurt am Main]]. For his regular income, Fischer took several low-wage jobs, such as working in a left-wing bookstore in Frankfurt. During this period, he began attending university events, including lectures organized by left-wing revolutionary students by [[Theodor W. Adorno]], [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]] and [[Oskar Negt]].<ref>Paul Hockenhos, ''Joschka Fischer and the Making of the Berlin Republic,'' Oxford University Press, 2007, p 86</ref> He studied the works of [[Karl Marx|Marx]], [[Mao Zedong|Mao]] and [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]] and became a member of the militant group, ''Revolution\u00e4rer Kampf'' (Revolutionary Struggle). Fischer was a leader in several street battles involving the radical ''[[Putzgruppe]]'' (literally \"cleaning squad\", with the first syllable being an [[acronym]] for ''Proletarische Union f\u00fcr Terror und Zerst\u00f6rung'', \"Proletarian Union for Terror and Destruction\"), which attacked a number of police officers. Photos of one such brawl in March 1973, which were later to haunt Fischer, show him clubbing policeman Rainer Marx,<ref name=NYT_Firebrand>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Roger|title=Germany's Foreign Minister Is Pursued by His Early Firebrand Self|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C00EEDD123DF936A25752C0A9679C8B63|date=15 January 2001|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=24 April 2008}}</ref> to whom he later publicly apologized.\n\nFischer is a close friend of [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], whom he met during that time. In 1971, he began working for the car manufacturer [[Opel]] and attempted to organise his fellow workers for the coming communist revolution. (This was not organising on behalf of a regular labour union: the vast majority of Opel's workers had already been organised for decades by [[IG Metall]], the German metalworkers' union.) This resulted in his dismissal from the company after six months. Fischer then continued making a living with unskilled work while continuing his activism. He worked as a taxi driver from 1976 to 1981 and later in a bookstore in Frankfurt.\n\nIn the ''Deutscher Herbst'' ([[German autumn]]) of 1977, Germany was rattled by a series of left-wing [[terrorism|terrorist]] attacks by the [[Red Army Faction]] (RAF) and [[Revolutionary Cells (RZ)]]. According to Fischer's own account, witnessing these events, particularly the kidnapping and murder of [[Hanns-Martin Schleyer]] and the [[Operation Entebbe|Entebbe hijacking]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/27/books/review/27hari.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1|newspaper=The New York Times|title=The Red and the Green|first=Johann|last=Hari|date=27 November 2005|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Michael |date=14 February 200 |url=http://www.postwritersgroup.com/archives/kell0211.htm |title=Who is Joschka Fischer? |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525141300/http://www.postwritersgroup.com/archives/kell0211.htm |archivedate=25 May 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> made him renounce violence as a means for political change. Instead, he became involved in the [[new social movements]] and later in the newly founded [[Alliance '90/The Greens|Green Party]], mainly in the state of [[Hesse]]. Nevertheless, in 1978 he said he did not mourn the killings of Schleyer, [[Siegfried Buback]] and [[J\u00fcrgen Ponto]] by the RAF.<ref>Jochen B\u00f6lsche: [http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-18370244.html ''Die verlorene Ehre der Apo.''] in: ''[[Der Spiegel]].'' No. 5, 29. January 2001.</ref>\n\nIn May 1981, the Hessian Secretary of Commerce [[Heinz-Herbert Karry]] was murdered with a firearm that in 1973 had been transported in Fischer's car, along with other weapons stolen from an American army base.<ref>{{cite news |last=Karacs |first=Imre |date=3 August 1998 |title=Kohl turns his fire on the Greens |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/kohl-turns-his-fire-on-the-greens-1169537.html |accessdate=July 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525141300/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/kohl-turns-his-fire-on-the-greens-1169537.html |archivedate=25 May 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Fischer maintained he had given the car to the later terrorist [[Hans-Joachim Klein]] solely for the purpose of having Klein fit it with a new engine. Only later had Fischer learned that his car had been used to transport stolen weapons.{{citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nAs Foreign Minister, Fischer apologised for the violence of his ''Putzgruppe'' days, without disassociating himself from the radical movement. Some critics continue to charge that Fischer was the leading figure of a 1976 discussion that led to the use of [[Molotov cocktail]]s in an upcoming demonstration in support of RAF member [[Ulrike Meinhof]]. Fischer was arrested on 14 May 1976 as a suspect in the Molotov cocktail attacks on police, but was released after two days. Fischer stated that he never used Molotov cocktails against the police. The firebombing of policeman [[J\u00fcrgen Weber]]'s police car left Weber with burns over 60% of his body.<ref name=NYT_Firebrand/>\n\n==Green politician==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F065084-0014, Bonn, Pressekonferenz der Gr\u00fcnen, Bundestagswahl.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Joschka Fischer on 17 February 1983]]\n\nFrom 1983 to 1985, Fischer was a member of the [[Bundestag]] for the Green party. His stint in federal parliament saw him frequently engage in a frank and confrontational debating style, exemplified by an incident on 18 October 1984, when he addressed [[Richard St\u00fccklen]], then vice president of the parliament, with the words: \"If I may say so, Mr. President, you are an asshole\" (German: \"Mit Verlaub, Herr Pr\u00e4sident, Sie sind ein Arschloch.\"). In 1985, Fischer became Minister for the Environment in the [[Landtag of Hesse]] in the first governmental [[Red-green alliance|Red-Green coalition]] between the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) and the Greens. Fischer caused a stir when he appeared at his oath of office ceremony wearing [[Athletic shoe|trainers]]. These sneakers are now part of the shoe collection at the [[German Leather Museum|German Leather and Shoe Museum]] in [[Offenbach, Hesse]].\n\nFischer also expressed his thoughts very frankly in the periodical of the Hessian Green party \"Stichwort Gr\u00fcn\". In an interview with ''[[Bunte]]'' magazine published on 27 July 1989, he rejected [[German reunification]] and demanded that the [[reunification clause]] be deleted from the preamble to the [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany]]. Even after the growth of the wave of the refugees from [[East Germany]], Fischer on 20 September 1989 demanded that the Federal Republic renounce reunification. In a column for ''[[Die Tageszeitung]]'' published on 17 November 1989, eight days after the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], he predicted that reunification would not happen. On 1 October 1990, Fischer said he refused to celebrate reunification.<ref name=kas>{{cite web|title=Schlaglichter der deutschen Einheit. Eine kommentierte Chronik(1987-1990)|url=https://www.kas.de/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=b766e451-ebe2-cbd4-72f0-a1824f960320&groupId=252038|website=kas.de|publisher=[[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]]|author=Michael Borchard|pages=17, 20, 22, 23, 28, 48|date=1 October 2008|language=de}}</ref>\n\nFischer was again environment minister in Hessen from 1991 to 1994 and then became co-chairman of the Greens' parliamentary faction in the Bundestag. Fischer was respected for his oratory skills, as well as for his charisma on the political stage. For a large part of the 1990s, with the social democrats languishing in the opinion polls, Fischer's admirers referred to him as the \"real\" leader of the opposition.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} He parlayed his clout into political success, as he moved the Greens to the centre ground of German politics, paving the way for their first participation in the nation's federal government.\n\n==Foreign Minister==\n[[File:Vladimir Putin 13 February 2001-2.jpg|thumb|Fischer with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] on 13 February 2001]]\n\nIn September 1998, the Social Democratic Party of Germany, led by Gerhard Schr\u00f6der, defeated the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] government of [[Helmut Kohl]]. The SPD's 41% and the Greens' 7% of the vote set the two parties on a possible path to government through a coalition. Schr\u00f6der stated his preference for a red-green coalition, as did an overwhelming majority of SPD members.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} After several weeks of negotiations, a SPD-Green government took power on 27 October 1998, with Fischer appointed as Minister of Foreign Affairs. By 2005, he was the second longest-serving foreign minister in German postwar history (after [[Hans-Dietrich Genscher]]).\n\nIn mid-April 1999, Germany came up with the first peace plan, when Fischer produced a proposal, notably including Russia, that would have rewarded the beginning of a Yugoslav pullout from Kosovo with a bombing pause.<ref>Warren Hodge (4 June 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/04/world/crisis-balkans-memo-continent-europeans-impressed-their-own-unity.html Europeans Impressed By Their Own Unity] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In May 1999, however, an antiwar protester flung a bag of red paint at Fischer during a party convention debating [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|NATO\u2019s airstrikes on Yugoslavia]] in the war over Kosovo; Fischer suffered a perforated eardrum.<ref>Tony Czuczka (23 September 2010), [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-09-23/green-party-s-trittin-hit-in-yoghurt-attack-at-hanover-anti-nuclear-event German Greens\u2019 Trittin Hit in Yoghurt Attack, Police Says] ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.</ref>\n\nIn an effort to make it easier for antiwar critics to back Schr\u00f6der\u2019s decision to send German [[Bundeswehr]] troops to [[Afghanistan]] in 2001, Fischer and Development Minister [[Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul]] announced a 256 million marks ($115 million) humanitarian-aid package for Afghan refugees.<ref>William Boston (15 November 2001), [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1005774857206960440 Germany's Schroeder Presses Coalition To Back Him With Vote of Confidence] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.</ref> In late 2001, Fischer hosted \u2013 under the auspices of the [[United Nations]] \u2013 a ten-day conference at the German [[Hotel Petersberg|government guesthouse]] above the Rhine River, where delegates from four Afghan factions signed the [[Bonn Agreement (Afghanistan)|Bonn Agreement]] establishing a transitional government for the country to replace the deposed [[Taliban]] regime.<ref>Peter Finn (28 November 2001), [http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2001-11-28/news/0111280283_1_northern-alliance-pashtun-delegates Afghan Delegates At U.N. Talks In Germany Urge Tolerance] ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''.</ref> At the time, Germany's longstanding links to Afghanistan and its 2001 chairmanship of the Afghanistan Support Group of countries pledging humanitarian and reconstruction aid for the country, were the reasons it was picked to host the meeting.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/a/a-13-a-2001-11-22-14-afghan-66423982/550167.html Afghan Conference Switched to Bonn for Security Concerns] ''[[Voice of America]]'', 22 November 2001.</ref>\n\nIn September 2001, Fischer summoned Ahmad Azizi, the Iranian ambassador to Germany, for urgent talks after several reformist intellectuals \u2013 including [[Akbar Ganji]], [[Mehrangiz Kar]] and [[Ezzatollah Sahabi]] \u2013 were given prison sentences of between four and 10 years for participating in a [['Iran After the Elections' Conference|2000 academic and cultural conference]] sponsored by the [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation]] in [[Berlin]] in late 2000.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1116536.stm Germany's 'concern' at Iran verdicts] ''[[BBC News]]'', 14 January 2001.</ref>\n\nIn 2005, critics charged that Fischer's relaxing of controls on visa regulations for [[Ukraine]], would allow illegal immigrants to enter [[Germany]] with fake identities.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/64507/ |title=Germany's Fischer preps Kyiv students for future |newspaper=[[Kyiv Post]] |date=21 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100422232033/http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/64507/ |archivedate=22 April 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> A parliamentary committee was established to examine the case, and unlike in other such committee hearings, Fischer's statement (and that of other top officials) was shown live on public television. Fischer's appearance before the committee lasted twelve hours. (See [[German Visa Affair 2005]]).\n\nFischer represented the German government at the funeral services for [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Foreign Minister]] [[Anna Lindh]] of [[Sweden]] on 19 September 2003 in [[Stockholm]]; [[Pope]] [[List of dignitaries at the funeral of Pope John Paul II|John Paul II]] on 8 April 2005 in [[Rome]]; and former [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|UK Foreign Secretary]] [[Robin Cook]] on 12 August 2005 in [[Edinburgh]].<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/cook-funeral-hears-blair-s-moral-failure-criticised-1.1181252 Cook funeral hears Blair's 'moral failure' criticised] ''[[Irish Times]]'', 12 August 2005.</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat of the coalition government in the [[2005 German federal election|2005 election]], Fischer announced that he would retire to the backbench. \"After 20 years of power, now I want my freedom back\", Fischer said.<ref>Yassin Musharbash, [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/fischers-bedingter-abschied-ich-will-die-freiheit-zurueck-a-375678.html \"Fischers bedingter Abschied: 'Ich will die Freiheit zur\u00fcck'\"], ''Spiegel Online'' 20 September 2005.</ref> On 13 October 2005, it was announced that [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] of the SPD would succeed Fischer as foreign minister.\n\n===Western Balkans policy===\nIn 1999, Fischer supported German military participation in the [[Kosovo War]]. This proved to be a highly controversial position since Fischer's plan not only clashed with the largely [[pacifism|pacifist]] philosophy of The Greens, but because it also supported for the first time since [[World War II]] active participation of German soldiers in combat. Fischer justified this military involvement with allegations that [[Serbia]] was planning to commit [[genocide]] against the Kosovo [[Albanians]].\n\nFischer represented the German government at the funeral services for [[Prime Minister of Serbia|Prime Minister]] [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]] of [[Serbia]] on 16 March 2003 (alongside Development Minister [[Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul]])<ref>Jos\u00e9 Comas (16 March 2003), [http://elpais.com/diario/2003/03/16/internacional/1047769221_850215.html Belgrado vive su mayor funeral desde Tito] ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''.</ref> and [[President of Macedonia|President]] [[Boris Trajkovski]] of [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] on 5 March 2004 in [[Skopje]].\n\n===Transatlantic relations===\n[[File:Fischer und Paul Wolfowitz.jpg|thumb|Fischer and [[Paul Wolfowitz]] at [[the Pentagon]] on 19 September 2001.]]\nOn fundamental issues like the [[International Criminal Court]], the [[Kyoto Protocol]], and the crisis in the Middle East, Fischer was openly differing with the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]].<ref>Steven Erlanger (21 July 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/21/weekinreview/the-world-america-the-invulnerable-the-world-looks-again.html The World; America the Invulnerable? The World Looks Again] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 1999, both Fischer and Justice Minister [[Herta D\u00e4ubler-Gmelin]] appealed for [[clemency]] for the [[LaGrand case|LaGrand brothers]], two German citizens sentenced to death in [[Arizona]]. According to the German government, the LaGrands had been denied their rights as German citizens because prosecutors did not inform the German consulate of the brothers' arrest in 1982 until a decade later. However, both were put to death in a cloud of [[cyanide]] gas.<ref>Roger Cohen (5 March 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/05/us/us-execution-of-german-stirs-anger.html U.S. Execution of German Stirs Anger] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In response, the European Union submitted an anti-death-penalty resolution to the [[United Nations Commission on Human Rights]].<ref>Elizabeth Olson (28 March 1999), [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/05/us/us-execution-of-german-stirs-anger.html U.S. Execution of German Stirs Anger] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nAlthough Fischer was in favour of stationing German troops in [[Afghanistan]], he advised chancellor Schr\u00f6der not to join the war in [[Iraq]]. Fischer famously confronted [[United States Defense Secretary]] [[Donald Rumsfeld]] at the 39th [[Munich Security Conference]] in 2003 on the secretary's purported evidence for Iraq's possession of [[weapons of mass destruction]] (''\"Excuse me, I am not convinced\"'').\n\n===Middle East policy===\nFischer has been criticized for attending a 1969 conference of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], where [[Palestinians|Palestinian]] leader [[Yasser Arafat]] called for an all-out war on [[Israel]] \"until the end\".<ref>Paul Berman, ''Power and the Idealists'' (NY: Soft Skull Press, 2005), pp. 9-10, and Chapter 1, ''passim''.</ref>\n\nDuring their time in government, both Fischer and Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der were widely considered sincerely, if not uncritically, pro-Israeli.<ref>Steven Erlanger (7 April 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/07/weekinreview/the-world-the-jewish-question-europe-knows-who-s-to-blame-in-the-middle-east.html The World: The Jewish Question; Europe Knows Who's to Blame in the Middle East] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In 1999, Fischer led a delegation including [[European Commissioner]] [[Manuel Mar\u00edn]] and the European Union\u2019s Special Envoy to the Middle East [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Moratinos]] on a visit to Jerusalem and the [[Palestinian territories]], but also to a range of other countries which have a crucial role in the peace process, including Lebanon, Syria, Jordan and Egypt.<ref>[http://www.politico.eu/article/eu-strives-to-keep-middle-east-peace-talks-alive/ EU strives to keep Middle East peace talks alive] ''[[European Voice]]'', 3 February 1999.</ref> By 2001, he emerged as a pivotal figure in the hopes for the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process]], in part because he helped bring about a lull in the violence after the [[Dolphinarium discotheque massacre]] in June 2001. His intervention led to an announced cease-fire arranged by [[George Tenet]], the [[Director of Central Intelligence|United States Director of Central Intelligence]]; Fischer had been in Tel Aviv at the time of the blast.<ref>Deborah Sontag (3 June 2001), [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/03/world/arafat-calls-for-cease-fire-deploring-tel-aviv-attack.html Arafat Calls for Cease-Fire, Deploring Tel Aviv Attack] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> Fischer later brokered a meeting between Arafat and the Israeli foreign minister, [[Shimon Peres]], to discuss how to implement the cease-fire.<ref>[[Clyde Haberman]] (22 August 2001), [https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/22/world/new-middle-east-peace-bid-brokered-by-german-envoy.html New Middle East Peace Bid Brokered by German Envoy] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, Fischer presented a proposal that calls for Arafat to appoint an interim prime minister. After the vote, the proposal said, elected officials could continue democratic reforms leading to a provisional Palestinian state by the end of 2003 and to final borders by 2005.<ref>[[Todd S. Purdum]] (12 July 2002), [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/12/world/bush-s-mideast-consultations-proceed-quietly.html Bush's Mideast Consultations Proceed, Quietly] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> He represented the German government at the funeral services for Arafat on 12 November 2004 in [[Cairo]] and at the inauguration of the new Holocaust Memorial Museum at [[Yad Vashem]] in March 2005.<ref>Steven Erlanger (16 March 2005), [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/16/world/middleeast/new-museum-putting-a-human-face-on-the-holocaust-opens-in.html New Museum, Putting a Human Face on the Holocaust, Opens in Israel] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n===European integration===\nIn a direct challenge to nation states in Europe, Fischer in May 2000 proposed the creation of a [[United States of Europe|European federation]] with a directly elected president and parliament sharing real executive and legislative powers. Fischer proposed the eventual enactment of a constitutional treaty that would set out which powers were to be shifted to the new European executive and parliament, and those that remained at national level.<ref>Roger Cohen (15 May 2000), [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/15/world/german-urges-europe-create-central-body-for-governing.html German Urges Europe Create Central Body For Governing] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref> In response, [[President of France|President]] [[Jacques Chirac]] of France urged Germany in June 2000 to join France in spearheading a core group of European Union countries that would move faster than others toward political and economic union.<ref>[[Suzanne Daley]] (28 June 2000), [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/28/world/french-leader-in-berlin-urges-a-fast-track-to-unity-in-europe.html French Leader, in Berlin, Urges A Fast Track to Unity in Europe] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\nIn October 2002, Fischer was appointed by the German government to the [[Convention on the Future of Europe]], replacing [[Peter Glotz]]. Fischer had expressed a keen interest in taking part in the Convention during the coalition talks with Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der following the [[2002 German federal election|2002 elections]].<ref>Martin Banks (23 October 2002), [http://www.politico.eu/article/mixed-reaction-to-convention-role-for-fischer-2/ Mixed reaction to Convention role for Fischer] ''[[European Voice]]''.</ref> In a paper jointly signed by Fischer and his French counterpart, Foreign Minister [[Dominique de Villepin]], in November 2002, Germany and France pushed for a [[Defense pact|mutual defence commitment]] to be part of the constitution.<ref>Dana Spinant (12 March 2003), [http://www.politico.eu/article/does-eu-need-a-mutual-defence-pact/ Does EU need a mutual defence pact?] ''[[European Voice]]''.</ref> In 2004, he was one of the [[signatories to the Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe]].\n\n====Relations with Russia====\nFischer has long been critical of Russia, especially on human rights.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14041654 Joschka Fischer v Gerhard Schr\u00f6der] ''[[The Economist]]''.</ref> However, during his time as foreign minister, Germany\u2019s relations with Russia were primarily guided by Chancellor Gerhard Schr\u00f6der. In 2004, Fischer called on Ukraine to hold a recount of the [[2004 Ukrainian presidential election|presidential elections]] after Putin-backed candidate [[Viktor Yanukovich]] was the first to declare his victory despite mass protests in Kyiv.<ref>Arkady Ostrovsky (24 November 2004), [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/597ac7d8-3dbe-11d9-abe0-00000e2511c8.html Vote's outcome seen as defining moment for Moscow] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref>\n\n==Life after politics==\nFrom September 2006 until 2007, Fischer was a senior fellow at the [[Liechtenstein Institute on Self-Determination]], and as a visiting professor co-taught with [[Wolfgang F. Danspeckgruber]] at [[Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs]], both at [[Princeton University]]. He has also spoken at other American universities on various topics in foreign affairs and international relations.\n\nIn addition, Fischer joined various non-governmental organizations, including:\n* [[Arab Democracy Foundation]], Founding Member of the Board of Trustees (since 2007)\n* [[Council on Foreign Relations]], Member<ref>Victor Homola (28 July 2006), [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/28/world/europe/28briefs-007.html Germany: Farewell to German Politics] ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* [[European Council on Foreign Relations]] (ECFR), Founding Co-Chairman of the Board (alongside [[Martti Ahtisaari]] and [[Mabel van Oranje]])<ref>[http://www.ecfr.eu/about About Us] [[European Council on Foreign Relations]] (ECFR).</ref>\n* United Nations Association of Germany (DGVN), Member of the Presidium<ref>[http://www.dgvn.de/structure-of-una-germany/presidium/ Presidium] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918015652/http://www.dgvn.de/structure-of-una-germany/presidium/ |date=18 September 2016 }} United Nations Association of Germany (DGVN).</ref>\n* [[Meridiam]], Member of the Supervisory Board (since 2012)<ref>[http://www.meridiam.com/en/team Supervisory Board] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601174003/http://www.meridiam.com/en/team |date=1 June 2016 }} [[Meridiam]].</ref>\n* [[Institut f\u00fcr die Wissenschaften vom Menschen|Institute for Human Sciences]] (IWM), Member of the Board of Patrons<ref>[http://www.iwm.at/the-institute/boards/ Board of Patrons]</ref>\n* [[Roland Berger|Roland Berger Human Dignity Award]], Member of the Awards Committee<ref>[http://m.rolandbergerstiftung.org/en/the-foundation/the-committees/?tx_lombperson_pi2%5Bgremium%5D=3&tx_lombperson_pi2%5Baction%5D=detail&tx_lombperson_pi2%5Bcontroller%5D=Committee&cHash=b471bf28758cc4f8d667a13dfb11ef27 Member of the Awards Committee] Roland Berger Foundation.</ref>\n\nSince 2008, Fischer has been Senior Strategic Counsel at [[Albright Stonebridge Group]], Washington, DC, consulting firm led by [[Madeleine Albright]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thealbrightgroupllc.com/Who_We_Are.htm |title=Albright Group |accessdate=27 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.thealbrightgroupllc.com/Who_We_Are.htm |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In this capacity, has in the past been advising [[Siemens]], [[BMW]] and [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse]].<ref>[https://www.handelsblatt.com/unternehmen/management/vom-gruenen-zum-berater-fuer-diese-firmen-arbeitet-joschka-fischer/3901594.html F\u00fcr diese Firmen arbeitet Joschka Fischer] ''[[Handelsblatt]]'', 4 March 2011.</ref><ref>[http://boerse.ard.de/aktien/deutsche-boerse-kaempft-weiter100.html Deutsche B\u00f6rse k\u00e4mpft weiter] ''[[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]]'', 23 December 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Fischer took a post as adviser to the [[Nabucco pipeline]] project, in which the German RWE company is also involved. According to media reports, the \"six-digit salary\" consultancy contract has already been signed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wsws.org/articles/2009/jul2009/fisc-j03.shtml |author=Ulrich Rippert |title=Joschka Fischer takes post as Nabucco pipeline adviser |publisher=[[World Socialist Web Site]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.wsws.org/articles/2009/jul2009/fisc-j03.shtml |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 September 2010 Fischer supported the new initiative [[Spinelli Group]], which was founded to reinvigorate efforts towards federalisation of the European Union (EU). Other prominent supporters are: [[Jacques Delors]], [[Daniel Cohn-Bendit]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Andrew Duff]], [[Elmar Brok]].\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2002 \u2013 Honorary doctorate of the [[University of Haifa]]\n* 2003 \u2013 [[Buber-Rosenzweig-Medal|Buber Rosenzweig Medal]] (awarded by [[Paul Spiegel]])\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Gottlieb Duttweiler Institute|Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize]] (awarded by [[Micheline Calmy-Rey]] and [[Jean-Claude Juncker]])<ref>Jacob Greber (4 May 2004), [http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/joschka-fischer-wins-gottlieb-duttweiler-prize/3887864 Joschka Fischer wins Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize] ''Swissinfo''.</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 Honorary doctorate of [[Tel Aviv University]]\n* 2009 \u2013 [[Leo-Baeck-Medal|Leo Baeck Medal]] (awarded by [[James Wolfensohn]] and [[Henry Kissinger]])\n* 2012 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[University of Michigan]]<ref>[http://www.ur.umich.edu/update/archives/121015/honorary Six to receive honorary degrees at Winter Commencement] ''University of Michigan''.</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 Medal for Extraordinary Merits for Bavaria in a United Europe\n\n==Personal life==\nPrior to the [[German Visa Affair 2005]], Fischer was a popular politician, \"loved by an entire nation.\" Writing in ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', journalist Charles Hawley opined that since 1998, \"Joschka Fischer's popularity has been virtually unassailable: The icon of the environmentally minded Green Party could, it seemed, do no wrong. Indeed, Fischer was so popular in 2002 that Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder largely based his early election campaign on the fact that Fischer would remain at his side at the helm of Germany's political leadership.\"<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">\"[http://www.spiegel.de/international/political-scandal-joschka-fischer-with-his-back-against-the-wall-a-343108.html Political Scandal: Joschka Fischer with His Back Against the Wall]\" ''Der Spiegel'', 22 February 2005</ref> As Germany\u2019s Foreign Minister, Fischer\u2019s popularity soared when he opposed the [[Iraq War]], and his very public struggle with his weight endeared him to many Germans.\n[[File:Joska fischer wappen.png|thumb]]\n\nUp until 1996, Fischer was a [[bon vivant]], and often spoke openly about his love for good wines and food despite his \"chunky\" figure.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/> As he ascended to the Foreign Ministry, Fischer decided to lose weight, transforming his body almost overnight by refraining from alcohol and becoming a vegetarian. In 2000, he covered the topic of his weight loss by writing the book ''My Long Race Towards Myself'' on his experience, which became an immediate [[bestseller]] in Germany.\nHalf a year before becoming foreign minister, he had his marathon debut at the 1998 [[Hamburg Marathon]] (clocking 3:41)<ref>{{cite web |author=Herbert Seffrey |url=http://www.herbertsteffny.de/percoach.htm |title=Personal Trainer |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.herbertsteffny.de/percoach.htm |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> As minister, he finished [[New York City Marathon|New York]] in 1999 (3:55)<ref>{{cite news |author=Gisela Oswald |title=New York Marathon: Fischer im Ziel |trans-title=New York Marathon: Fisher in target |work=Spiegel Online |url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/new-york-marathon-fischer-im-ziel-a-51392.html |date=11 August 1999 |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/new-york-marathon-fischer-im-ziel-a-51392.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Berlin Marathon|Berlin]] in 2000 (3:55)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rp-online.de/sport/joschka-fischer-auf-rang-8919-1.1539566 |title=Joschka Fischer auf Rang 8.919 |language=de |publisher=RP Online |date=9 October 2000 |accessdate=28 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.rp-online.de/sport/joschka-fischer-auf-rang-8919-aid-1.1539566 |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nAfterwards, he reduced training and during the months preceding the [[Iraq War]], Fischer began putting on weight again.\n\nFischer was married to [[Germans|German]]-[[Iran]]ian film producer and screenwriter [[:de:Minu Barati|Minu Barati]] in 2005. It is his fifth marriage. His two children with his previous partner and eventual wife, Inge Vogel (to whom he was married from 1984-1987), were born in 1979 and 1983, respectively. At the time of his wedding with Barati in 2005, she was mother to a six-year-old daughter from a previous relationship, while Fischer's children were 23 and 26 of age at the time. The couple lives with Barati's daughter.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Print.aspx?storyid=125719 |title=Fischer marries for fifth time |newspaper=[[Gulf Daily News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/Print.aspx?storyid=125719 |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he commissioned German heraldist [[Dieter Krieger]] to produce a [[coat of arms]], which was registered to the Rhein-Main [[Roll of arms|Wappenrolle]] ( <nowiki>http://RMWR.dieter-krieger.de</nowiki> ). The arms are a type of a \"[[Canting arms]]\"; [[Division of the field#Common divisions of the field|party per fesse]] silver and gules, in chief crossed axes with red blades and black handles, in base, a fish in the first. [[Crest (heraldry)|Crest]] of the red eagle's wings, [[mantling]] red doubled silver.<ref>{{cite news |author=Franziska v. Mutius |url=https://www.welt.de/print-welt/article330518/Joschka_Fischer_setzt_auf_Tradition_und_kauft_ein_Familienwappen.html |title=Joschka Fischer setzt auf Tradition und kauft ein Familienwappen |newspaper=[[Die Welt]] |date=27 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116065904/http://www.welt.de/print-welt/article330518/Joschka_Fischer_setzt_auf_Tradition_und_kauft_ein_Familienwappen.html |archivedate=16 November 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.schloss-alsbach.org/rolle1.htm ''Bundesau\u00dfenminister a. D. Joschka Fischer erh\u00e4lt Wappenbrief der Rhein-Main-Wappenrolle''] (with Picture) on Website of [[Schloss Alsbach|Schlosses Alsbach]]</ref>\n\nHe describes himself as Catholic, but not very religious.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dennis Kremer|url=https://www.welt.de/fernsehen/article1246648/Joschka-Fischer-und-die-sieben-Todsuenden.html|title=Joschka Fischer und die sieben Tods\u00fcnden|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=10 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Paul Berman: ''Idealisten an der Macht. Die Passion des Joschka Fischer.'' Siedler, M\u00fcnchen 2006, {{ISBN|3-88680-846-7}}.\n* J\u00fcrgen Schreiber: ''Meine Jahre mit Joschka. Nachrichten von fetten und mageren Zeiten.'' Econ, Berlin 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-430-30033-9}}.\n* Christian Y. Schmidt: ''Wir sind die Wahnsinnigen. Joschka Fischer und seine Frankfurter Gang.'' Verbrecher Verlag, Berlin 2013.\n* Interviews\n* [[Gero von Boehm]]: ''Joschka Fischer. 31. August 2010''. Interview in: ''Begegnungen. Menschenbilder aus drei Jahrzehnten''. Collection Rolf Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2012, {{ISBN|978-3-89910-443-1}}, S. 678\u2013692\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Joschka Fischer|Joschka Fischer}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Britannica|208420}}\n*{{HessBib PPN|116465336}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130122073751/http://bostonreview.net/BR29.3/hockenos.html Boston Review article reviewing Fischer's biography]\n*[http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/biografien/FischerJoschka/index.html Biography at the German Historic Museum] {{in lang|de}}\n*[http://www.dhm.de/ausstellungen/spuren_der_macht/fischer_index.htm Photographs of Joschka Fischer 1991 - 1998 at the German Historic Museum] {{in lang|de}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721193118/http://citron-vert.info/article.php3?id_article=669 Joschka Fischer, la retraite ou pas ?] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110721193220/http://citron-vert.info/article.php3?id_article=674 Joscka Fischer : les discours d\u2019un Vert aux affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[https://archive.is/20080119011546/http://prok.princeton.edu/2-1/interview Interview with Joschka Fischer] After moving to Princeton University, Fischer gives an in-depth interview about security and globalization for [[Princeton Report on Knowledge]].\n*[http://www.project-syndicate.org/columnist/joschka-fischer Joschka Fischer's monthly syndicated commentary series, \"The Rebel Realist\", from Project Syndicate]\n\nThe following sources reflect the views of U.S. adversaries of Fischer and his policies, especially Germany's decision not to participate in the 2003 U.S.-led invasion of Iraq.\n*[http://slate.com/id/2078560 ''Why Germany Isn't Convinced]'' by [[Paul Berman]] in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''\n*''Power and the Idealists : Or, The Passion of Joschka Fischer, and Its Aftermath'' by Paul Berman. {{ISBN|1-932360-91-3}} (Originally appeared as a 25,000 word essay in ''[[The New Republic]]'', 3 September 2001)\n*[http://www.signandsight.com/features/380.html ''The last rock 'n' roller of German politics''] In an interview with the taz given in September 2005, Fischer reflects on what his coming retirement means for his party, his country and himself. At signandsight.com\n\nJoschka Fischer writes a monthly commentary series, \"The Rebel Realist\", for Project Syndicate, a non-profit association of newspapers around the world.\n*[http://www.project-syndicate.org/series/38/description The Rebel Realist]\n\nJoschka Fisher speaks to Leadel.NET, an online Jewish media portal, in a video interview\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081202114943/http://leadel.net/]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Klaus Kinkel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice-Chancellor of Germany|Vice Chancellor of Germany]]|years=1998\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Franz M\u00fcntefering]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Germany)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]|years=1998\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Speaker at the [[College of Europe]] Opening Ceremony|years=2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{BRDFMs}}\n{{GermanViceChancellors}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fischer, Joschka}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Alliance 90/The Greens politicians]]\n[[Category:Foreign Ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:German Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Hesse]]\n[[Category:People from Gerabronn]]\n[[Category:People of Hungarian German descent]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gottlieb Duttweiler Prize]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Hesse]]\n[[Category:21st-century German politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag 2005\u20132009]]\n", "name_user": "JWHBerlin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joschka_Fischer"}
{"title_page": "Expo 2020", "text_new": "{{coord missing|United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = <!-- Width of infobox, default: 25em; Note: use auto for automatic width -->\n| class           = Universal\n| category        = 3\n| image           = Dubai Expo 2020 Logo.png\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = \n| year            = 2020\n| name            = \t\n| motto           = Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\n| building        = \n| area            ={{convert|438|ha|acre|abbr=off}} \n| invent          = \n| visitors        = \n| organized       = [[Reem Al Hashimi]] (Managing Director)\n| mascot = Salama, Rashid, Latifa, Alif, Opti, and Terra<ref name=\"mascots\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/attractions/mascots|accessdate=3 November 2019|title=Mascots &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref>\n| cnt             = 192 confirmed April 2019<ref name=\"2018countrycount\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20190425-all-countries-invited|accessdate=April 25, 2019|title=192 countries to take part in Expo 2020}}</ref>\n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = United Arab Emirates\n| city            = [[Dubai]]\n| venue           = \n| coord           = \n| cand            = \n| award           = {{start date|2013|11|27}}\n| open            = October 1, 2021\n| close           = March 31, 2022\n| prevexpo        = [[Expo 2015]]\n| prevcity        = [[Milan]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 2025]]\n| nextcity        = [[Osaka]]\n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = [[Expo 2017]]\n| prevsupcity     = [[Astana]]\n| nextsuppl       = [[Expo 2023]]\n| nextsupcity     = [[Buenos Aires]]\n| prevunho        = [[2019 World Horticultural Exposition]]\n| prevunhocity    = [[Beijing]]\n| nextunho        = [[2021 World Horticultural Exposition]]\n| nextunhocity    = [[Doha]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.expo2020dubai.com/}}\n}}\n'''Expo 2020''' ({{lang-ar|\u0625\u0643\u0633\u0628\u0648 2020}}) is a [[World Expo]] to be hosted by [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]], opening on 1st October 2021. The [[Bureau International des Expositions]] (BIE) general assembly in [[Paris]] awarded Dubai as the host on November 27, 2013.\n\n==Parameters==\nAs a World Expo, it may be a maximum of six\nmonths in length<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/how-to-organize-an-expo|title=How is an Expo organised?|website=www.bie-paris.org|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> and adhere to a wide universal theme that applies to all humanity. Past themes of Universal Expositions include \"Man and His World\" [[Montreal]] [[Expo 67]], \"The Age of Discovery\" [[Seville]] [[Seville Expo '92|Expo 92]] and \"Feeding the Planet, Energy for Life\" [[Milan]] [[Expo 2015]].\n\n==Organization==\nThe main site of Expo Dubai 2020 will be a 438-hectare area (1083 acres) located between the cities of Dubai and Abu Dhabi, near [[Dubai emirate|Dubai]]'s southern border with [[Abu Dhabi emirate|Abu Dhabi]].\nThe master plan, designed by the American firm [[HOK (firm)|HOK]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hok.com/design/service/planning-urban-design/dubai-expo-2020-master-plan/|title=Dubai Expo 2020 Master Plan|last=HOK|website=www.hok.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> is organized around a central plaza, entitled ''Al Wasl'', enclosed by three large Thematic districts. Each one is dedicated to one of the sub-themes of Expo 2020 \u2013 Opportunity, Mobility and Sustainability.<ref name=\"themese\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/themes|title=Themes at Expo 2020 Dubai|website=www.expo2020dubai.com|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\nDubai has also been emphasizing on investments in various sectors such as economic growth, real estate, environmental avenues and public affairs. In recent times, Dubai has made major investments in Real Estate<ref>{{cite web|last=Nagraj|first=Aarti|title=Dubai Properties launches two-tower project|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/dubai-properties-launches-two-tower-project-business-bay/|accessdate=30 May 2016|publisher=Gulf Business}}</ref> as well as introduced a world's largest [[Solar Power]] Project which is all set to start by Expo 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nagraj|first=Aarti|title=Dubai launches world\u2019s largest concentrated solar power project|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/dewa-launches-worlds-largest-concentrated-solar-power-project/|accessdate=2 June 2016|publisher=Gulf Business}}</ref> Apart from pumping money, the nation is also keen on giving equal prominence to public relationships. The initiative \u2013 Dubai Happiness Agenda, has 16 programmes under four themes that sums up 82 projects to be set in the city with an aim to make the city the happiest by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamdan|first=Lubna|title=Dubai scores 89% on happiness index for government services|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/dubai-scores-89-on-happiness-index-for-government-services-633287.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Arabian Business}}</ref> The Dubai Expo 2020 also would see a rise in the [[GDP]] as predicted by the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Al Heialy|first=Yasmin|title=Expo 2020 spending to help Dubai's economy outperform peers|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/expo-2020-spending-help-dubai-s-economy-outperform-peers-631173.html|accessdate=10 May 2016|publisher=Arabian Business}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UAE Gears Up Ahead of Dubai EXPO 2020|url=https://www.shuraa.com/blog/2016/06/uae-gears-up-ahead-of-dubai-expo-2020.html|accessdate=16 June 2016|publisher=Shuraa Business Setup}}</ref>\n\n==Participants==\nThe following nations have announced their participation in Expo 2020:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n#  {{flagcountry|Afghanistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Algeria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Australia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Angola}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Argentina}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Australia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Azerbaijan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Austria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bahamas}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bahrain}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Belarus}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Belgium}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bhutan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bulgaria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Burkina Faso}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bangladesh}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Brunei}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Brazil}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Canada}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cambodia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cape Verde}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Central African Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Chile}}\n#  {{flagcountry|China}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Colombia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cuba}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cyprus}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Czech Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Republic of Congo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Denmark}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Dominican Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Djibouti}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ecuador}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Egypt}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Estonia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|France}}<ref>{{cite news | author =Sam Bridge | title =Construction starts on France's Expo 2020 Dubai pavilion | quote =\"...construction work has started on the French Pavilion, Lumi\u00e8re Lumi\u00e8res, for Expo 2020 Dubai.\" | newspaper =Arabian Business | date =May 2, 2019 | url =https://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/419287-construction-starts-on-frances-expo-2020-dubai-pavilion | accessdate =May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|Fiji}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Finland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Greece}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Grenada}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Guinea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Germany}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Hong Kong}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Hungary}}\n#  {{flagcountry|India}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Indonesia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Israel}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Italy}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iran}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iraq}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iceland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ireland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Japan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Jordan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kazakhstan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kosovo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kuwait}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kyrgyzstan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Laos}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lesotho}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lebanon}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Liberia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lithuania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Luxembourg}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Latvia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Macau}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Marshall Islands}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Malaysia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mauritius}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Monaco}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mongolia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Morocco}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Myanmar}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mexico}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mozambique}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nauru}}\n#  {{flagcountry|NLD}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nepal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nigeria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|New Zealand}}\n#  {{flagcountry|North Korea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Norway}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Oman}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Pakistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Palestine}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enasher.com/our-work/projects/design-palestine-pavilion-expo-2020-dubai|title=Design for Palestine Pavilion at Expo 2020 - Dubai &#124; Al Nasher|accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Pavilionps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotelandrest.com/ar/tourism-news/article-53680/|title=\u0647\u0648\u062a\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0646\u062f \u0631\u064a\u0633\u062a - \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0645\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u064a\u0627\u0646 \u062d\u0627\u0636\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u00ab\u0625\u0643\u0633\u0628\u0648 2020 \u062f\u0628\u064a\u00bb|accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|Philippines}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Poland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Peru}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Panama}}\n#  {{flag country|Qatar}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Russia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Romania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Rwanda}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Senegal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Serbia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Singapore}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sierra Leone}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Slovenia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Solomon Islands}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Somalia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Spain}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Lucia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saudi Arabia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|South Korea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sweden}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Switzerland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|South Africa}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sudan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|San Marino}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sri Lanka}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Taiwan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Thailand}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Togo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tunisia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tuvalu}}\n#  {{flagcountry|East Timor}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Turkey}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Turkmenistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tajikistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tanzania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ukraine}}\n#  {{flagcountry|United Arab Emirates}}<ref>{{cite news | title =Construction of Expo 2020 Dubai pavilions set to start in April | quote =\"Last month, the foundations of the futuristic falcon-inspired UAE pavilion were laid.\" | newspaper =Arabian Business | date =January 20, 2018 | url =https://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/387795-construction-of-expo-2020-dubai-pavilions-set-to-start-in-april | accessdate =May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n#  {{flagcountry|United States of America}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uganda}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uruguay}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uzbekistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Vatican City}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Vietnam}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Venezuela}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Zimbabwe}}\n# {{div col end}}\n}}\n\n===Pavilions===\nThe Palestine pavilion will be between the Saudi and UAE pavilion and occupy 1250 square metres.<ref name=\"Pavilionps\" />\n\nThe Russia pavilion is planned to be 27 metres tall and cover more than 4500 square metres. It is being designed by Tchoban SPEECH and Simpateka Entertainment.<ref name=\"Russia2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20191119-russia-groundbreaking|accessdate=29 January 2020|title=Russia sets its sights high for pavilion &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref>\n\n== International Participant Meeting (IPM) ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2019}}\n2017 IPM meeting was held in October 2018.\n\n2018 IPM meeting was held on 26-27 Nov 2018 hosted by [[Reem Al Hashimi]], the Managing Director of Expo 2020 Dubai.\n\n==Themes==\nThe expo will have a theme called \"Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\".The expo will also have three subthemes: opportunity, mobility and sustainability,<ref name=\"themese\" /> each with its own pavilion. The Opportunity pavilion is designed by Cox Architecture,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/opportunity|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Opportunity Pavilion}}</ref> Mobility by [[Foster and Partners]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/mobility|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Mobility Pavilion}}</ref> and Sustainability by [[Grimshaw Architects]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/sustainability|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Sustainability Pavilion}}</ref>\n\n===Sustainability===\nIn the sustainability district in addition to the sustainability pavilion, there is a [[Grouper|Hammour]] House which explores coral reef; a district stage which seats 300 and \n''Walk through a waterfall'' Brazil's national pavilion,\n''Water the desert'' Czech Republic's,\n''Enter a rainforest'' Singapore's,\n''Wear cutting-edge devices'' Germany's,\nand ''Enter a miniature world'' Netherlands's pavilion.<ref name=sustain>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/themes/sustainability-district|title=Sustainability District &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tour of Dubai Expo 2020 site ==\nExpo 2020 organisers have invited UAE residents to visit the Expo 2020 site as it nears completion. Visitors would board colorful Expo 2020 branded coaches at various pick up points across the UAE. The bus journey includes an introduction to the history of World Expos. At the site, the visitors would disembark at the Visitor Centre for snacks and activities, followed by a tour of the site and its iconic architecture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/free-bus-tour-of-dubai-expo-2020-site-ahead-of-greatest-show-in-the-world-|title=Free bus tour of Dubai Expo 2020 site for residents announced|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=July 17, 2019|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\nThe emirate's tourism and hospitality sectors will face new opportunities and challenges in hosting the event. Najeeb Mohammad Saleh, head of the planning research at Dubai Municipality said \"We looked at three different scenarios - low, medium and rapid. We have adopted the medium-growth scenario, and expect the population by 2020 to be about 2.8 million.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefirstgroup.com/en/news/how-is-dubai-preparing-for-the-world-expo-2020|title=HOW IS DUBAI PREPARING FOR THE WORLD EXPO 2020?|date=March 1, 2015|work=The First Group|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\nThe upcoming Expo 2020 means that most premium hotels will be operating near full capacity through to 2021. Benjamin Moore Middle East is focussed on the UAE's luxury hospitality segment as the moment. By helping hotels upgrade the paints and coatings they use to more durable products, while simultaneously helping them reduce their maintenance costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://design-middleeast.com/paint-it|title=Paint it!|last=Arora|first=Roma|date=November 10, 2019|work=Design Middle east|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn order to raise awareness about smart recycling, Expo 2020 will organize nationwide bus tours with the waste partner Dulsco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20200115-dulsco-bus|title=All aboard for Expo\u2019s recycling bus {{!}} Expo 2020 Dubai|website=www.expo2020dubai.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Emergency care services at Expo 2020 site ==\nThe on-site emergency centre includes an isolation room, emergency care room, ambulances and helicopter services. [[Rob Cooling]], vice president of health, safety and environment at Expo 2020 Dubai stated in a media interview that equipment and preventive measures are in place to manage emergencies. The centre is equipped to provide immediate care and stabilisation in the 'golden hour'. The golden hour in emergency care means the first sixty minutes after an injury or illness when medical care may be most effective.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/expo-2020-dubai-emergency-centre-to-provide-olympic-quality-care-to-visitors-1.894928|title=Expo 2020 Dubai emergency centre to provide 'Olympic quality' care to visitors|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=August 5, 2019|work=The National|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Developments==\nIn November 2019, the UAE permitted [[Israel]]i passport holders to enter the country during Expo 2020. Israelis were allowed to have their own pavilion at the event and to even visit the country afterwards.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5620240,00.html|title=Dubai to open its doors to Israeli tourists in 2020|accessdate=6 November 2019|website=Yedioth Ahronoth}}</ref>\n\nA French luxury brand [[Cartier (jeweler)|Cartier]] was expected to set up a women centric pavilion in association with prominent [[human rights]] lawyer [[Amal Clooney]], in October 2020. Clooney was to lend her voice to the initiative to discuss the role of women in society and ways to tackle [[gender inequality]], while celebrating female achievers.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/culture/featured-news/amal-clooney-joins-cartier-for-for-dubai-expo-2020-pavillion|title=Amal Clooney Partners With Cartier To Empower Women At Dubai Expo 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=Harper\u2019s Bazaar Arabia}}</ref>\n\n===Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic===\nIn 2020, the globally expanding [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] brought Expo 2020 Dubai under questions, as the event was expected to attract nearly 25 million visitors in October that year.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b7a7902a-68ff-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=Gulf economies rocked by coronavirus and oil price war|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=Financial Times}}</ref> In March, the Geneva Council for Rights and Liberties warned against the abuse and exploitation of [[migrant workers in the United Arab Emirates]]. While rest of the country was under a lockdown due to the spread of coronavirus, the migrants continued to work on Expo 2020. The Geneva Council condemned the \u201cdiscriminatory treatment of migrant workers\u201d, urging the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] to encourage the [[UAE]] to ensure their health and safety.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-migrant-workers-overseas-human-rights-covid-19-a9426086.html|title=Coronavirus: Migrant workers in UK and overseas face \u2018disproportionate risk\u2019 from Covid-19|accessdate=26 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2020 the expo indicated that it was investigating postponement of the world's fair. An event that would require a two third's majority agreement from a BIE annual general meeting.<ref name=\"March30post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/expo-covid-19|access-date=30 March 2020|title=Expo 2020 Dubai and the UAE response to COVID-19 &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref> On 4 April 2020 the BIE announced that a meeting of the executive committee would take place virtually on 21 April to discuss a proposal to hold the expo between 1 October 2021 and 31 March 2022.<ref name=\"BIEpostpone1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/news-announcements/expo-dubai-2020-2/bie-convenes-21-april-meeting-of-its-executive-committee-to-discuss-change-of-dates-for-expo-2020-dubai|access-date=5 April 2020|title=BIE convenes 21 April meeting of its Executive Committee to discuss change of dates for Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref> A final decision would need a two third's majority vote from BIE members.<ref name=\"BIEpostpone1\" />\n\nOn 21 April the executive committee unanimously to delay the expo until 1 October 2021 \u2013 31 March 2022,<ref name=Unambie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/news-announcements/expo-dubai-2020-2/bie-executive-committee-proposes-postponement-of-expo-2020-dubai-member-states-to-vote-on-change-of-dates\n|access-date=21 April 2020|title=BIE Executive Committee proposes postponement of Expo 2020 Dubai, Member States to vote on change of dates}}</ref> with this now{{Update after|2020|05|30}} going to a remote vote of the general assembly.<ref name=Unambie\" /> There is no proposal to change the name of the expo.<ref name=Unambie\" />\n\n==Bids and bidding==\nOnce  the first city had lodged a bid with the BIE, other cities had six months to respond. In early 2011, Izmir of Turkey and Ayutthaya of Thailand submitted bids to the BIE, initiating the six-month window for other cities to bid. When this window closed on 2 November 2011, there were five prospective cities, with Dubai making a last minute entry. The BIE voted and selected the host city on 27 November 2013.\n\nFive cities originally bid for the slot for a world's fair in 2020, with four remaining: Dubai, United Arab Emirates; Yekaterinburg, Russia; Izmir, Turkey; or S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil. Expo 2020 will represent a first as a Middle Eastern destination will be hosting the event for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expomuseum.com/2020/ |title=ExpoMuseum / Expo 2020, Ayutthaya, Thailand; Dubai, USA; Izmir, Turkey; Sao Paulo, Brazil; or Yekaterinburg, Russia |publisher=Expomuseum.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>\n\nThe following cities lodged bids to the BIE for hosting the 2020 EXPO:\n* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Izmir]], [[Turkey]]\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/business/20110802/165518448.html |title=Russia to propose Yekaterinburg as Expo 2020 venue &#124; Business &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/430-yekaterinburg-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Yekaterinburg, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prefeitura.sp.gov.br/cidade/secretarias/relacoes_internacionais/noticias/?p=13802 |title=Portal da Prefeitura da Cidade de S\u00e3o Paulo |publisher=Prefeitura.sp.gov.br |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/431-sao-paulo-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Sao Paulo, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|UAE}} [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlingske.dk/article/20080612/koebenhavn/80612042/ |title=K\u00f8benhavn vil huse verdensudstilling &#124; www.b.dk |publisher=Berlingske.dk |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>\nS\u00e3o Paulo was eliminated from contention after the first round of votes. Izmir was knocked out in the second. Yekaterinburg lost to Dubai in the third and final round of voting.\n\n===Dubai Expo===\nUAE selected the theme \"Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\", sub-themes being Sustainability, Mobility and Opportunity.<ref>{{cite web |author=Maeve Hosea |url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/expo_2020_dubai_celebrates_in_style |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: Dubai celebrates in style |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=2013-11-28 |accessdate=2015-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223140241/http://vision.ae/en/articles/expo_2020_dubai_celebrates_in_style |archive-date=December 23, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=His Highness Sheikh Ahmed bin Saeed Al Maktoum January 2015 |url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/world_expo_from_vision_to_victory |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: From vision to victory |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=January 2014 |accessdate=2015-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027092626/http://vision.ae/en/articles/world_expo_from_vision_to_victory |archive-date=October 27, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n\"In today\u2019s highly interconnected world, a renewed vision of progress and development based on shared purpose and commitment is key. While a married human mind, an individual country, or a specific community is both unique and remarkable, it is by working collaboratively that we truly advance.\" Dubai Ruler [[Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]] said in support of the bid.\n\nThe World Expo in Dubai in 2020 will be the first to be held in the [[MENA]] & SA (Middle East and North Africa & South Asia) region.\nOn 27 November 2013, when Dubai won the right to host the expo 2020, fireworks erupted at the world's tallest building, [[Burj Khalifa]]. A national holiday was declared the following day for all educational institutions across the country. The Dubai Ruler promised Dubai would \"astonish the world,\" in 2020. The staging of the world fair and the preparations leading up to it are expected to result in 277,000 new jobs in the UAE, an injection of nearly $40 billion into the economy, and an increase in visitors of at least 25 million and up to 100 million.<ref name=\"Expo 2020 Dubai\">{{cite web|title=Dubai wins right to host Expo 2020|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/economy/dubai-expo-2020-would-support-277-000-jobs-1.1181465|accessdate=28 November 2013|publisher=Gulf News}}</ref> Director General of Dubai Municipality, Hussain Nasser Lootah, said that they have the largest laboratory in the region, and can easily research new materials and technologies required for construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/business/economy-finance/dubai-is-ready-to-deal-with-expo-2020-construction-boom-lootah-2014-11-19-1.570636 |title=Dubai is ready to deal with Expo 2020 construction boom: Lootah \u2013 Emirates 24&#124;7 |work=Emirates247.com |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2015-09-19}}</ref> The world's tallest commercial tower to be built in Dubai, in [[Jumeirah Lake Towers]], was given the name \"Burj 2020\" in honour of the World Expo 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmcc.ae/content-page?Turner-to-Project-Manage-Burj2020&articleid=a051000000UWFsnAAH|title=Turner to Project Manage Burj 2020|publisher=DMCC|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> [[Hamdan bin Mohammed Al Maktoum]] also went to the top floor of the [[Burj Khalifa]] to wave the UAE flag, a few days after the World Expo 2020 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20131128/ARTICLE/311289967/1036|title=Shaikh Hamdan waves UAE flag from top of Burj Khalifa \u2013 Khaleej Times|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Yekaterinburg Expo===\nThe Russian bid ''The Global Mind'' would have run from May 1 to October 31, and would have been the second largest expo (after [[Expo 2010|2010]] in Shanghai) and intended to  \"survey world opinion through seven universal questions\".<ref name=\"Ekaterinburg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/ekaterinburg-russia|accessdate=17 November 2013|title=Ekaterinburg \u2013 Russia}}</ref>\n\n===\u0130zmir Expo===\nThe Turkish bid had a theme of ''New Routes to a Better World / Health for All'' and would have run from April 30 to October 31.<ref name=\"bieizmir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/izmir-turkey|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Izmir \u2013 Turkey}}</ref> A ''Health for All'' symposium was held in October 2013 for BIE delegates and was to discuss health issues across the world.<ref name=\"h4asymposium\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Health For All Symposium|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034410/http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===S\u00e3o Paulo Expo===\nA Brazilian expo would have been called ''Power of Diversity, Harmony for Growth'',<ref name=\"saopself\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saopauloexpo2020.com.br/?page_id=718&lang=en|accessdate=28 November 2013|title=The theme  \u2013  S\u00e3o Paulo Expo 2020}}</ref> run from May 15 to November 15 and would have covered 502 hectares.<ref name=\"biesaop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/sao-paulo-brazil|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Sao Paulo \u2013 Brazil}}</ref>\n\n==Ticket prices==\nThe normal 1-day tickets for the expo cost AED 120, while the 3-day tickets are AED 260. There is a 50% discount on entry for students of any age and youth aged 6 to 17. The expo gives free access to kids up to 5 years and adults 65 years & above. Disabled persons are also allowed free entry and a caregiver can also visit with them at half the ticket price.''<ref name=\"tickets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.globalmediainsight.com/blog/dubai-expo-2020-facts-and-statistics|accessdate=16 December 2019|title=Dubai Expo 2020 Facts and Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://expo2020dubai.com}}\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/2020-dubai Expo 2020 page at the BIE]\n*[http://www.epo.org/law-practice/legal-texts/official-journal/2016/etc/se4/p219.html European Patent Office]\n*[http://www.ExpoBids.com/ ExpoBids.com] Noticias sobre las Ofertas de la Feria Mundial de Todo El Mundo.\n*[http://www.studylove.org/worldsfairs19.html#2020 2020 Dubai (BIE World Expo)] \u2013 approximately 95 links\n*[http://www.youtube.com/user/DubaiExpo2020 Expo 2020 Dubai] - YouTube User\n*[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UDxQqPZBSI Emarati (Dubai Expo 2020 Song)] - YouTube, music video, 3m50s\n*[https://profounduae.com/impact-of-expo-2020-on-uae-business/ Impact of EXPO 2020 on UAE Business]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n\n[[Category:2020 festivals]]\n[[Category:Scheduled events]]\n[[Category:Events in Dubai]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in Asia|UAE]]\n[[Category:2020s in Dubai]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord missing|United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = <!-- Width of infobox, default: 25em; Note: use auto for automatic width -->\n| class           = Universal\n| category        = 3\n| image           = Dubai Expo 2020 Logo.png\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = \n| year            = 2020\n| name            = \t\n| motto           = Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\n| building        = \n| area            ={{convert|438|ha|acre|abbr=off}} \n| invent          = \n| visitors        = \n| organized       = [[Reem Al Hashimi]] (Managing Director)\n| mascot = Salama, Rashid, Latifa, Alif, Opti, and Terra<ref name=\"mascots\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/attractions/mascots|accessdate=3 November 2019|title=Mascots &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref>\n| cnt             = 192 confirmed April 2019<ref name=\"2018countrycount\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20190425-all-countries-invited|accessdate=April 25, 2019|title=192 countries to take part in Expo 2020}}</ref>\n| org             = \n| biz             = \n| country         = United Arab Emirates\n| city            = [[Dubai]]\n| venue           = \n| coord           = \n| cand            = \n| award           = {{start date|2013|11|27}}\n| open            = TBD\n| close           = TBD\n| prevexpo        = [[Expo 2015]]\n| prevcity        = [[Milan]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 2025]]\n| nextcity        = [[Osaka]]\n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = [[Expo 2017]]\n| prevsupcity     = [[Astana]]\n| nextsuppl       = [[Expo 2023]]\n| nextsupcity     = [[Buenos Aires]]\n| prevunho        = [[2019 World Horticultural Exposition]]\n| prevunhocity    = [[Beijing]]\n| nextunho        = [[2021 World Horticultural Exposition]]\n| nextunhocity    = [[Doha]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.expo2020dubai.com/}}\n}}\n'''Expo 2020''' ({{lang-ar|\u0625\u0643\u0633\u0628\u0648 2020}}) is a [[World Expo]] to be hosted by [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]], opening on October 20, 2020. The [[Bureau International des Expositions]] (BIE) general assembly in [[Paris]] awarded Dubai as the host on November 27, 2013.\n\n==Parameters==\nAs a World Expo, it may be a maximum of six\nmonths in length<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/how-to-organize-an-expo|title=How is an Expo organised?|website=www.bie-paris.org|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> and adhere to a wide universal theme that applies to all humanity. Past themes of Universal Expositions include \"Man and His World\" [[Montreal]] [[Expo 67]], \"The Age of Discovery\" [[Seville]] [[Seville Expo '92|Expo 92]] and \"Feeding the Planet, Energy for Life\" [[Milan]] [[Expo 2015]].\n\n==Organization==\nThe main site of Expo Dubai 2020 will be a 438-hectare area (1083 acres) located between the cities of Dubai and Abu Dhabi, near [[Dubai emirate|Dubai]]'s southern border with [[Abu Dhabi emirate|Abu Dhabi]].\nThe master plan, designed by the American firm [[HOK (firm)|HOK]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hok.com/design/service/planning-urban-design/dubai-expo-2020-master-plan/|title=Dubai Expo 2020 Master Plan|last=HOK|website=www.hok.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> is organized around a central plaza, entitled ''Al Wasl'', enclosed by three large Thematic districts. Each one is dedicated to one of the sub-themes of Expo 2020 \u2013 Opportunity, Mobility and Sustainability.<ref name=\"themese\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/themes|title=Themes at Expo 2020 Dubai|website=www.expo2020dubai.com|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\nDubai has also been emphasizing on investments in various sectors such as economic growth, real estate, environmental avenues and public affairs. In recent times, Dubai has made major investments in Real Estate<ref>{{cite web|last=Nagraj|first=Aarti|title=Dubai Properties launches two-tower project|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/dubai-properties-launches-two-tower-project-business-bay/|accessdate=30 May 2016|publisher=Gulf Business}}</ref> as well as introduced a world's largest [[Solar Power]] Project which is all set to start by Expo 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nagraj|first=Aarti|title=Dubai launches world\u2019s largest concentrated solar power project|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/dewa-launches-worlds-largest-concentrated-solar-power-project/|accessdate=2 June 2016|publisher=Gulf Business}}</ref> Apart from pumping money, the nation is also keen on giving equal prominence to public relationships. The initiative \u2013 Dubai Happiness Agenda, has 16 programmes under four themes that sums up 82 projects to be set in the city with an aim to make the city the happiest by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamdan|first=Lubna|title=Dubai scores 89% on happiness index for government services|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/dubai-scores-89-on-happiness-index-for-government-services-633287.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Arabian Business}}</ref> The Dubai Expo 2020 also would see a rise in the [[GDP]] as predicted by the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Al Heialy|first=Yasmin|title=Expo 2020 spending to help Dubai's economy outperform peers|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/expo-2020-spending-help-dubai-s-economy-outperform-peers-631173.html|accessdate=10 May 2016|publisher=Arabian Business}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UAE Gears Up Ahead of Dubai EXPO 2020|url=https://www.shuraa.com/blog/2016/06/uae-gears-up-ahead-of-dubai-expo-2020.html|accessdate=16 June 2016|publisher=Shuraa Business Setup}}</ref>\n\n==Participants==\nThe following nations have announced their participation in Expo 2020:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n#  {{flagcountry|Afghanistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Algeria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Australia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Angola}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Argentina}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Australia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Azerbaijan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Austria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bahamas}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bahrain}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Belarus}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Belgium}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bhutan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bulgaria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Burkina Faso}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Bangladesh}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Brunei}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Brazil}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Canada}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cambodia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cape Verde}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Central African Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Chile}}\n#  {{flagcountry|China}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Colombia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cuba}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Cyprus}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Czech Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Republic of Congo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Denmark}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Dominican Republic}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Djibouti}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ecuador}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Egypt}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Estonia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|France}}<ref>{{cite news | author =Sam Bridge | title =Construction starts on France's Expo 2020 Dubai pavilion | quote =\"...construction work has started on the French Pavilion, Lumi\u00e8re Lumi\u00e8res, for Expo 2020 Dubai.\" | newspaper =Arabian Business | date =May 2, 2019 | url =https://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/419287-construction-starts-on-frances-expo-2020-dubai-pavilion | accessdate =May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|Fiji}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Finland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Greece}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Grenada}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Guinea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Germany}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Hong Kong}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Hungary}}\n#  {{flagcountry|India}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Indonesia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Israel}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Italy}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iran}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iraq}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Iceland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ireland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Japan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Jordan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kazakhstan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kosovo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kuwait}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Kyrgyzstan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Laos}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lesotho}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lebanon}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Liberia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Lithuania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Luxembourg}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Latvia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Macau}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Marshall Islands}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Malaysia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mauritius}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Monaco}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mongolia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Morocco}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Myanmar}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mexico}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Mozambique}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nauru}}\n#  {{flagcountry|NLD}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nepal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Nigeria}}\n#  {{flagcountry|New Zealand}}\n#  {{flagcountry|North Korea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Norway}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Oman}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Pakistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Palestine}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enasher.com/our-work/projects/design-palestine-pavilion-expo-2020-dubai|title=Design for Palestine Pavilion at Expo 2020 - Dubai &#124; Al Nasher|accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Pavilionps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotelandrest.com/ar/tourism-news/article-53680/|title=\u0647\u0648\u062a\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0646\u062f \u0631\u064a\u0633\u062a - \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0645\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u064a\u0627\u0646 \u062d\u0627\u0636\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u00ab\u0625\u0643\u0633\u0628\u0648 2020 \u062f\u0628\u064a\u00bb|accessdate=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|Philippines}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Poland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Portugal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Peru}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Panama}}\n#  {{flag country|Qatar}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Russia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Romania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Rwanda}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Senegal}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Serbia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Singapore}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sierra Leone}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Slovenia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Solomon Islands}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Somalia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Spain}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Lucia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Saudi Arabia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|South Korea}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sweden}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Switzerland}}\n#  {{flagcountry|South Africa}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sudan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|San Marino}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Sri Lanka}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Taiwan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Thailand}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Togo}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tunisia}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tuvalu}}\n#  {{flagcountry|East Timor}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Turkey}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Turkmenistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tajikistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Tanzania}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Ukraine}}\n#  {{flagcountry|United Arab Emirates}}<ref>{{cite news | title =Construction of Expo 2020 Dubai pavilions set to start in April | quote =\"Last month, the foundations of the futuristic falcon-inspired UAE pavilion were laid.\" | newspaper =Arabian Business | date =January 20, 2018 | url =https://www.arabianbusiness.com/construction/387795-construction-of-expo-2020-dubai-pavilions-set-to-start-in-april | accessdate =May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n#  {{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n#  {{flagcountry|United States of America}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uganda}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uruguay}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Uzbekistan}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Vatican City}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Vietnam}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Venezuela}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n#  {{flagcountry|Zimbabwe}}\n# {{div col end}}\n}}\n\n===Pavilions===\nThe Palestine pavilion will be between the Saudi and UAE pavilion and occupy 1250 square metres.<ref name=\"Pavilionps\" />\n\nThe Russia pavilion is planned to be 27 metres tall and cover more than 4500 square metres. It is being designed by Tchoban SPEECH and Simpateka Entertainment.<ref name=\"Russia2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20191119-russia-groundbreaking|accessdate=29 January 2020|title=Russia sets its sights high for pavilion &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref>\n\n== International Participant Meeting (IPM) ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2019}}\n2017 IPM meeting was held in October 2018.\n\n2018 IPM meeting was held on 26-27 Nov 2018 hosted by [[Reem Al Hashimi]], the Managing Director of Expo 2020 Dubai.\n\n==Themes==\nThe expo will have a theme called \"Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\".The expo will also have three subthemes: opportunity, mobility and sustainability,<ref name=\"themese\" /> each with its own pavilion. The Opportunity pavilion is designed by Cox Architecture,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/opportunity|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Opportunity Pavilion}}</ref> Mobility by [[Foster and Partners]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/mobility|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Mobility Pavilion}}</ref> and Sustainability by [[Grimshaw Architects]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/pavilions/sustainability|accessdate=2019-07-14|title=Sustainability Pavilion}}</ref>\n\n===Sustainability===\nIn the sustainability district in addition to the sustainability pavilion, there is a [[Grouper|Hammour]] House which explores coral reef; a district stage which seats 300 and \n''Walk through a waterfall'' Brazil's national pavilion,\n''Water the desert'' Czech Republic's,\n''Enter a rainforest'' Singapore's,\n''Wear cutting-edge devices'' Germany's,\nand ''Enter a miniature world'' Netherlands's pavilion.<ref name=sustain>{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/discover/themes/sustainability-district|title=Sustainability District &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tour of Dubai Expo 2020 site ==\nExpo 2020 organisers have invited UAE residents to visit the Expo 2020 site as it nears completion. Visitors would board colorful Expo 2020 branded coaches at various pick up points across the UAE. The bus journey includes an introduction to the history of World Expos. At the site, the visitors would disembark at the Visitor Centre for snacks and activities, followed by a tour of the site and its iconic architecture.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/uae/dubai/free-bus-tour-of-dubai-expo-2020-site-ahead-of-greatest-show-in-the-world-|title=Free bus tour of Dubai Expo 2020 site for residents announced|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=July 17, 2019|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Preparations==\nThe emirate's tourism and hospitality sectors will face new opportunities and challenges in hosting the event. Najeeb Mohammad Saleh, head of the planning research at Dubai Municipality said \"We looked at three different scenarios - low, medium and rapid. We have adopted the medium-growth scenario, and expect the population by 2020 to be about 2.8 million.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefirstgroup.com/en/news/how-is-dubai-preparing-for-the-world-expo-2020|title=HOW IS DUBAI PREPARING FOR THE WORLD EXPO 2020?|date=March 1, 2015|work=The First Group|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\nThe upcoming Expo 2020 means that most premium hotels will be operating near full capacity through to 2021. Benjamin Moore Middle East is focussed on the UAE's luxury hospitality segment as the moment. By helping hotels upgrade the paints and coatings they use to more durable products, while simultaneously helping them reduce their maintenance costs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://design-middleeast.com/paint-it|title=Paint it!|last=Arora|first=Roma|date=November 10, 2019|work=Design Middle east|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn order to raise awareness about smart recycling, Expo 2020 will organize nationwide bus tours with the waste partner Dulsco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/whats-new/expo-stories/20200115-dulsco-bus|title=All aboard for Expo\u2019s recycling bus {{!}} Expo 2020 Dubai|website=www.expo2020dubai.com|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Emergency care services at Expo 2020 site ==\nThe on-site emergency centre includes an isolation room, emergency care room, ambulances and helicopter services. [[Rob Cooling]], vice president of health, safety and environment at Expo 2020 Dubai stated in a media interview that equipment and preventive measures are in place to manage emergencies. The centre is equipped to provide immediate care and stabilisation in the 'golden hour'. The golden hour in emergency care means the first sixty minutes after an injury or illness when medical care may be most effective.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/uae/expo-2020-dubai-emergency-centre-to-provide-olympic-quality-care-to-visitors-1.894928|title=Expo 2020 Dubai emergency centre to provide 'Olympic quality' care to visitors|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=August 5, 2019|work=The National|access-date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Developments==\nIn November 2019, the UAE permitted [[Israel]]i passport holders to enter the country during Expo 2020. Israelis were allowed to have their own pavilion at the event and to even visit the country afterwards.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5620240,00.html|title=Dubai to open its doors to Israeli tourists in 2020|accessdate=6 November 2019|website=Yedioth Ahronoth}}</ref>\n\nA French luxury brand [[Cartier (jeweler)|Cartier]] was expected to set up a women centric pavilion in association with prominent [[human rights]] lawyer [[Amal Clooney]], in October 2020. Clooney was to lend her voice to the initiative to discuss the role of women in society and ways to tackle [[gender inequality]], while celebrating female achievers.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/culture/featured-news/amal-clooney-joins-cartier-for-for-dubai-expo-2020-pavillion|title=Amal Clooney Partners With Cartier To Empower Women At Dubai Expo 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020|website=Harper\u2019s Bazaar Arabia}}</ref>\n\n===Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic===\nIn 2020, the globally expanding [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] brought Expo 2020 Dubai under questions, as the event was expected to attract nearly 25 million visitors in October that year.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b7a7902a-68ff-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3|title=Gulf economies rocked by coronavirus and oil price war|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=Financial Times}}</ref> In March, the Geneva Council for Rights and Liberties warned against the abuse and exploitation of [[migrant workers in the United Arab Emirates]]. While rest of the country was under a lockdown due to the spread of coronavirus, the migrants continued to work on Expo 2020. The Geneva Council condemned the \u201cdiscriminatory treatment of migrant workers\u201d, urging the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] to encourage the [[UAE]] to ensure their health and safety.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-uk-migrant-workers-overseas-human-rights-covid-19-a9426086.html|title=Coronavirus: Migrant workers in UK and overseas face \u2018disproportionate risk\u2019 from Covid-19|accessdate=26 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2020 the expo indicated that it was investigating postponement of the world's fair. An event that would require a two third's majority agreement from a BIE annual general meeting.<ref name=\"March30post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.expo2020dubai.com/en/expo-covid-19|access-date=30 March 2020|title=Expo 2020 Dubai and the UAE response to COVID-19 &#124; Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref> On 4 April 2020 the BIE announced that a meeting of the executive committee would take place virtually on 21 April to discuss a proposal to hold the expo between 1 October 2021 and 31 March 2022.<ref name=\"BIEpostpone1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/news-announcements/expo-dubai-2020-2/bie-convenes-21-april-meeting-of-its-executive-committee-to-discuss-change-of-dates-for-expo-2020-dubai|access-date=5 April 2020|title=BIE convenes 21 April meeting of its Executive Committee to discuss change of dates for Expo 2020 Dubai}}</ref> A final decision would need a two third's majority vote from BIE members.<ref name=\"BIEpostpone1\" />\n\nOn 21 April the executive committee unanimously to delay the expo until 1 October 2021 \u2013 31 March 2022,<ref name=Unambie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/news-announcements/expo-dubai-2020-2/bie-executive-committee-proposes-postponement-of-expo-2020-dubai-member-states-to-vote-on-change-of-dates\n|access-date=21 April 2020|title=BIE Executive Committee proposes postponement of Expo 2020 Dubai, Member States to vote on change of dates}}</ref> with this now{{Update after|2020|05|30}} going to a remote vote of the general assembly.<ref name=Unambie\" /> There is no proposal to change the name of the expo.<ref name=Unambie\" />\n\n==Bids and bidding==\nOnce  the first city had lodged a bid with the BIE, other cities had six months to respond. In early 2011, Izmir of Turkey and Ayutthaya of Thailand submitted bids to the BIE, initiating the six-month window for other cities to bid. When this window closed on 2 November 2011, there were five prospective cities, with Dubai making a last minute entry. The BIE voted and selected the host city on 27 November 2013.\n\nFive cities originally bid for the slot for a world's fair in 2020, with four remaining: Dubai, United Arab Emirates; Yekaterinburg, Russia; Izmir, Turkey; or S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil. Expo 2020 will represent a first as a Middle Eastern destination will be hosting the event for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expomuseum.com/2020/ |title=ExpoMuseum / Expo 2020, Ayutthaya, Thailand; Dubai, USA; Izmir, Turkey; Sao Paulo, Brazil; or Yekaterinburg, Russia |publisher=Expomuseum.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>\n\nThe following cities lodged bids to the BIE for hosting the 2020 EXPO:\n* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Izmir]], [[Turkey]]\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/business/20110802/165518448.html |title=Russia to propose Yekaterinburg as Expo 2020 venue &#124; Business &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/430-yekaterinburg-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Yekaterinburg, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prefeitura.sp.gov.br/cidade/secretarias/relacoes_internacionais/noticias/?p=13802 |title=Portal da Prefeitura da Cidade de S\u00e3o Paulo |publisher=Prefeitura.sp.gov.br |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/431-sao-paulo-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Sao Paulo, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|UAE}} [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlingske.dk/article/20080612/koebenhavn/80612042/ |title=K\u00f8benhavn vil huse verdensudstilling &#124; www.b.dk |publisher=Berlingske.dk |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>\nS\u00e3o Paulo was eliminated from contention after the first round of votes. Izmir was knocked out in the second. Yekaterinburg lost to Dubai in the third and final round of voting.\n\n===Dubai Expo===\nUAE selected the theme \"Connecting Minds, Creating the Future\", sub-themes being Sustainability, Mobility and Opportunity.<ref>{{cite web |author=Maeve Hosea |url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/expo_2020_dubai_celebrates_in_style |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: Dubai celebrates in style |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=2013-11-28 |accessdate=2015-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223140241/http://vision.ae/en/articles/expo_2020_dubai_celebrates_in_style |archive-date=December 23, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=His Highness Sheikh Ahmed bin Saeed Al Maktoum January 2015 |url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/world_expo_from_vision_to_victory |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: From vision to victory |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=January 2014 |accessdate=2015-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027092626/http://vision.ae/en/articles/world_expo_from_vision_to_victory |archive-date=October 27, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n\"In today\u2019s highly interconnected world, a renewed vision of progress and development based on shared purpose and commitment is key. While a married human mind, an individual country, or a specific community is both unique and remarkable, it is by working collaboratively that we truly advance.\" Dubai Ruler [[Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]] said in support of the bid.\n\nThe World Expo in Dubai in 2020 will be the first to be held in the [[MENA]] & SA (Middle East and North Africa & South Asia) region.\nOn 27 November 2013, when Dubai won the right to host the expo 2020, fireworks erupted at the world's tallest building, [[Burj Khalifa]]. A national holiday was declared the following day for all educational institutions across the country. The Dubai Ruler promised Dubai would \"astonish the world,\" in 2020. The staging of the world fair and the preparations leading up to it are expected to result in 277,000 new jobs in the UAE, an injection of nearly $40 billion into the economy, and an increase in visitors of at least 25 million and up to 100 million.<ref name=\"Expo 2020 Dubai\">{{cite web|title=Dubai wins right to host Expo 2020|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/economy/dubai-expo-2020-would-support-277-000-jobs-1.1181465|accessdate=28 November 2013|publisher=Gulf News}}</ref> Director General of Dubai Municipality, Hussain Nasser Lootah, said that they have the largest laboratory in the region, and can easily research new materials and technologies required for construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/business/economy-finance/dubai-is-ready-to-deal-with-expo-2020-construction-boom-lootah-2014-11-19-1.570636 |title=Dubai is ready to deal with Expo 2020 construction boom: Lootah \u2013 Emirates 24&#124;7 |work=Emirates247.com |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2015-09-19}}</ref> The world's tallest commercial tower to be built in Dubai, in [[Jumeirah Lake Towers]], was given the name \"Burj 2020\" in honour of the World Expo 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmcc.ae/content-page?Turner-to-Project-Manage-Burj2020&articleid=a051000000UWFsnAAH|title=Turner to Project Manage Burj 2020|publisher=DMCC|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> [[Hamdan bin Mohammed Al Maktoum]] also went to the top floor of the [[Burj Khalifa]] to wave the UAE flag, a few days after the World Expo 2020 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20131128/ARTICLE/311289967/1036|title=Shaikh Hamdan waves UAE flag from top of Burj Khalifa \u2013 Khaleej Times|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Yekaterinburg Expo===\nThe Russian bid ''The Global Mind'' would have run from May 1 to October 31, and would have been the second largest expo (after [[Expo 2010|2010]] in Shanghai) and intended to  \"survey world opinion through seven universal questions\".<ref name=\"Ekaterinburg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/ekaterinburg-russia|accessdate=17 November 2013|title=Ekaterinburg \u2013 Russia}}</ref>\n\n===\u0130zmir Expo===\nThe Turkish bid had a theme of ''New Routes to a Better World / Health for All'' and would have run from April 30 to October 31.<ref name=\"bieizmir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/izmir-turkey|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Izmir \u2013 Turkey}}</ref> A ''Health for All'' symposium was held in October 2013 for BIE delegates and was to discuss health issues across the world.<ref name=\"h4asymposium\">{{cite web|url=http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Health For All Symposium|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034410/http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===S\u00e3o Paulo Expo===\nA Brazilian expo would have been called ''Power of Diversity, Harmony for Growth'',<ref name=\"saopself\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saopauloexpo2020.com.br/?page_id=718&lang=en|accessdate=28 November 2013|title=The theme  \u2013  S\u00e3o Paulo Expo 2020}}</ref> run from May 15 to November 15 and would have covered 502 hectares.<ref name=\"biesaop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/sao-paulo-brazil|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Sao Paulo \u2013 Brazil}}</ref>\n\n==Ticket prices==\nThe normal 1-day tickets for the expo cost AED 120, while the 3-day tickets are AED 260. There is a 50% discount on entry for students of any age and youth aged 6 to 17. The expo gives free access to kids up to 5 years and adults 65 years & above. Disabled persons are also allowed free entry and a caregiver can also visit with them at half the ticket price.''<ref name=\"tickets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.globalmediainsight.com/blog/dubai-expo-2020-facts-and-statistics|accessdate=16 December 2019|title=Dubai Expo 2020 Facts and Statistics}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://expo2020dubai.com}}\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/2020-dubai Expo 2020 page at the BIE]\n*[http://www.epo.org/law-practice/legal-texts/official-journal/2016/etc/se4/p219.html European Patent Office]\n*[http://www.ExpoBids.com/ ExpoBids.com] Noticias sobre las Ofertas de la Feria Mundial de Todo El Mundo.\n*[http://www.studylove.org/worldsfairs19.html#2020 2020 Dubai (BIE World Expo)] \u2013 approximately 95 links\n*[http://www.youtube.com/user/DubaiExpo2020 Expo 2020 Dubai] - YouTube User\n*[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7UDxQqPZBSI Emarati (Dubai Expo 2020 Song)] - YouTube, music video, 3m50s\n*[https://profounduae.com/impact-of-expo-2020-on-uae-business/ Impact of EXPO 2020 on UAE Business]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n\n[[Category:2020 festivals]]\n[[Category:Scheduled events]]\n[[Category:Events in Dubai]]\n[[Category:World's fairs in Asia|UAE]]\n[[Category:2020s in Dubai]]\n", "name_user": "THEunique", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo_2020"}
{"title_page": "Occitano-Romance languages", "text_new": "{{Expand Aragonese|Luengas occitano-romances|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand Catalan|Lleng\u00fces occitanorom\u00e0niques|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand French|Langues occitano-romanes|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Lenguas occitanorromances|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox language family\n  |name=Occitano-Romance\n  |altname=[[Gallia_Narbonensis|'''Narbonensis dialect''']]\n  |region=[[France]], [[Spain]], [[Andorra]], [[Monaco]], parts of [[Italy]]\n  |familycolor=Indo-European\n  |fam2=[[Italic languages|Italic]]\n  |fam3=[[Romance languages|Romance]]\n  |fam4=[[Western Romance languages|Western Romance]]\n  |fam5=[[Gallo-Romance languages|Gallo-Romance]]\n  |child1=[[Occitan language|Occitan]] (including [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]] and [[Gascon language|Gascon]], sometimes classified as separate languages)\n  |child2=[[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n  |glotto=none\n  |map = Ibero orientales.PNG\n  |mapcaption = Occitano-Romance languages and dialects\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#D8BFD8|[[Vivaro-Alpine]]}}\n{{legend|#EE82EE|[[Auvergnat]]}}\n{{legend|#DA70D6|[[Limousin dialect|Limousin]]}}\n{{legend|#9370DB|[[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]}}\n{{legend|#9400D3|[[Lengadocian]]}}\n{{legend|#8B008B|[[Gascon language|Gascon]]}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#DC143C|[[Balearic dialect|Balearic]]}}\n{{legend|#B22222|[[Algherese]]}}\n{{legend|#8B0000|[[Northern Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|[[Central Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF4500|[[Northwestern Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF8C00|[[Valencian]]}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#FFA07A|[[Ribagor\u00e7an]]}}\n{{col-end}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Occitano-Romance''' or '''Gallo-Narbonnese''' ({{lang-ca|'''lleng\u00fces occitanorom\u00e0niques'''}}, {{lang-oc|'''lengas occitanoromanicas'''}}) is a branch of the [[Romance languages|Romance language group]] that encompasses the [[Catalan language|Catalan]] and [[Occitan language|Occitan]] languages spoken in parts of southern [[France]] and northeastern [[Spain]].<ref>\"Mas se confrontam los parlars naturals de Catalonha e d'Occitania, i a pas cap de dobte, em en pres\u00e9ncia de parlars d'una meteissa familha linguistica, la qu'ai qualificada d'occitano-romana, pla\u00e7ada a egala dist\u00e0ncia entre lo franc\u00e9s e l'espanh\u00f2l.\" Lo\u00eds Alib\u00e8rt, ''\u00d2c'', n\u00b07 (01/1950), p. 26</ref> [[Aragonese language|Aragonese]], a [[West Iberian languages|West Iberian language]], is sometimes also included due to the significant influence from the group.\n\n==Extent==\nThe group covers the languages of the southern part of [[France]] ([[Occitania]] including [[Northern Catalonia]]), eastern [[Spain]] ([[Catalonia]], [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencian Community]], [[Balearic Islands]], [[La Franja]], [[Carche]]), together with [[Andorra]], [[Monaco]], parts of [[Italy]] ([[Occitan Valleys]], [[Alghero]], [[Guardia Piemontese]]), and historically in the [[County of Tripoli]] and the possessions of the [[Crown of Aragon]]. The existence of this group of languages is discussed on both linguistic and political bases.\n\n==Classification==\nAccording to some linguists both [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Catalan language|Catalan]] should be considered [[Gallo-Romance languages]]. Other linguists concur as regarding Occitan but consider Catalan to be part of the [[Iberian Romance languages|Ibero-Romance languages]].\n\nThe issue at debate is as political as it is linguistic because the division into [[Gallo-Romance]] and [[Ibero-Romance languages]] stems from the current nation states of [[France]] and [[Spain]] and so is based more on territorial criteria than historic and linguistic criteria. One of the main proponents of the unity of the languages of the [[Iberian Peninsula]] was Spanish philologist [[Ram\u00f3n Men\u00e9ndez Pidal]], and for a long time, others such as Swiss linguist [[Wilhelm Meyer-L\u00fcbke]] (''Das Katalanische'', Heidelberg, 1925) have supported the kinship of [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Catalan language|Catalan]].\n\nFrom the 8th century to the 13th century, there was no clear linguistic distinction between Occitania and Catalonia. For instance, the [[Provence|Proven\u00e7al]]  [[troubadour]], [[Albertet de Sestaro|Albertet de Sestar\u00f3]], says: \"Monks, tell me which according to your knowledge are better: the French or the Catalans? and here I shall put Gascony, Provence, Limousin, Auvergne and Viennois while there shall be the land of the two kings.\"<ref>''Monges, causetz, segons vostre siensa qual valon mais, catalan ho franc\u00e9s?/ E met de sai Guascuenha e Proensa/ E lemoz\u00ed, alvernh\u2019 e vian\u00e9s/ E de lai met la terra dels dos reis.''</ref> In [[Marseille]], a typical Proven\u00e7al song is called 'Catalan song'.<ref name=\"Fontanals1861\">{{cite book|author=Manuel Mil\u00e1 y Fontanals|title=De los trovadores en Espa\u00f1a: Estudio de lengua y poes\u00eda provenzal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0EPQAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA14|year=1861|publisher=J. Verdaguer|page=14}}</ref>\n\n==Internal variation==\n[[File:Bec supradialectal.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Supradialectal classification of Occitano-Romance according to P. Bec]]\n[[File:Sumien supradialectal.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Supradialectal classification of Occitano-Romance according to D. Sumien]]\nMost linguists separate Catalan and Occitan, but both languages have been treated as one in studies by Occitan linguists attempting to classify the dialects of Occitan in [[supradialectal]] groups, such is the case of [[Pierre Bec]]<ref>Pierre BEC (1973), ''Manuel pratique d\u2019occitan moderne'', coll. Connaissance des langues, Paris: Picard</ref> and, more recently, of [[Domergue Sumien]].<ref>Domergue SUMIEN (2006), ''La standardisation pluricentrique de l'occitan: nouvel enjeu sociolinguistique, d\u00e9veloppement du lexique et de la morphologie'', coll. Publications de l'Association Internationale d'\u00c9tudes Occitanes, Turnhout: Brepols</ref>\n\nBoth join together in an Aquitano-Pyrenean or Pre-Iberian group including Catalan, Gascon and a part of [[Languedocien|Languedocian]], leaving the rest of Occitan in one (Sumien: Arverno-Mediterranean) or two groups (Bec: Arverno-Mediterranean, Central Occitan\n\n== Linguistic variation ==\n\n=== Lexical comparison ===\n\nVariations in the spellings and pronunciations of numbers in several Occitano-Romance dialects<ref>{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212044805/http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/Indoeuro.htm|date=20120212044805|title=Indo-European numerals (Eugene Chan)}}</ref><ref>[[:an:Cardinals_en_l%27aragon%C3%A9s|Cardinals en l'argon\u00e9s]]</ref>:\n\n:{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n|-\n! rowspan=3|<small>Numeral</small>\n! colspan=5| '''[[Occitan language|Occitan]]'''\n! colspan=2| '''[[Catalan language|Catalan]]'''\n! rowspan=3| '''[[Aragonese language|Aragonese]]'''<ref> {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421202355/http://maldelenguas.blogspot.com/2012/05/los-numeros-en-aragones-los-cardinales.html|date=20190421202355|title=Los n\u00fameros en aragon\u00e9s: Cardinales}} </ref>\n! rowspan=3|<small>PROTO-</small><br>OcRm\n|-\n! colspan=2|Northern Occitan \n! colspan=1|Western Occitan \n! colspan=2|Eastern Occitan \n! rowspan=2|[[Catalan dialects|Eastern Catalan]]\n! rowspan=2|[[Catalan dialects|Northwestern Catalan]]\n|-\n![[Auvergnat]] !! [[Limousin dialect|Limousin]]\n! colspan=1|[[Gascon language|Gascon]]\n![[Languedocien dialect|Languedocien]] !! [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]\n|-\n| 1 || vyn / vyn\u0250<br>''vun'' / ''vun\u00e5'' || \u1ef9 / yn\u0254<br>''un'' / ''una''\n| y / yo<br>''un'' / ''ua''\n| \u1ef9 / yno<br>''un'' / ''una'' || y\u014b / yno<br>''un'' / ''una''\n| un / un\u0259<br>''un'' / ''una'' \n|un / una\n''un'' / ''una''\n| un~uno / una<br>''un~uno'' / ''una'' || *un / *una\n|-\n| 2 || du / dua<br>''dou'' / ''duas'' || du / dua<br>''dos'' / ''doas''\n| dys / dyos<br>''dus'' / ''duas''\n| dus / duos<br>''dos'' / ''doas'' || dus / duas<br>''dous'' / ''douas''\n| dos / du\u0259s<br>''dos'' / ''dues'' \n|dos \n''dos'' / ''dues''\n| dos / duas<br>''dos'' / ''duas'' || *dos~dus /<br> *duas\n|-\n| 3 || t\u0280ei<br>''trei'' || trei<br>''tres''\n| tres<br>''tres''\n| tres<br>''tres'' || t\u0280es<br>''tres''\n| tr\u025bs<br>''tres'' \n|tr\u025bs<br>''tres''|| t\u027ees<br>''tres'' || *tres\n|-\n| 4 || kat\u0280\u0259<br>''catre'' || katre<br>''quatre''\n| kwat\u0259<br>''quatre''\n| katre<br>''quatre'' || kat\u0280\u0259<br>''quatre''\n| kwatr\u0259<br>''quatre'' \n|kwatre\n''quatre''\n| kwatro~kwatre<br>''quatro / quatre'' || *kwatre\n|-\n| 5 || \u0283in<br>''sin'' || \u0283in<br>''cinc''\n| si\u014bk<br>''cinq''\n| si\u014bk<br>''cinq'' || si\u014b<br>''cinq''\n| si\u014b / si\u014bk<br>''cinc'' \n|si\u014b / si\u014bk<br>''cinc''|| \u03b8i\u014bko~\u03b8i\u014bk<br>''cinco / cinc'' || *si\u014bk\n|-\n| 6 || \u0283ei<br>''siei'' || \u0283iei<br>''sieis''\n| \u0283eis<br>''sheis''\n| si\u025bis<br>''si\u00e8is'' || siei<br>''sieis''\n| sis<br>''sis'' \n|sis\n''sis''\n| seis~sieis<br>''seis / sieis''  || *sieis\n|-\n| 7 || se<br>''s\u00e9'' || \u0283e<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''s\u00e8t'' || s\u025b<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''set'' \n|s\u025bt<br>''set''|| siet~s\u025bt<br>''siet / set'' || *s\u025bt\n|-\n| 8 || v\u00f8<br>''veu'' || j\u0265e<br>''u\u00e8ch''\n| weit<br>''ueit''\n| \u0265e\u02a7<br>''u\u00e8ch'' || v\u0265e<br>''vue''\n| buit / vuit<br>''vuit'' \n|vuit / wit\n''vuit'' / ''huit''\n| weito~weit<br>''ueito / ueit'' || *weit\n|-\n| 9 || ni\u00f8~nou<br>''nieu''~''nou'' || n\u0254u<br>''n\u00f2u''\n| nau<br>''nau''\n| n\u0254u<br>''n\u00f2u'' || nu<br>''n\u00f2u''\n| n\u0254u<br>''nou'' \n|n\u0254u<br>''nou''|| nweu~n\u0254u<br>''nueu / nou'' || *n\u0254u\n|-\n| 10 || die~de<br>''di\u00e9''~''d\u00e9'' || di\u025b~de<br>''detz''\n| d\u025b\u02a6<br>''d\u00e8tz''\n| d\u025b\u02a6<br>''d\u00e8ts'' || d\u025bs<br>''d\u00e8s''\n| d\u025bu<br>''deu'' \n|d\u025bu<br>''deu''|| die\u03b8~deu<br>''diez'' / ''deu'' || *d\u025b\u02a6\n|}\n\nThe numbers 1 and 2 have both feminine and masculine forms agreeing with the object they modify.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occitano-Romance Languages}}\n[[Category:Occitano-Romance languages|Occitano-Romance languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of France|Languages of France]]\n[[Category:Languages of Spain ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Aragonese|Luengas occitano-romances|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand Catalan|Lleng\u00fces occitanorom\u00e0niques|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand French|Langues occitano-romanes|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand Occitan|Occitanoromanic|date=April 2020}}\n{{Expand Spanish|Lenguas occitanorromances|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox language family\n  |name=Occitano-Romance\n  |altname=[[Gallia_Narbonensis|'''Narbonensis dialect''']]\n  |region=[[France]], [[Spain]], [[Andorra]], [[Monaco]], parts of [[Italy]]\n  |familycolor=Indo-European\n  |fam2=[[Italic languages|Italic]]\n  |fam3=[[Romance languages|Romance]]\n  |fam4=[[Western Romance languages|Western Romance]]\n  |fam5=[[Gallo-Romance languages|Gallo-Romance]]\n  |child1=[[Occitan language|Occitan]] (including [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]] and [[Gascon language|Gascon]], sometimes classified as separate languages)\n  |child2=[[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n  |glotto=none\n  |map = Ibero orientales.PNG\n  |mapcaption = Occitano-Romance languages and dialects\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#D8BFD8|[[Vivaro-Alpine]]}}\n{{legend|#EE82EE|[[Auvergnat]]}}\n{{legend|#DA70D6|[[Limousin dialect|Limousin]]}}\n{{legend|#9370DB|[[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]}}\n{{legend|#9400D3|[[Lengadocian]]}}\n{{legend|#8B008B|[[Gascon language|Gascon]]}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#DC143C|[[Balearic dialect|Balearic]]}}\n{{legend|#B22222|[[Algherese]]}}\n{{legend|#8B0000|[[Northern Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|[[Central Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF4500|[[Northwestern Catalan]]}}\n{{legend|#FF8C00|[[Valencian]]}}\n{{col-3}}\n{{legend|#FFA07A|[[Ribagor\u00e7an]]}}\n{{col-end}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Occitano-Romance''' or '''Gallo-Narbonnese''' ({{lang-ca|'''lleng\u00fces occitanorom\u00e0niques'''}}, {{lang-oc|'''lengas occitanoromanicas'''}}) is a branch of the [[Romance languages|Romance language group]] that encompasses the [[Catalan language|Catalan]] and [[Occitan language|Occitan]] languages spoken in parts of southern [[France]] and northeastern [[Spain]].<ref>\"Mas se confrontam los parlars naturals de Catalonha e d'Occitania, i a pas cap de dobte, em en pres\u00e9ncia de parlars d'una meteissa familha linguistica, la qu'ai qualificada d'occitano-romana, pla\u00e7ada a egala dist\u00e0ncia entre lo franc\u00e9s e l'espanh\u00f2l.\" Lo\u00eds Alib\u00e8rt, ''\u00d2c'', n\u00b07 (01/1950), p. 26</ref> [[Aragonese language|Aragonese]], a [[West Iberian languages|West Iberian language]], is sometimes also included due to the significant influence from the group.\n\n==Extent==\nThe group covers the languages of the southern part of [[France]] ([[Occitania]] including [[Northern Catalonia]]), eastern [[Spain]] ([[Catalonia]], [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencian Community]], [[Balearic Islands]], [[La Franja]], [[Carche]]), together with [[Andorra]], [[Monaco]], parts of [[Italy]] ([[Occitan Valleys]], [[Alghero]], [[Guardia Piemontese]]), and historically in the [[County of Tripoli]] and the possessions of the [[Crown of Aragon]]. The existence of this group of languages is discussed on both linguistic and political bases.\n\n==Classification==\nAccording to some linguists both [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Catalan language|Catalan]] should be considered [[Gallo-Romance languages]]. Other linguists concur as regarding Occitan but consider Catalan to be part of the [[Iberian Romance languages|Ibero-Romance languages]].\n\nThe issue at debate is as political as it is linguistic because the division into [[Gallo-Romance]] and [[Ibero-Romance languages]] stems from the current nation states of [[France]] and [[Spain]] and so is based more on territorial criteria than historic and linguistic criteria. One of the main proponents of the unity of the languages of the [[Iberian Peninsula]] was Spanish philologist [[Ram\u00f3n Men\u00e9ndez Pidal]], and for a long time, others such as Swiss linguist [[Wilhelm Meyer-L\u00fcbke]] (''Das Katalanische'', Heidelberg, 1925) have supported the kinship of [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Catalan language|Catalan]].\n\nFrom the 8th century to the 13th century, there was no clear linguistic distinction between Occitania and Catalonia. For instance, the [[Provence|Proven\u00e7al]]  [[troubadour]], [[Albertet de Sestaro|Albertet de Sestar\u00f3]], says: \"Monks, tell me which according to your knowledge are better: the French or the Catalans? and here I shall put Gascony, Provence, Limousin, Auvergne and Viennois while there shall be the land of the two kings.\"<ref>''Monges, causetz, segons vostre siensa qual valon mais, catalan ho franc\u00e9s?/ E met de sai Guascuenha e Proensa/ E lemoz\u00ed, alvernh\u2019 e vian\u00e9s/ E de lai met la terra dels dos reis.''</ref> In [[Marseille]], a typical Proven\u00e7al song is called 'Catalan song'.<ref name=\"Fontanals1861\">{{cite book|author=Manuel Mil\u00e1 y Fontanals|title=De los trovadores en Espa\u00f1a: Estudio de lengua y poes\u00eda provenzal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0EPQAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA14|year=1861|publisher=J. Verdaguer|page=14}}</ref>\n\n==Internal variation==\n[[File:Bec supradialectal.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Supradialectal classification of Occitano-Romance according to P. Bec]]\n[[File:Sumien supradialectal.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Supradialectal classification of Occitano-Romance according to D. Sumien]]\nMost linguists separate Catalan and Occitan, but both languages have been treated as one in studies by Occitan linguists attempting to classify the dialects of Occitan in [[supradialectal]] groups, such is the case of [[Pierre Bec]]<ref>Pierre BEC (1973), ''Manuel pratique d\u2019occitan moderne'', coll. Connaissance des langues, Paris: Picard</ref> and, more recently, of [[Domergue Sumien]].<ref>Domergue SUMIEN (2006), ''La standardisation pluricentrique de l'occitan: nouvel enjeu sociolinguistique, d\u00e9veloppement du lexique et de la morphologie'', coll. Publications de l'Association Internationale d'\u00c9tudes Occitanes, Turnhout: Brepols</ref>\n\nBoth join together in an Aquitano-Pyrenean or Pre-Iberian group including Catalan, Gascon and a part of [[Languedocien|Languedocian]], leaving the rest of Occitan in one (Sumien: Arverno-Mediterranean) or two groups (Bec: Arverno-Mediterranean, Central Occitan\n\n== Linguistic variation ==\n\n=== Lexical comparison ===\n\nVariations in the spellings and pronunciations of numbers in several Occitano-Romance dialects<ref>{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212044805/http://lingweb.eva.mpg.de/numeral/Indoeuro.htm|date=20120212044805|title=Indo-European numerals (Eugene Chan)}}</ref><ref>[[:an:Cardinals_en_l%27aragon%C3%A9s|Cardinals en l'argon\u00e9s]]</ref>:\n\n:{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n|-\n! rowspan=3|<small>Numeral</small>\n! colspan=5| '''[[Occitan language|Occitan]]'''\n! colspan=2| '''[[Catalan language|Catalan]]'''\n! rowspan=3| '''[[Aragonese language|Aragonese]]'''<ref> {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421202355/http://maldelenguas.blogspot.com/2012/05/los-numeros-en-aragones-los-cardinales.html|date=20190421202355|title=Los n\u00fameros en aragon\u00e9s: Cardinales}} </ref>\n! rowspan=3|<small>PROTO-</small><br>OcRm\n|-\n! colspan=2|Northern Occitan \n! colspan=1|Western Occitan \n! colspan=2|Eastern Occitan \n! rowspan=2|[[Catalan dialects|Eastern Catalan]]\n! rowspan=2|[[Catalan dialects|Northwestern Catalan]]\n|-\n![[Auvergnat]] !! [[Limousin dialect|Limousin]]\n! colspan=1|[[Gascon language|Gascon]]\n![[Languedocien dialect|Languedocien]] !! [[Proven\u00e7al dialect|Proven\u00e7al]]\n|-\n| 1 || vyn / vyn\u0250<br>''vun'' / ''vun\u00e5'' || \u1ef9 / yn\u0254<br>''un'' / ''una''\n| y / yo<br>''un'' / ''ua''\n| \u1ef9 / yno<br>''un'' / ''una'' || y\u014b / yno<br>''un'' / ''una''\n| un / un\u0259<br>''un'' / ''una'' \n|un / una\n''un'' / ''una''\n| un~uno / una<br>''un~uno'' / ''una'' || *un / *una\n|-\n| 2 || du / dua<br>''dou'' / ''duas'' || du / dua<br>''dos'' / ''doas''\n| dys / dyos<br>''dus'' / ''duas''\n| dus / duos<br>''dos'' / ''doas'' || dus / duas<br>''dous'' / ''douas''\n| dos / du\u0259s<br>''dos'' / ''dues'' \n|dos \n''dos'' / ''dues''\n| dos / duas<br>''dos'' / ''duas'' || *dos~dus /<br> *duas\n|-\n| 3 || t\u0280ei<br>''trei'' || trei<br>''tres''\n| tres<br>''tres''\n| tres<br>''tres'' || t\u0280es<br>''tres''\n| tr\u025bs<br>''tres'' \n|tr\u025bs<br>''tres''|| t\u027ees<br>''tres'' || *tres\n|-\n| 4 || kat\u0280\u0259<br>''catre'' || katre<br>''quatre''\n| kwat\u0259<br>''quatre''\n| katre<br>''quatre'' || kat\u0280\u0259<br>''quatre''\n| kwatr\u0259<br>''quatre'' \n|kwatre\n''quatre''\n| kwatro~kwatre<br>''quatro / quatre'' || *kwatre\n|-\n| 5 || \u0283in<br>''sin'' || \u0283in<br>''cinc''\n| si\u014bk<br>''cinq''\n| si\u014bk<br>''cinq'' || si\u014b<br>''cinq''\n| si\u014b / si\u014bk<br>''cinc'' \n|si\u014b / si\u014bk<br>''cinc''|| \u03b8i\u014bko~\u03b8i\u014bk<br>''cinco / cinc'' || *si\u014bk\n|-\n| 6 || \u0283ei<br>''siei'' || \u0283iei<br>''sieis''\n| \u0283eis<br>''sheis''\n| si\u025bis<br>''si\u00e8is'' || siei<br>''sieis''\n| sis<br>''sis'' \n|sis\n''sis''\n| seis~sieis<br>''seis / sieis''  || *sieis\n|-\n| 7 || se<br>''s\u00e9'' || \u0283e<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''s\u00e8t'' || s\u025b<br>''s\u00e8t''\n| s\u025bt<br>''set'' \n|s\u025bt<br>''set''|| siet~s\u025bt<br>''siet / set'' || *s\u025bt\n|-\n| 8 || v\u00f8<br>''veu'' || j\u0265e<br>''u\u00e8ch''\n| weit<br>''ueit''\n| \u0265e\u02a7<br>''u\u00e8ch'' || v\u0265e<br>''vue''\n| buit / vuit<br>''vuit'' \n|vuit / wit\n''vuit'' / ''huit''\n| weito~weit<br>''ueito / ueit'' || *weit\n|-\n| 9 || ni\u00f8~nou<br>''nieu''~''nou'' || n\u0254u<br>''n\u00f2u''\n| nau<br>''nau''\n| n\u0254u<br>''n\u00f2u'' || nu<br>''n\u00f2u''\n| n\u0254u<br>''nou'' \n|n\u0254u<br>''nou''|| nweu~n\u0254u<br>''nueu / nou'' || *n\u0254u\n|-\n| 10 || die~de<br>''di\u00e9''~''d\u00e9'' || di\u025b~de<br>''detz''\n| d\u025b\u02a6<br>''d\u00e8tz''\n| d\u025b\u02a6<br>''d\u00e8ts'' || d\u025bs<br>''d\u00e8s''\n| d\u025bu<br>''deu'' \n|d\u025bu<br>''deu''|| die\u03b8~deu<br>''diez'' / ''deu'' || *d\u025b\u02a6\n|}\n\nThe numbers 1 and 2 have both feminine and masculine forms agreeing with the object they modify.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occitano-Romance Languages}}\n[[Category:Occitano-Romance languages|Occitano-Romance languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of France|Languages of France]]\n[[Category:Languages of Spain ]]\n", "name_user": "AquitaneHungerForce", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed Expand Occitan, template is missing and that article appears to have little not already in this article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Occitano-Romance_languages"}
{"title_page": "Pan American Development Foundation", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name = Pan American Development Foundation\n| logo = \n| Non-profit_type = [[Non-governmental organization]]\n| size = \n| abbreviation = PADF\n| founded = 1962\n| type = International Development Organization\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]<!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| area_served = [[Latin America]], [[Caribbean]]\n| founder = Ronald Scheman\n| key_people = Katie Taylor, Executive Director<ref>{{cite web |title=PADF Selects New Executive Director: Catarina \"Katie\" Taylor |url=https://www.padf.org/news/padf-selects-new-executive-director-catarina-katie-taylor |website=Pan American Development Foundation |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n| website = [http://www.padf.org www.padf.org]\n}}\nThe '''Pan American Development Foundation''' ('''PADF''') is a non-governmental and non-political organization created in 1962 by the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS), the public sector and the private sector to focus on issues of pressing concern in the Western Hemisphere. PADF, a non-profit organization, has worked in every country in the region. PADF aims to bring together stakeholders to create sustainable economic development, strengthen civil society and respond to natural disasters for the most disadvantaged people in Latin America and the Caribbean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.padf.org/ht/d/sp/i/29319/pid/29319 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009234203/http://www.padf.org/ht/d/sp/i/29319/pid/29319 |archivedate=2010-10-09 }}</ref>\n\nPADF, which also works to support the principles of the Inter-American Democratic Charter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/OASpage/eng/Documents/Democractic_Charter.htm|title=Democratic Charter|website=www.oas.org}}</ref> is an independent affiliate of the OAS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/|title=OAS - Organization of American States: Democracy for peace, security, and development|first=|last=OAS|date=1 August 2009|website=www.oas.org}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe PADF was established in 1962, by the Organization of American States (OAS), as part of the [[Alliance for Progress]] initiated by U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]]. It was created through a cooperative agreement between the OAS and private enterprise to provide a specialized non-governmental organization to assist the least advantaged people in Latin America and the Caribbean. Since its creation, PADF has implanted development programs throughout the Western Hemisphere carrying out the goals set forth by the OAS.\n\nIn 1975, OAS named PADF a \u201cspecial purpose foundation\u201d achieving consultative status with the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.padf.org/pages/history |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106183350/http://www.padf.org/pages/history |archivedate=2013-01-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\nIn keeping with its mission to create \u201ca Hemisphere of Opportunity for All,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.padf.org/programs|title=Create Economic Opportunities|website=PADF}}</ref> PADF implements a range of different programs, reaching millions of people in Latin American and the Caribbean. The programs are divided into four areas of development.\n\n===Economic opportunity programs===\nPADF implements economic opportunity programs with the focus of improving the livelihoods of disadvantaged individuals and families. The programs include support for micro and medium-size businesses, skills training for youth and vulnerable groups, improving agricultural conditions and techniques, and expanding or improving local infrastructure.\n\n====LEAD program====\nIn 2012, PADF implemented the Leveraging Effective Application of Direct Investment (LEAD) program with $13 million in funding from the [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID). The LEAD program is a business plan competition which awards grants to small and medium enterprises. The grants range from $50,000 to $200,000 and must be matched be the grantee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haitilibre.com/en/news-7939-haiti-economy-2nd-edition-of-business-plan-competition.html|title=Haiti - Economy : 2nd Edition of Business Plan Competition - HaitiLibre.com : Haiti news 7/7|website=haitilibre.com}}</ref>\n\nPADF announced the launch of the second edition of the LEAD Program on February 20, 2013. Following the launch of the second round, a group of Haitian businesses, which had been awarded LEAD grants, participated in a business and investment seminar at [[Columbia University]]. The event is part of a series of investment events and conferences that the businesses are participating in throughout the United States, Canada and the Dominican Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/03/19/haiti-small-businesses-launch-road-show-tour-of-us-dominican-republic/|title=Haiti: Small Businesses Launch \"Road Show\" Tour of US, Dominican Republic|date=19 March 2013|website=caribjournal.com}}</ref>\n\n===Community and civil society programs===\nThroughout Latin America and the Caribbean, PADF partners with civil society organizations on programs intended to increase their capacity to respond to community needs. Civil society programming aims to enhance democratic values and empower communities and social entrepreneurs. It also promotes human rights, especially for Afro-descendants, indigenous and other vulnerable groups. Since its foundation in 1962, PADF has worked with thousands of civil society and community-based groups.\n\n===Social progress programs===\nPADF initiates programs, often with partnership from private corporations and donors, to confront social issues and strengthen communities in many Latin American and Caribbean nations. PADF has implemented programs aimed at community-driven development, improving infrastructure and housing, upgrading technical training and health services, aiding at-risk youth, and combating human trafficking, gang activities and violence.\n\n===Natural disaster programs===\nPADF works with local non-governmental organizations and communities to prepare for disasters, taking systematic precautions to reduce the risk of potential disasters. The programs are designed to lessen the impact of disasters and crises by: helping communities prepare for disasters; providing emergency relief; assisting disaster recovery, reconstruction and mitigation; strengthening community responses to natural disasters; supporting the Inter-American Committee for Disaster Reduction (IACDR); and aiding victims or humanitarian crises.\n\nPADF also responds to natural disasters and implements disaster relief programs in Latin America and the Caribbean. PADF has provided disaster relief assistance to communities in [[Brazil]], [[Chile]], [[Costa Rica]], [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], [[Haiti]], [[Honduras]], [[Jamaica]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Colombia]], [[Panama]], [[St. Lucia]] and [[Venezuela]].\n\n====2010 Haiti earthquake response====\nOn January 12, 2010, an [[earthquake]] with a scale of 7.0 struck Haiti just 10 miles west of the capital, [[Port-au-Prince]]. According to Haitian government estimations, the earthquake killed or injured 616,000 people, damaged or destroyed 250,000 residences, and left 1,000,000 people homeless.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/world/haitians-angry-over-slow-aid-20100204-ng2g.html|title=Haitians angry over slow aid|last=Renois|first=Clarens|date=4 February 2010|website=The Age|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the disaster, PADF has helped assess the structural safety of more than 400,000 buildings, repaired more than 9,000 homes, and instituted more than 1,000 community development programs in what is the single largest effort in the organization's history.\n\n'''COVID-19 response'''\n\nFollowing the spread of the COVID-19 Pandemic, PADF\u2019s social media presence has been largely centered around of public education and awareness. Their posts showcase precautionary measures, dispelled myths regarding the virus, provision of mental health resources, and continuous acknowledgement of breakthroughs in international human rights and transitional justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/padforg/|title=Pan American Development Fndtn (@padforg) profile on Instagram \u2022 485 posts|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Efforts include the creation and sharing of posters and related videos (including a hand-washing music video by Haitian artist BIC)<ref>\u201cLave Men Nou ( Kowonaviris/Kovid-19) .\u201d ''Youtube'', 7 Apr. 2020, youtu.be/QYEVuHXjfAM.</ref> in English, Haitian-Creole and Spanish for Latin American and Caribbean/ Haitian audiences. \n\nComplementary to their social media presence, PADF has taken initiative to start an emergency fund aimed towards assisting the 650 million people throughout Latin America and the Caribbean who are at risk to health-related, economic and social impacts of the pandemic. Moreover, with over 60 years of experience, sound financial resources, and strong affiliations with communities throughout these areas, PADF has been able to provide immediate assistance to urgent areas through mobile and e-vouchers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.padf.org/pressroom|title=Press Room|website=Pan American Development Foundation {{!}} PADF|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, PADF is supporting \"Dar una mano Ecuador\" (Give a Hand without Shaking Hands). It is a campaign whose aim is to administer non-perishable food packages to families in Ecuador who are among the most severely impacted and vulnerable communities in Latin America from the pandemic.<ref>\u201cGive a Hand without Shaking Hands - A Campaign to Feed the Hungry in Ecuador during COVID-19.\u201d ''Youtube'', 17 Apr. 2020, youtu.be/2U4lNDkFyb8.</ref>\n\n==Funding==\nPADF is a [[501(c)(3)]] tax-exempt organization in the United States. It receives donations from individuals, corporations, multilateral organizations (such as the World Bank, the UN, the Inter-American Development Bank, among others) and governments. It is audited each year and an annual statement is published in its annual report.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.padf.org/}}\n\n[[Category:Development charities based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Organization of American States]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name = Pan American Development Foundation\n| logo = \n| Non-profit_type = [[Non-governmental organization]]\n| size = \n| abbreviation = PADF\n| founded = 1962\n| type = International Development Organization\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]<!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| area_served = [[Latin America]], [[Caribbean]]\n| founder = Ronald Scheman\n| key_people = Katie Taylor, Executive Director<ref>{{cite web |title=PADF Selects New Executive Director: Catarina \"Katie\" Taylor |url=https://www.padf.org/news/padf-selects-new-executive-director-catarina-katie-taylor |website=Pan American Development Foundation |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref>\n| website = [http://www.padf.org www.padf.org]\n}}\nThe '''Pan American Development Foundation''' ('''PADF''') is a non-governmental and non-political organization created in 1962 by the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS), the public sector and the private sector to focus on issues of pressing concern in the Western Hemisphere. PADF, a non-profit organization, has worked in every country in the region. PADF aims to bring together stakeholders to create sustainable economic development, strengthen civil society and respond to natural disasters for the most disadvantaged people in Latin America and the Caribbean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.padf.org/ht/d/sp/i/29319/pid/29319 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009234203/http://www.padf.org/ht/d/sp/i/29319/pid/29319 |archivedate=2010-10-09 }}</ref>\n\nPADF, which also works to support the principles of the Inter-American Democratic Charter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/OASpage/eng/Documents/Democractic_Charter.htm|title=Democratic Charter|website=www.oas.org}}</ref> is an independent affiliate of the OAS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/en/|title=OAS - Organization of American States: Democracy for peace, security, and development|first=|last=OAS|date=1 August 2009|website=www.oas.org}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe PADF was established in 1962, by the Organization of American States (OAS), as part of the [[Alliance for Progress]] initiated by U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]]. It was created through a cooperative agreement between the OAS and private enterprise to provide a specialized non-governmental organization to assist the least advantaged people in Latin America and the Caribbean. Since its creation, PADF has implanted development programs throughout the Western Hemisphere carrying out the goals set forth by the OAS.\n\nIn 1975, OAS named PADF a \u201cspecial purpose foundation\u201d achieving consultative status with the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.padf.org/pages/history |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106183350/http://www.padf.org/pages/history |archivedate=2013-01-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Programs==\nIn keeping with its mission to create \u201ca Hemisphere of Opportunity for All,\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.padf.org/programs|title=Create Economic Opportunities|website=PADF}}</ref> PADF implements a range of different programs, reaching millions of people in Latin American and the Caribbean. The programs are divided into four areas of development.\n\n===Economic opportunity programs===\nPADF implements economic opportunity programs with the focus of improving the livelihoods of disadvantaged individuals and families. The programs include support for micro and medium-size businesses, skills training for youth and vulnerable groups, improving agricultural conditions and techniques, and expanding or improving local infrastructure.\n\n====LEAD program====\nIn 2012, PADF implemented the Leveraging Effective Application of Direct Investment (LEAD) program with $13 million in funding from the [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID). The LEAD program is a business plan competition which awards grants to small and medium enterprises. The grants range from $50,000 to $200,000 and must be matched be the grantee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haitilibre.com/en/news-7939-haiti-economy-2nd-edition-of-business-plan-competition.html|title=Haiti - Economy : 2nd Edition of Business Plan Competition - HaitiLibre.com : Haiti news 7/7|website=haitilibre.com}}</ref>\n\nPADF announced the launch of the second edition of the LEAD Program on February 20, 2013. Following the launch of the second round, a group of Haitian businesses, which had been awarded LEAD grants, participated in a business and investment seminar at [[Columbia University]]. The event is part of a series of investment events and conferences that the businesses are participating in throughout the United States, Canada and the Dominican Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caribjournal.com/2013/03/19/haiti-small-businesses-launch-road-show-tour-of-us-dominican-republic/|title=Haiti: Small Businesses Launch \"Road Show\" Tour of US, Dominican Republic|date=19 March 2013|website=caribjournal.com}}</ref>\n\n===Community and civil society programs===\nThroughout Latin America and the Caribbean, PADF partners with civil society organizations on programs intended to increase their capacity to respond to community needs. Civil society programming aims to enhance democratic values and empower communities and social entrepreneurs. It also promotes human rights, especially for Afro-descendants, indigenous and other vulnerable groups. Since its foundation in 1962, PADF has worked with thousands of civil society and community-based groups.\n\n===Social progress programs===\nPADF initiates programs, often with partnership from private corporations and donors, to confront social issues and strengthen communities in many Latin American and Caribbean nations. PADF has implemented programs aimed at community-driven development, improving infrastructure and housing, upgrading technical training and health services, aiding at-risk youth, and combating human trafficking, gang activities and violence.\n\n===Natural disaster programs===\nPADF works with local non-governmental organizations and communities to prepare for disasters, taking systematic precautions to reduce the risk of potential disasters. The programs are designed to lessen the impact of disasters and crises by: helping communities prepare for disasters; providing emergency relief; assisting disaster recovery, reconstruction and mitigation; strengthening community responses to natural disasters; supporting the Inter-American Committee for Disaster Reduction (IACDR); and aiding victims or humanitarian crises.\n\nPADF also responds to natural disasters and implements disaster relief programs in Latin America and the Caribbean. PADF has provided disaster relief assistance to communities in [[Brazil]], [[Chile]], [[Costa Rica]], [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], [[Haiti]], [[Honduras]], [[Jamaica]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Colombia]], [[Panama]], [[St. Lucia]] and [[Venezuela]].\n\n====2010 Haiti earthquake response====\nOn January 12, 2010, an [[earthquake]] with a scale of 7.0 struck Haiti just 10 miles west of the capital, [[Port-au-Prince]]. According to Haitian government estimations, the earthquake killed