//screenrant.com/too-hot-to-handle-lydia-clyma-netflix-hot-new-show/ |website=screenrant.com |publisher=ScreenRant |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Episode table\n| background=#7FF10D\n| overall=4\n| season=4\n| title=30\n| airdate=20\n| airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Too Hot to Handle \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/too-hot-to-handle/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ENews\"/>\n| aux1=15\n| aux1T=Prize money\n| released=y\n| episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Love, Sex or Money\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|100000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = When Harry Met Frances...\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|97000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Revenge Is a Dish Best Served Hot\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|94000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Two's Company, Three's a ... Threesome\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|94000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Boys to Men\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|75000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = The Bryce Isn't Right\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|55000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Sisters over Misters\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|43000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Lust or Bust\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|75000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nThe show was created by Laura Gibson and developed by Charlie Bennett, citing ''[[Seinfeld]]'' episode, \"[[The Contest (Seinfeld episode)|The Contest]]\" as their inspiration for the premise of ''Too Hot to Handle''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kurkland |first1=Daniel |title=Too Hot To Handle: Awesome Facts About The Making Of Netflix's New Show |url=https://www.thethings.com/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-show-facts-making-of/ |website=TheThings.com |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Laura Gibson, creative director of [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]]-owned production company [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]], which produced the eight-part series, told ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' that she had been working to produce a dating show since 2016.<ref name=\"inspiration\">{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Peter |title=\u2018Too Hot To Handle\u2019: Producers Dish The Dirt On Netflix Reality Show That Combines \u2018Seinfeld\u2019s \u2018The Contest\u2019 With \u2018Love Island\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/too-hot-to-handle-love-island-seinfeld-the-contest-netflix-1202910204/ |website=deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nViki Kolar and Jonno Richards, executive producers for ''Too Hot to Handle'', said they found inspiration for the virtual character from [[artificial intelligence]] and [[Virtual assistant|virtual assistants]], especially in [[Artificial intelligence for video surveillance|video surveillance]]. Viki Kolar stated, \"[A.I.] is literally everywhere around us. It's kind of governing us, it's taking over,\" in an interview with ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tannenbaum |first1=Emily |title=Netflix\u2019s Too Hot to Handle Is the Funniest, Least Sexy Reality Show About Sex |url=https://www.glamour.com/story/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-review |website=glamour.com |publisher=Glamour |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\nOn 5 May 2019, [[Netflix|Netflix Studios, LLC]] applied to trademark the phrase \"Too Hot to Handle\" for all educational, training, entertainment, sporting, and cultural purposes. The application was approved on 24 June 2019, and was extended on 5 March 2020.<ref name=\"trademark\">{{cite web |title=TOO HOT TO HANDLE - Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/884/51/too-hot-to-88451346.html |website=trademarks.justia.com |publisher=Justia Trademarks |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This has been done with other [[List of original programs distributed by Netflix|Netflix original programs]] such as ''[[Stranger Things]]'', ''[[The OA]]'', and ''[[Big Mouth (TV series)|Big Mouth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Netflix Studios, LLC Trademarks |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/owners/netflix-studios-llc-3160899/ |website=trademarks.justia.com |publisher=Justia Trademarks |accessdate=27 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Too Hot to Handle'' was produced by [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] production company [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Peter |title='Too Hot To Handle': Netflix Unveils Trailer & Sets Premiere For Steamy Reality Dating Format |url=https://deadline.com/video/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-premiere-trailer/ |website=deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show, instead of using a human as their host, used a [[virtual assistant]] named Lana. [[Desiree Burch]] provided voice-over narration, making snarky and comedic remarks towards the contestants.<ref name=\"narrator\">{{cite web |last1=Smail |first1=Gretchen |title='Too Hot To Handle' Narrator Desiree Burch Is The Perfect Person For The Job |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/too-hot-to-handle-narrator-desiree-burch-is-the-perfect-person-for-the-job-22794089 |website=bustle.com |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn 2018, [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]] announced that casting for an untitled reality television show was open.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Desiree |title='Too Hot to Handle' Cast Teases What to Expect From the No-Sex Dating Series (Exclusive) |url=https://www.etonline.com/too-hot-to-handle-cast-teases-what-to-expect-from-the-no-sex-dating-series-exclusive-144771 |website=etonline.com |publisher=Entertainment Tonight |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In total, over 3,000 people auditioned for the show; however, producer Louise Peet stated that the people who ultimately ended up being on the show stood out to the casting team and were chosen quickly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Elena |title=The Too Hot to Handle Cast and Creators Answer Your Burning Questions |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a32158960/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-facts-rules/ |website=oprahmag.com |publisher=The Oprah Magazine |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nA luxury resort called [https://casatau.com/ Casa Tau] in [[Punta Mita]], [[Mexico]] opened to guests in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lague |first1=Adam |title=Is This the Most Luxurious Home in Punta Mita? |url=https://magazine.luxuryretreats.com/casa-tau-most-luxurious-home-punta-mita/ |website=magazine.luxuryretreat.com |publisher=Luxury Retreats Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after, ''Too Hot to Handle'' started filming at Casa Tau in late-March 2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brockington |first1=Ariana |title=This Is When All The Too Hot To Handle Action Was Filmed |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2020/04/9685374/when-was-too-hot-to-handle-filmed-netflix |website=refinery29.com |publisher=Refinery29 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and ended filming in April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanton |first1=Kayla |title=Where Was 'Too Hot To Handle' Filmed? You Can Plan Your Own Luxury Stay |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-was-too-hot-to-handle-filmed-you-can-plan-your-own-luxury-stay-22817237 |website=bustle.com |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Elena |title=Netflix's Too Hot to Handle Was Filmed at This $15,660-a-Night Mexican Villa |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a32110085/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-filming-location/ |website=oprahmah.com |publisher=The Oprah Magazine |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> After filming had ended, all fourteen contestants were able to spend several days at the resort with no cameras before going home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baty |first1=Emma |title=Harry and Francesca From 'Too Hot to Handle' Felt Like the Group Was \"Against\" Them During the Retreat |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a32173308/harry-francesca-too-hot-to-handle-interview/ |website=cosmopolitan.com |publisher=Cosmopolitan |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Release ===\nOn 10 April 2020, [[Netflix]] released the trailer for the first season of ''Too Hot to Handle''.<ref name=\"trailer\">{{cite web |title=Season 1 Trailer: Too Hot to Handle |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81189742?trackId=14277282&tctx=0%2C0%2C1a03b184-4d1a-4d08-ae4d-cd1d13d41a6e-4706103%2C%2C |publisher=Netflix |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first season of ''Too Hot to Handle'' consisted of eight episodes,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corinthios |first1=Aurelie |title=Netlix Drops Too Hot to Handle Trailer: See 10 Hot Singles Attempt Celibacy for a $100K Prize |url=https://people.com/tv/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-trailer/ |website=people.com |publisher=People |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> all of which were released on 17 April 2020 on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masonhall |first1=Erika |title=NETFLIX SPARKS JOY WITH RETURNING UNSCRIPTED FAVORITES RHYTHM + FLOW, THE CIRCLE, AND LOVE IS BLIND, PLUS AN ALL-NEW SHOW FROM MARIE KONDO |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-sparks-joy-with-returning-unscripted-favorites-rhythm-flow-the-circle-and-love-is-blind-plus-an-all-new-show-from-marie-kondo |website=media.netflix.com |publisher=Netflix Media Center |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Prize ===\nAt the allocation ceremony, the ten remaining contestants became the winners. Bryce Hirschberg, Chloe Veitch, David Birtwistle, Francesca Farago, Harry Jowsey, Kelz Dyke, Lydia Clyma, Nicole O'Brien, Rhonda Paul, and Sharron Townsend all split the {{USD|75000|long=no}} prize fund, resulting in {{USD|7500|long=no}} for each person.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Lust or Bust |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81031053?trackId=200257859 |series=Too Hot to Handle |series-link=Too Hot to Handle (TV series) |network=Netflix |date=17 April 2020 |season=1 |number=8}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n''Too Hot to Handle'' became the #1 television program on [[Netflix]] during the week of April 19.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Decider |title=Netflix Top 10 List: Today\u2019s Most Popular Shows and Movies, Reviewed |url=https://decider.com/list/netflix-top-10-movies-and-shows/ |website=decider.com |publisher=Decider |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421132624/https://decider.com/list/netflix-top-10-movies-and-shows/ |archivedate=21 April 2020 |date=20 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the first season of ''Too Hot to Handle'' 43%, holding an average rating of 4.28 out of 10 from 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/too_hot_to_handle/s01|title=TOO HOT TO HANDLE: SEASON 1 (2020)|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, gives the series a [[metascore]] of 43 based on 10 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/too-hot-to-handle|title=Too Hot to Handle - TV Show Reviews|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\nCritic John Serba of ''[[Decider (website)|Decider]]'' panned the show, stating that \"to call it tawdry is to engage in nuclear understatement\", calling it \"some of the dreckiest dreck ever drecked\", and advising viewers to skip it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Serba |first1=John |title=Stream It Or Skip It: \u2018Too Hot to Handle\u2019 on Netflix, Possibly the Trashiest Reality Show Ever |url=https://decider.com/2020/04/17/too-hot-to-handle-on-netflix-stream-it-or-skip-it/ |website=Decider |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nRachelle Hampton of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' also wrote a negative review, stating: \"Despite an irresistibly juicy premise, ''Too Hot to Handle'' doesn\u2019t know what kind of show it wants to be, and it suffers for lack of direction. (...) Its will-they-or-won\u2019t-they concept is ruined as soon as it becomes clear that, yes, they ''obviously'' will, even if it means losing tens of thousands of dollars.\"<ref name=\"Slate\"></ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Netflix title|80241027}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt12004280}}\n* [https://www.instagram.com/toohotnetflix/ @toohotnetflix] on [[Instagram]]\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Too Hot to Handle}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:American dating and relationship reality television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|2020 Netflix reality series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the television series|other uses|Too Hot to Handle (disambiguation){{!}}Too Hot to Handle}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Too Hot to Handle\n| image                    = Too Hot to Handle title card.png\n| caption                  = The title card for the series.\n| genre                    = [[Reality television|Reality]] [[dating game show]]\n| presenter                = [[Virtual assistant|Lana]]\n| narrated                 = [[Desiree Burch]]\n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| location                 = [[Punta Mita]], [[Mexico]]\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 8        \n| executive_producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Ed Sleeman\n* Jonno Richards\n* Leon Wilson\n* Viki Kolar\n}}\n| creator                  = Laura Gibson\n| based_on = ''{{Based on|[[The Contest]]'' from ''[[Seinfeld]]''|[[Larry David]] and [[Jerry Seinfeld]]\n}}\n| developer                = {{plainlist|\n* Charlie Bennett\n* Laura Gibson\n}}\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 36\u201343 minutes\n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n| company                  = [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]]\n| distributor              = [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| released                 =  {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n\n'''''Too Hot to Handle''''' is a [[reality television]] [[dating game show]] produced by [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] production company [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]]. It was created by Laura Gibson and developed by Charlie Bennett. The show consisted of eight episodes, all of which were released on 17 April 2020 on [[Netflix]]. The host of the series is a [[virtual assistant]], named \"Lana\", who will give the cast the rules they must follow for the season; [[Desiree Burch]] provided voice-over narration. The premise of the show is to teach young, single people to create genuine connections instead of their usual [[One-night stand|flings]]. If contestants engage in any sexual contact on the island, then the prize money would decrease, starting at {{USD|100000|long=no}}.\n\nOn finale night, Bryce Hirschberg, Chloe Veitch, David Birtwistle, Francesca Farago, Harry Jowsey, Kelz Dyke, Lydia Clyma, Nicole O'Brien, Rhonda Paul, and Sharron Townsend were all deemed the winners of ''Too Hot to Handle'' and split the {{USD|75000|long=no}} prize.\n\n== Format ==\nThe series will follow the original group of ten singles as they are taken to a special island villa for four weeks to find love and {{USD|100000|long=no}}. However, twelve hours into the retreat, the contestants are informed by a [[virtual assistant]], Lana,<ref name=\"ENews\">{{cite web |last1=Harnick |first1=Chris |title=Too Hot to Handle Tasks Horny Contestants With Keeping Their Hands to Themselves for Money |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1139399/too-hot-to-handle-tasks-horny-contestants-with-keeping-their-hands-to-themselves-for-money |website=eonline.com |publisher=ENews |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> that they [[Sexual abstinence|cannot do anything sexual]], such as kissing, [[Sexual intercourse|sex]], or [[Masturbation|masturbating]]. If they do, then the prize money will decrease by a set amount.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henry |first1=Grace |title=When is Too Hot to Handle on? Everything you need to know about Netflix\u2019s new dating show |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-03-23/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-release-date/ |website=radiotimes.com |publisher=RadioTimes |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Kissing can deduct up to {{USD|3000|long=no}} from the total prize fund, and sex can dock up to {{USD|20000|long=no}}.<ref name=\"rules\">{{cite web |title=What you need to know about Netflix's wild social experiment Too Hot to Handle |url=https://ew.com/tv/what-you-need-to-know-about-netflixs-social-experiment-too-hot-to-handle/ |website=ew.com |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Midway through the game, four new contestants joined as part of the retreat and followed the same rules as everyone else, making a total of fourteen contestants. At several points during the retreat, Lana set up workshops for the contestants to play in order to stay entertained.<ref name=\"rules\"/> These games can consist of many things, such as [[Shibari]].<ref name=\"Slate\">{{cite web |last1=Hampton |first1=Rachelle |title=Netflix\u2019s Too Hot to Handle Bungles Its Juicy Reality TV Premise |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-no-sex-reality-show-review.html |website=slate.com |publisher=Slate Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMidway through the season, the contestants were given watches, which would emit a light when the contestants made a genuine connection. Once the light turned on, the rules of the retreat were void for the contestant and they were able to explore their connection further. If their connection was strong enough, they were able to have a night at the private suite, but their lights would not turn on during the night, so they still needed to follow the rules.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Two's Company, Three's a ... Threesome |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81031049?trackId=200257859 |series=Too Hot to Handle |series-link=Too Hot to Handle (TV series) |network=Netflix |date=17 April 2020 |season=1 |number=4}}</ref> If a contestant was not showing growth in making a strong connection, they would be eliminated.\n\nAs part of the final night, the two contestants that cost the most money from sexual contact would have to spend the night together in the special suite without any physical contact at all. If they were to spend the entire night with no contact, the amount of money they cost from the prize fund was added back. Before the prize fund was allocated, several contestants were eliminated since they failed to seek personal growth. At the allocation ceremony, the remaining contestants all split the prize money since they all experienced personal growth in their dating life.\n\nSeveral publications have compared the format of ''Too Hot to Handle'' to that of ''[[Love Island (franchise)|Love Island]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Curto |first1=Justin |title=Netflix\u2019s Too Hot to Handle Will Fill the Love Is Blind\u2013Size Hole in Your Life |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/too-hot-to-handle-trailer-netflix.html |website=vulture.com |publisher=Vulture |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Baty |first1=Emma |title=Netflix Just Made Their Own Version of 'Love Island,' but the Contestants Can\u2019t Hook Up With Each Other |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a32109096/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-trailer/ |website=cosmopolitan.com |publisher=Cosmopolitan |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\nThe cast was revealed on ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' on 10 April 2020.<ref name=\"cast\">{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Desiree |title='Too Hot to Handle': Meet the Cast of Your Next Netflix Quarantine Obsession |url=https://www.etonline.com/too-hot-to-handle-meet-the-cast-of-your-next-netflix-quarantine-obsession-144404 |website=etonline.com |publisher=Entertainment Tonight |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Contestant\n! Age\n! Residence\n! Entered\n! Exited\n! Status\n! {{abbr|Refs|References}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"|'''[[Bryce Hirschberg]]'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"|'''29'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"|'''[[Venice, California|Venice]], [[California]], [[United States]]'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"|'''Episode 3'''\n| style=\"background:lavender;\"|'''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n| rowspan=\"14\"|<ref name=\"cast\"/><ref name=\"rules\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Elena |title=Here Are the Too Hot to Handle Cast Members' Instagram Handles and Bios |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/g32099092/too-hot-to-handle-cast-instagram-handles-bio/ |website=oprahmag.com |publisher=The Oprah Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Chloe Veitch'''\n| '''21'''\n| '''[[Essex]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''David Birtwistle'''\n| '''28'''\n| '''[[Wigan]], [[Greater Manchester]], [[United Kingdom]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Francesca Farago'''\n| '''26'''\n| '''[[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Harry Jowsey'''\n| '''23'''\n| '''[[Queensland]], [[Australia]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Kelechi \"Kelz\" Dyke'''\n| '''27'''\n| '''[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Lydia Clyma'''\n| '''22'''\n| '''[[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]], [[United Kingdom]]'''\n| '''Episode 6'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Nicole O'Brien'''\n| '''23'''\n| '''[[County Cork]], [[Ireland]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Rhonda Paul'''\n| '''27'''\n| '''[[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-style=\"background:lavender;\"\n| '''Sharron Townsend'''\n| '''25'''\n| '''[[Camden, New Jersey|Camden]], [[New Jersey]], [[United States]]'''\n| '''Episode 1'''\n| '''Episode 8'''\n| {{won|'''Winner'''}}\n|-\n| Kori Sampson\n| 22\n| [[Plymouth]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| Episode 6\n| Episode 8\n| {{Eliminated}}\n|-\n| Madison Wyborny\n| 20\n| [[California]], [[United States]]\n| Episode 6\n| Episode 8\n| {{Eliminated}}\n|-\n| Matthew Smith\n| 29\n| [[Highlands Ranch, Colorado|Highlands Ranch]], [[Colorado]], [[United States]]\n| Episode 1\n| Episode 6\n| {{Quit|Walked}}\n|-\n| Haley Cureton\n| 20\n| [[Jacksonville]], [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| Episode 1\n| Episode 6\n| {{Eliminated}}\n|}\n\n=== Other appearances ===\nMatthew Smith was a contestant on the [[America's Next Top Model (season 21)|twenty-first]] season of ''[[America's Next Top Model]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Tilly |title=Too Hot To Handle\u2019s Jesus was previously on America\u2019s Next Top Model and you totally wouldn\u2019t recognise him |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/19/hot-handles-jesus-previously-americas-next-top-model-completely-unrecognisable-12578077/ |website=metro.co.uk |publisher=Metro |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Harry Jowsey was a contestant on the first season of ''Heartbreak Island'' in [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Harry Jowsey |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/shows/heartbreak-island/contestants/harry-jowsey |website=tvnz.co.nz |publisher=tvnz |accessdate=20 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Lydia Clyma was featured on ''Magaluf Weekender'' and ''Sex Clinic''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fedich |first1=Justin |title=Too Hot to Handle: Everything to Know About Lydia Clyma From Netflix's Reality Show |url=https://screenrant.com/too-hot-to-handle-lydia-clyma-netflix-hot-new-show/ |website=screenrant.com |publisher=ScreenRant |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Episode table\n| background=#7FF10D\n| overall=4\n| season=4\n| title=30\n| airdate=20\n| airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Too Hot to Handle \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/too-hot-to-handle/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ENews\"/>\n| aux1=15\n| aux1T=Prize money\n| released=y\n| episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Love, Sex or Money\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|100000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = When Harry Met Frances...\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|97000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Revenge Is a Dish Best Served Hot\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|94000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Two's Company, Three's a ... Threesome\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|94000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Boys to Men\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|75000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = The Bryce Isn't Right\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|55000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Sisters over Misters\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|43000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Lust or Bust\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|17|df=yes}}\n| Aux1            = {{USD|75000|long=no}}\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 7FF10D\n}}\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Background ===\nThe show was created by Laura Gibson and developed by Charlie Bennett, citing ''[[Seinfeld]]'' episode, \"[[The Contest (Seinfeld episode)|The Contest]]\" as their inspiration for the premise of ''Too Hot to Handle''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kurkland |first1=Daniel |title=Too Hot To Handle: Awesome Facts About The Making Of Netflix's New Show |url=https://www.thethings.com/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-show-facts-making-of/ |website=TheThings.com |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Laura Gibson, creative director of [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]]-owned production company [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]], which produced the eight-part series, told ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' that she had been working to produce a dating show since 2016.<ref name=\"inspiration\">{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Peter |title=\u2018Too Hot To Handle\u2019: Producers Dish The Dirt On Netflix Reality Show That Combines \u2018Seinfeld\u2019s \u2018The Contest\u2019 With \u2018Love Island\u2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/too-hot-to-handle-love-island-seinfeld-the-contest-netflix-1202910204/ |website=deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nViki Kolar and Jonno Richards, executive producers for ''Too Hot to Handle'', said they found inspiration for the virtual character from [[artificial intelligence]] and [[Virtual assistant|virtual assistants]], especially in [[Artificial intelligence for video surveillance|video surveillance]]. Viki Kolar stated, \"[A.I.] is literally everywhere around us. It's kind of governing us, it's taking over,\" in an interview with ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tannenbaum |first1=Emily |title=Netflix\u2019s Too Hot to Handle Is the Funniest, Least Sexy Reality Show About Sex |url=https://www.glamour.com/story/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-review |website=glamour.com |publisher=Glamour |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Development ===\nOn 5 May 2019, [[Netflix|Netflix Studios, LLC]] applied to trademark the phrase \"Too Hot to Handle\" for all educational, training, entertainment, sporting, and cultural purposes. The application was approved on 24 June 2019, and was extended on 5 March 2020.<ref name=\"trademark\">{{cite web |title=TOO HOT TO HANDLE - Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/884/51/too-hot-to-88451346.html |website=trademarks.justia.com |publisher=Justia Trademarks |accessdate=27 March 2020 |date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This has been done with other [[List of original programs distributed by Netflix|Netflix original programs]] such as ''[[Stranger Things]]'', ''[[The OA]]'', and ''[[Big Mouth (TV series)|Big Mouth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Netflix Studios, LLC Trademarks |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/owners/netflix-studios-llc-3160899/ |website=trademarks.justia.com |publisher=Justia Trademarks |accessdate=27 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Too Hot to Handle'' was produced by [[Fremantle (company)|Fremantle]] production company [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Peter |title='Too Hot To Handle': Netflix Unveils Trailer & Sets Premiere For Steamy Reality Dating Format |url=https://deadline.com/video/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-premiere-trailer/ |website=deadline.com |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show, instead of using a human as their host, used a [[virtual assistant]] named Lana. [[Desiree Burch]] provided voice-over narration, making snarky and comedic remarks towards the contestants.<ref name=\"narrator\">{{cite web |last1=Smail |first1=Gretchen |title='Too Hot To Handle' Narrator Desiree Burch Is The Perfect Person For The Job |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/too-hot-to-handle-narrator-desiree-burch-is-the-perfect-person-for-the-job-22794089 |website=bustle.com |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn 2018, [[Talkback (production company)|Talkback]] announced that casting for an untitled reality television show was open.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy |first1=Desiree |title='Too Hot to Handle' Cast Teases What to Expect From the No-Sex Dating Series (Exclusive) |url=https://www.etonline.com/too-hot-to-handle-cast-teases-what-to-expect-from-the-no-sex-dating-series-exclusive-144771 |website=etonline.com |publisher=Entertainment Tonight |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In total, over 3,000 people auditioned for the show; however, producer Louise Peet stated that the people who ultimately ended up being on the show stood out to the casting team and were chosen quickly.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Elena |title=The Too Hot to Handle Cast and Creators Answer Your Burning Questions |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/a32158960/too-hot-to-handle-netflix-facts-rules/ |website=oprahmag.com |publisher=The Oprah Magazine |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nA luxury resort called [https://casatau.com/ Casa Tau] in [[Punta Mita]], [[Mexico]] opened to guests in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lague |first1=Adam |title=Is This the Most Luxurious Home in Punta Mita? |url=https://magazine.luxuryretreats.com/casa-tau-most-luxurious-home-punta-mita/ |website=magazine.luxuryretreat.com |publisher=Luxury Retreats Magazine |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=27 March 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Soon after, ''Too Hot to Handle'' started filming at Casa Tau in late-March 2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brockington |first1=Ariana |title=This Is When All The Too Hot To Handle Action Was Filmed |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2020/04/9685374/when-was-too-hot-to-handle-filmed-netflix |website=refinery29.com |publisher=Refinery29 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and ended filming in April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blanton |first1=Kayla |title=Where Was 'Too Hot To Handle' Filmed? You Can Plan Your Own Luxury Stay |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/where-was-too-hot-to-handle-filmed-you-can-plan-your-own-luxury-stay-22817237 |website=bustle.com |publisher=Bustle |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicolaou |first1=Elena |title=Netflix's Too Hot to Handle Was Filmed at This $15,660-a-Night Mexican Villa |url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a32110085/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-filming-location/ |website=oprahmah.com |publisher=The Oprah Magazine |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> After filming had ended, all fourteen contestants were able to spend several days at the resort with no cameras before going home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baty |first1=Emma |title=Harry and Francesca From 'Too Hot to Handle' Felt Like the Group Was \"Against\" Them During the Retreat |url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a32173308/harry-francesca-too-hot-to-handle-interview/ |website=cosmopolitan.com |publisher=Cosmopolitan |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Release ===\nOn 10 April 2020, [[Netflix]] released the trailer for the first season of ''Too Hot to Handle''.<ref name=\"trailer\">{{cite web |title=Season 1 Trailer: Too Hot to Handle |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81189742?trackId=14277282&tctx=0%2C0%2C1a03b184-4d1a-4d08-ae4d-cd1d13d41a6e-4706103%2C%2C |publisher=Netflix |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The first season of ''Too Hot to Handle'' consisted of eight episodes,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corinthios |first1=Aurelie |title=Netlix Drops Too Hot to Handle Trailer: See 10 Hot Singles Attempt Celibacy for a $100K Prize |url=https://people.com/tv/netflix-too-hot-to-handle-trailer/ |website=people.com |publisher=People |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> all of which were released on 17 April 2020 on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Masonhall |first1=Erika |title=NETFLIX SPARKS JOY WITH RETURNING UNSCRIPTED FAVORITES RHYTHM + FLOW, THE CIRCLE, AND LOVE IS BLIND, PLUS AN ALL-NEW SHOW FROM MARIE KONDO |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflix-sparks-joy-with-returning-unscripted-favorites-rhythm-flow-the-circle-and-love-is-blind-plus-an-all-new-show-from-marie-kondo |website=media.netflix.com |publisher=Netflix Media Center |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Prize ===\nAt the allocation ceremony, the ten remaining contestants became the winners. Bryce Hirschberg, Chloe Veitch, David Birtwistle, Francesca Farago, Harry Jowsey, Kelz Dyke, Lydia Clyma, Nicole O'Brien, Rhonda Paul, and Sharron Townsend all split the {{USD|75000|long=no}} prize fund, resulting in {{USD|7500|long=no}} for each person.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Lust or Bust |url=https://www.netflix.com/watch/81031053?trackId=200257859 |series=Too Hot to Handle |series-link=Too Hot to Handle (TV series) |network=Netflix |date=17 April 2020 |season=1 |number=8}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n''Too Hot to Handle'' became the #1 television program on [[Netflix]] during the week of April 19.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Decider |title=Netflix Top 10 List: Today\u2019s Most Popular Shows and Movies, Reviewed |url=https://decider.com/list/netflix-top-10-movies-and-shows/ |website=decider.com |publisher=Decider |accessdate=21 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421132624/https://decider.com/list/netflix-top-10-movies-and-shows/ |archivedate=21 April 2020 |date=20 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the first season of ''Too Hot to Handle'' 43%, holding an average rating of 4.28 out of 10 from 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/too_hot_to_handle/s01|title=TOO HOT TO HANDLE: SEASON 1 (2020)|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, gives the series a [[metascore]] of 43 based on 10 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/too-hot-to-handle|title=Too Hot to Handle - TV Show Reviews|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\nCritic John Serba of ''[[Decider (website)|Decider]]'' panned the show, stating that \"to call it tawdry is to engage in nuclear understatement\", calling it \"some of the dreckiest dreck ever drecked\", and advising viewers to skip it.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Serba |first1=John |title=Stream It Or Skip It: \u2018Too Hot to Handle\u2019 on Netflix, Possibly the Trashiest Reality Show Ever |url=https://decider.com/2020/04/17/too-hot-to-handle-on-netflix-stream-it-or-skip-it/ |website=Decider |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nRachelle Hampton of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' also wrote a negative review, stating: \"Despite an irresistibly juicy premise, ''Too Hot to Handle'' doesn\u2019t know what kind of show it wants to be, and it suffers for lack of direction. (...) Its will-they-or-won\u2019t-they concept is ruined as soon as it becomes clear that, yes, they ''obviously'' will, even if it means losing tens of thousands of dollars.\"<ref name=\"Slate\"></ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Netflix title|80241027}}\n* {{IMDb title|tt12004280}}\n* [https://www.instagram.com/toohotnetflix/ @toohotnetflix] on [[Instagram]]\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Too Hot to Handle}}\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2020s American reality television series]]\n[[Category:American dating and relationship reality television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n", "name_user": "Favre1fan93", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Too_Hot_to_Handle_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Rapeseed", "text_new": "{{distinguish|grape seed oil}}\n{{Redirect|Rapeseed oil|specific vegetable oils derived from rapeseed|Canola oil|and|Colza oil|}}\n{{Redirect|Brassica napus|another cultivar of the same species grown for its root|Rutabaga}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Rapeseed oil seed\n| image = Koeh-169.jpg\n| image_caption = Rapeseed (''Brassica napus'')\n| genus = Brassica\n| species = napus\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|L.]]{{Refn|group=note|''Brassica napus'' was originally described and published in ''[[Species Plantarum]]'' 2:666. 1753.{{Sfn|GRIN|2010a}} }}\n}}\n\n'''Rapeseed''' (''Brassica napus ''subsp.'' napus'') is a bright-yellow flowering member of the family [[Brassicaceae]] (mustard or cabbage family), cultivated mainly for its oil-rich seed, which naturally contains appreciable amounts of toxic [[erucic acid]]. '''[[Canola]]''' are a group of ''rapeseed'' [[cultivar]]s which were bred to have very low levels of [[erucic acid]] and are especially prized for use for human and animal food. ''Rapeseed'' is the third-largest source of [[vegetable oil]] and second-largest source of protein meal in the world.\n\n== Etymology and taxonomy ==\nThe term \"rape\" derives from the Latin word for [[turnip]], ''rapa'' or ''rapum'', cognate with the Greek word ''rhapys''.{{Sfn|OED|2016}}\n\nThe [[species]] ''Brassica napus'' belongs to the flowering plant family [[Brassicaceae]]. Rapeseed is a [[subspecies]] with the [[Autonym (botany)|autonym]]  ''B. napus ''subsp.'' napus''.{{Sfn|GRIN|2012a}} It encompasses winter and spring oilseed, vegetable and fodder rape.{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=54}} Siberian kale is a distinct leaf rape form [[Variety (botany)|variety]] (''B. napus ''var.'' pabularia'') which used to be common as a winter-annual vegetable.{{Sfn|GRIN|2010b}}{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=54}} The second subspecies of ''B. napus'' is [[rutabaga|''B. napus ''subsp.'' rapifera'']] (also subsp. ''napobrassica''; the rutabaga, swede, or yellow turnip).{{Sfn|GRIN|2012b}}{{Sfn|NCBI|2013}}\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Brassica napus 2.jpg|thumb|Rapeseed blossoms]]\n\n''Brassica napus'' grows to {{convert|100|cm|abbr=on}} height with [[pinnatifid]] and [[glaucous]] lower leaves{{Sfn|Martin|1965}}{{Sfn|Parnell|Curtis|Webb|2012}}{{Sfn|Webb|Parnell|Doogue|1996}} and with the upper leaves clasping the stem. ''Brassica napus'' can be distinguished from ''[[Brassica nigra]]'' by the upper leaves which do not clasp the stem, and from ''[[Brassica rapa]]'' by its smaller petals which are less than {{convert|13|mm|abbr=on}} across.{{Sfn|Parnell|Curtis|Webb|2012}}\n\nRapeseed flowers are yellow and about {{convert|17|mm|abbr=on}} across.{{Sfn|Parnell|Curtis|Webb|2012}} They are radial and consist of four [[petals]] in a typical cross-form, alternating with four [[sepals]]. They have indeterminate [[racemose]] flowering starting at the lowest bud and growing upward in the following days. The flowers have two lateral [[stamens]] with short filaments, and four median stamens with longer filaments whose anthers split away from the flower's center upon flowering.{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=56}}\n\nThe rapeseed pods are green and elongated [[Silique|siliquae]] during development that eventually ripen to brown. Each pod has two [[Locule|compartments]] separated by a inner central wall within which a row of oilseeds develop. The oilseeds are black and hard at maturity.{{Sfn|Alford|2008|pp=1-2}}\n\n== Ecology ==\nIn Northern Ireland, U K ''B. napus'' and ''B. rapa'' are recorded as escapes in roadside verges and waste ground.{{Sfn|Beesley|Wilde|1997|p=104}}\n\n== Uses ==\n[[File:Rapeseed, roasted.jpg|thumb|Roasted canola seeds]]\n\nRapeseed is grown for the production of [[compound feed|animal feed]], edible [[vegetable oils]], and [[biodiesel]]. Rapeseed was the third-leading source of vegetable oil in the world in 2000, after [[soybean]] and [[palm oil]].{{Sfn|USDA|2002|p=26}} It is the world's second-leading source of [[protein]] meal after soybean.{{Sfn|Heuz\u00e9|Tran|Sauvant|Lessire|2020}}\n\n=== Animal feed ===\nProcessing of rapeseed for oil production produces rapeseed meal as a byproduct. The byproduct is a high-protein animal feed, competitive with soybean. The feed is employed mostly for [[cattle]] feeding, but is also used for [[pig]]s and [[poultry]].{{Sfn |Heuz\u00e9 |Tran |Sauvant |Lessire |2020}} However, natural rapeseed oil contains 50% [[erucic acid]] and high levels of [[glucosinolates]] that significantly lowers the nutritional value of rapeseed press cakes for animal feed.{{Sfn|Potts|Rakow|Males|1999}}\n\n=== Vegetable oil ===\nRapeseed oil is one of the oldest known vegetable oils, but historically was used in limited quantities due to high levels of erucic acid, which is damaging to [[cardiac muscle]] of animals, and glucosinolates, which made it less nutritious in animal feed.{{Sfn|O'Brien|2008|pp=37-40}} Rapeseed oil can contain up to 54% erucic acid.{{Sfn|Sahasrabudhe|1977|p=323}} Food-grade canola oil derived from rapeseed cultivars, also known as rapeseed 00 oil, low erucic acid rapeseed oil, LEAR oil, and rapeseed canola-equivalent oil, has been [[generally recognized as safe]] by the [[United States Food and Drug Administration]].{{Sfn|USFDA|2010}} Canola oil is limited by government regulation to a maximum of 2% erucic acid by weight in the USA{{Sfn|USFDA|2010}} and 5% in the EU,{{Sfn|EC|1980}} with special regulations for infant food. These low levels of erucic acid are not believed to cause harm in human [[infants]].{{Sfn|USFDA|2010}}{{Sfn|EC|1980}}\n\n=== Biodiesel ===\nRapeseed oil is used as diesel fuel, either as [[biodiesel]], straight in heated fuel systems, or blended with petroleum distillates for powering motor vehicles. Biodiesel may be used in pure form in newer engines without engine damage and is frequently combined with fossil-fuel [[Diesel fuel|diesel]] in ratios varying from 2% to 20% biodiesel. Owing to the costs of growing, crushing, and refining rapeseed biodiesel, rapeseed-derived biodiesel from new oil costs more to produce than standard diesel fuel, so diesel fuels are commonly made from the used oil. Rapeseed oil is the preferred oil stock for biodiesel production in most of Europe, accounting for about 80% of the feedstock,{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} partly because rapeseed produces more oil per unit of land area compared to other oil sources, such as soybeans, but primarily because canola oil has a significantly lower [[Gel point (petroleum)|gel point]] than most other vegetable oils.\n\n=== Other ===\nRapeseed is also used as a [[cover crop]] in the US during the winter as it prevents [[soil erosion]], produces large amounts of [[biomass]], suppresses weeds and can improve soil [[tilth]] with its root system. Some cultivars of rapeseed are also used as annual forage and are ready for grazing livestock 80 to 90 days after planting.{{Sfn|AgMRC|2018}}\n\nRapeseed has a high [[Melliferous flower|melliferous]] potential and is a main forage crop for [[honeybees]].{{Sfn|Bertazzini|Forlani|2016}} Monofloral rapeseed honey has a whitish or milky yellow color, peppery taste and, due to its fast crystallization time, a soft-solid texture. It crystallizes within 3 to 4 weeks and can ferment over time if stored improperly.{{Sfn|Lixandru|2017}} The low fructose-to-glucose ratio in [[Monofloral honey|monofloral rapeseed honey]] causes it to quickly granulate in the [[honeycomb]], forcing beekeepers to extract the honey within 24 hours of it being capped.{{Sfn|Bertazzini|Forlani|2016}}\n\nAs a [[Lubricant#Biolubricant|biolubricant]], rapeseed has possible uses for bio-medical applications (e.g., lubricants for artificial joints) and the use of personal lubricant for sexual purposes.{{Sfn|Salimon|Salih|Yousif|2010}} Biolubricant containing 70% or more canola/rapeseed oil has replaced petroleum-based chainsaw oil in Austria although they are typically more expensive.{{Sfn|Garrett|1998}}\n\nRapeseed has been researched as a means of containing [[radionuclide]]s that contaminated the soil after the [[Chernobyl disaster]]{{Sfn|Smith|2004}}{{Sfn|RIA Novosti|2010}}{{Sfn|Walker|2010}} as it has a rate of uptake up to three times more than other grains, and only about 3 to 6% of the radionuclides go into the oilseeds.{{Sfn|Smith|2004}}\n\nRapeseed meal is mostly used as a soil fertilizer rather than for animal feed in [[China]].{{Sfn|Bonjean|Dequidt|Sang|Limagrain|2016}}\n\n== Cultivation ==\n[[File:Champ de colza C\u00f4te-d'Or Bourgogne avril 2014.jpg|thumb|Field of rapeseed]]\n\nCrops from the genus ''Brassica'', including rapeseed, were among the earliest plants to be widely cultivated by mankind as early as 10,000 years ago. Rapeseed was being cultivated in India as early as 4000 B.C. and it spread to China and Japan 2000 years ago.{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=54}}\n\nOilseed rape is predominantly cultivated in its winter form in most of Europe and Asia due to the requirement of [[vernalization]] to start the process of flowering. It is sown in autumn and remains in a [[Rosette (botany)|leaf rosette]] on the soil surface during the winter. The plant grows a long vertical stem in the next spring followed by lateral branch development. It generally flowers in late spring with the process of pod development and ripening occurring over a period of 6\u20138 weeks until [[midsummer]].{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=56}}\n\nIn Europe, winter rape is grown as an annual break crop in three to four year rotations with cereals such as [[wheat]] and [[barley]], and break crops such as [[peas]] and [[beans]]. This is done to reduce the possibility of pests and diseases being carried over from one crop to another.{{Sfn|Alford|2008|p=3}} Winter rape is less susceptible to [[crop failure]] as it is more vigorous than the summer variety and can compensate for damage done by pests.{{Sfn|Alford|2008|p=4}}\n\nSpring rapeseed is cultivated in Canada, northern Europe and Australia as it is not winter-hardy and does not require vernalization. The crop is sown in spring with stem development happening immediately after [[germination]].{{Sfn|Snowdon|L\u00fchs|Friedt|2006|p=56}}\n\nRapeseed can be cultivated on a wide variety of well-drained soils, prefers a [[pH]] between 5.5 and 8.3 and has a moderate tolerance of [[soil salinity]].{{Sfn|AgMRC|2018}} It is predominantly a [[Anemophily|wind-pollinated]] plant but shows significantly increased grain yields when [[Honey bee#Pollination|bee-pollinated]],{{Sfn|Chamb\u00f3|De Oliveira|Garcia|Duarte-J\u00fanior|2014}} almost double the final yield{{Sfn|Bertazzini|Forlani|2016}} but the effect is cultivar-dependent.{{Sfn|Lindstr\u00f6m|Herbertsson|Rundl\u00f6f|Smith|2015}} It is currently grown with high levels of nitrogen-containing fertilisers, and the manufacture of these generates [[Nitrous oxide|N<sub>2</sub>O]]. An estimated 3-5% of nitrogen provided as fertilizer for rapeseed is converted to N<sub>2</sub>O.{{Sfn|Lewis Jr.|2007}}\n\n== Diseases and pests==\nThe main diseases of the winter rapeseed crop are ''[[canker]]'', ''[[Pyrenopeziza brassicae|light leaf spot]]'', ''[[alternaria]]'' and ''[[sclerotinia]] stem rot''. Canker causes [[leaf spot]]ting, and premature ripening and weakening of the stem during the autumn-winter period. A conazole or [[triazole]] [[fungicide]] treatment is required in late autumn and in spring against ''canker'' while broad-spectrum fungicides are used during the spring-summer period for alternaria and sclerotinia control. Oilseed rape cannot be planted in close rotation with itself due to soil-borne diseases such as ''sclerotinia'', ''[[verticillium wilt]]'' and [[clubroot]].{{Sfn|Alford|2008}}\n\n=== Pests ===\nOilseed rape is attacked by a wide variety of insects, [[nematodes]], [[slugs]] as well as [[Wood-Pigeon|wood pigeons]]. The ''[[brassica pod midge]]'', ''[[Ceutorhynchus assimilis|cabbage seed weevil]]'', ''[[Ceutorhynchus pallidactylus|cabbage stem weevil]]'', ''[[Psylliodes chrysocephala|cabbage stem flea beetle]]'', ''[[Ceutorhynchus napi|rape stem weevil]]'' and ''[[pollen beetles]]'' are the primary insect pests that prey on the oilseed rape crop in Europe. The insect pests can feed on developing pods to lay eggs inside and eat the developing seeds, bore into the plant's stem and feed on pollen, leaves and flowers. Synthetic [[pyrethroid]] [[insecticides]] are the main attack vector against insect pests though there is a large-scale use of [[prophylactic]] insecticides in many countries. [[Molluscicide]] pellets are used either before or after sowing of the rapeseed crop to protect against slugs.{{Sfn|Alford|2008}}\n\n== History of the cultivars ==\nIn 1973, Canadian [[Agricultural science|agricultural scientists]]  launched a marketing campaign to promote [[canola]] consumption.{{Sfn|Thiyam-Holl\u00e4nder|Eskin|Matth\u00e4us|2013|p=4}} Seed, oil and protein meal derived from rapeseed cultivars which is low in erucic acid and low in glucosinolates was originally registered as a trademark, in 1978, of the Canola Council of Canada, as \"canola\".{{Sfn|Mag|1983|p=380}}{{Sfn|Roch\u00e9|2015|p=5}} This is now a generic term for edible varieties of rapeseed but is still officially defined in Canada as rapeseed oil that \"must contain less than 2% erucic acid and less than 30 \u00b5mol of glucosinolates per gram of air-dried oil-free meal.\"{{Sfn|Roch\u00e9|2015|p=5}}{{Sfn|CFIA|2017}}\n\nFollowing the [[European Parliament|European Parliament's]] [[Transport Biofuels Directive 2003|Transport Biofuels Directive]] in 2003 promoting the use of biofuels, the cultivation of winter rapeseed increased dramatically in Europe.{{Sfn|Bertazzini|Forlani|2016}}\n\n[[Bayer Cropscience]], in collaboration with [[BGI-Shenzhen]], China, Keygene N.V., the Netherlands, and the University of Queensland, Australia, announced it had sequenced the entire genome of ''B. napus'' and its constituent genomes present in ''B. rapa'' and ''B. oleracea'' in 2009. The \"A\" genome component of the amphidiploid rapeseed species ''B. napus'' is currently being sequenced by the Multinational ''Brassica'' Genome Project.<ref>{{cite web\n | title=The www.brassica.info website for the Multinational ''Brassica'' Genome Project\n | url=http://www.brassica.info\n}}</ref>{{Update after|2010|11|16}}\n\nA [[genetically modified]]-for-[[glyphosate]]-tolerance variety of rapeseed which was developed in 1998 is considered to be the most disease- and drought-resistant canola. By 2009, 90% of the rapeseed crops planted in Canada were of this sort,{{Sfn|Beckie |Harker |L\u00e9g\u00e8re |Morrison |2011|p=43}} adoption of which, however, has not been free of controversy. \n\n=== GMO controversy ===\n{{Main|Roundup Ready Canola}}\n\nThe [[Monsanto]] company [[genetically engineered]] new cultivars of rapeseed to be resistant to the effects of its [[herbicide]], [[Roundup (herbicide)|Roundup]]. In 1998, they brought this to the Canadian market. Monsanto sought compensation from farmers found to have crops of this cultivar in their fields without paying a license fee. However, these farmers claimed that the pollen containing the ''Roundup Ready'' gene was blown into their fields and crossed with unaltered canola. Other farmers claimed that after spraying Roundup in non-canola fields to kill weeds before planting, ''Roundup Ready'' [[Volunteer (botany)|volunteers]] were left behind, causing extra expense to rid their fields of the weeds.{{Sfn|Hartley|2008}}\n\nIn a closely followed legal battle, the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] found in favor of Monsanto's [[patent infringement]] claim for unlicensed growing of ''Roundup Ready'' in its 2004 ruling on ''[[Monsanto Canada Inc. v. Schmeiser]]'', but also ruled that Schmeiser was not required to pay any damages. The case garnered international controversy, as a court-sanctioned legitimization for the global patent protection of [[genetically modified crops]]. In March 2008, an [[out-of-court settlement]] between Monsanto and Schmeiser agreed that Monsanto would clean up the entire GMO-canola crop on Schmeiser's farm, at a cost of about CAD $660.{{Sfn|Hartley|2008}}\n\n==Production==\nThe [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] reports global production of 36 million tons of rapeseed in the 2003\u20132004 season, and an estimated 58.4 million tons in the 2010\u20132011 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fas.usda.gov/oilseeds/circular/2011/March/oilseeds.pdf |title=Oilseeds: World Markets and Trade |accessdate=17 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208134100/http://www.fas.usda.gov/oilseeds/circular/2011/March/oilseeds.pdf |archivedate=8 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nWorldwide production of rapeseed (including canola) has increased sixfold between 1975 and 2007. The production of canola and rapeseed since 1975 has opened up the edible oil market for rapeseed oil. Since 2002, production of biodiesel has been steadily increasing in EU and USA to 6 million metric tons in 2006. Rapeseed oil is positioned to supply a good portion of the vegetable oils needed to produce that fuel. World production was thus expected to trend further upward between 2005 and 2015 as biodiesel content requirements in Europe go into effect.<ref>Canola, Growing Great 2016, The Canola Council of Canada, 2007, page 3, 10</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Top rapeseed producers in millions of [[tonnes]]<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://faostat.fao.org/faostat/form?collection=Production.Crops.Primary&Domain=Production&servlet=1&hasbulk=0&version=ext&language=EN FAOSTAT]. UN Food & Agriculture Organisation.</ref><ref>[http://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#data/QC/ FAOSTAT]. UN Food & Agriculture Organisation.</ref>\n|-\n! Country ||1965 ||1975 ||1985||1995||2000||2005|| 2007 || 2009 || 2011 || 2012 || 2013 || 2014\n!2015\n!2016\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{CAN