{"title_page": "Las Iguanas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Las Iguanas Ltd\n| logo = [[File:Las Iguanas logo.svg|250px|Las Iguanas Logo Black And White]]\n| type = Private company\n| founders =  Eren Ali and Ajith Jaya-Wickrema\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Julie McEwan (brand director)}}\n| industry = [[Types of restaurant#Casual dining|Casual dining]]\n| genre = Latin American\n| products = Latin american foods from brazil, mexico and beyond\n| foundation = 1991, [[Bristol]], England\n| location = Bristol, England\n| homepage = [http://www.iguanas.co.uk iguanas.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Las Iguanas''' is a [[Types of restaurant#Casual dining|casual dining restaurant]] chain originating from the UK with a Latin American theme.<ref name=\"\u201ciguanas.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/about |title=About Las Iguanas |publisher=Las Iguanas |accessdate=22 January 2015 }}</ref> Founded in 1991, it operates 57 outlets in the UK as of July 2019.<ref name=\"iguanas locations\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants |title=Las Iguanas Locations |publisher=Las Iguanas  |accessdate=16 June 2017 }}</ref> It specialises in Latin American food from Brazil, Mexico and beyond, cooked from scratch.\n\n== History ==\nThe first Las Iguanas opened on St Nicholas Street, [[Bristol]], in April 1991,<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/about|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> offering a Latin American-themed menu. A further 53 restaurants have opened in the UK including [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], Manchester, London and Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Las Iguanas \u2013 Locations|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the group acquired its own Cacha\u00e7a sugar cane field and distillery on the Fazenda do Anil estate, outside [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Allegra Restaurant\">{{cite news|title=Allegra Restaurants Brand Portal \u2013 Las Iguanas \u2013 Overview|url=http://www.restaurantportal.co.uk/Brand-Profiles/Profiles/Las-Iguanas/1-Overview.aspx|accessdate=15 April 2015|publisher=Allegra Restaurants|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOne of the co-founders, Ajith Jaya-Wickrema, left Las Iguanas in August 2009 to start a Caribbean-themed restaurant chain, Turtle Bay.<ref>{{cite web|title= Las Iguanas founder leaves for \u2018other opportunities\u2019|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/People/Las-Iguanas-founder-leaves-for-other-opportunities|publisher=Big Hospitality|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> The first overseas branch of Las Iguanas was opened under franchise in [[Gibraltar]] in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iguanas.gi/|title=Las Iguanas Gibraltar|website=iguanas.gi}}</ref>\n\n== Food ==\n[[File:Xinxim.jpg|thumb|250px|An example of food served in Las Iguanas \u2013 Xinxim]]\nLas Iguanas menus include Latin American food such as nachos, burritos, xinxim, fajitas and tapas, along with steaks and burgers. They include vegetarian and vegan options such as veggie chilli, moqueca and empanadas, and gluten-free options. Las Iguanas is approved by the Vegetarian Society.<ref>{{cite web|title=Las Iguanas \u2013 Book Now|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegsocapproved.com/FDG/Details/73292|title=Vegsoc Approved|website=vegsocapproved.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Las iguanas deansgate.jpg|thumb|Las Iguanas Restaurant at [[Deansgate]], Manchester, England]]\n\n==Recognition==\nLas Iguanas made it on to the 2019 Sunday Times 100 Best Companies to work for in 26th place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.b.co.uk/the-lists/mid-companies/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822230453/https://www.b.co.uk/the-lists/mid-companies/|archive-date=22 August 2019|title=Best 100 Mid Companies|website=Best Companies}}</ref> The list celebrates UK companies with the highest levels of staff engagement. Las Iguanas also made the list in 2015 and 2013.<ref name=\"Sunday Times Top 100\">{{cite news|title=Las Iguanas celebrate Sunday Times Top 100 ranking|url=http://www.hospitalityandcateringnews.com/2015/01/las-iguanas-celebrate-sunday-times-top-100-ranking/|accessdate=15 April 2015|publisher=Hospitality & Catering News|date=5 January 2015}}</ref> Las Iguanas retained the Investors in People Gold award in 2015 and also holds IiP Champion status. The company held a Glassdoor.co.uk rating of 4.5 and a 92% approval rating of MD Mos Shamel in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Overview/Working-at-Las-Iguanas-EI_IE524326.11,22.htm|title=Working at Las Iguanas|website=Glassdoor}}</ref> Shamel stepped down from his role in July 2019, handing over to Julie McEwan who was promoted to brand director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.propelinfo.com/pi-Newsletter-tue.php?datetime=20190723080000|title=CDG reshapes leadership team, half-year like-for-likes up 3%|date=23 July 2019|website=Propel Newsletter}}</ref> In December 2019 Las Iguanas was recognised as the top-rated hospitality business on the Glassdoor Best Places to Work 2020 list, ranking 11th overall.<ref>[https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Award/Best-Places-to-Work-UK-LST_KQ0,22.htm </ref>\n\nLas Iguanas won best restaurant drinks offer at the Restaurant Magazine R200 Awards in October 2014.<ref name=\"Bills R200 Awards\">{{cite news|title=Bills Wins Operator of the Year at R200 Awards|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/Events-Awards/Bill-s-R200-Awards|accessdate=7 July 2015|publisher=BigHospitality|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt won the overall award at the National Burger Awards 2017 with the Buenos Aires Burger.<ref>http://www.nationalburgerawards.co.uk/</ref> It won Best Non-traditional Cuban Sandwich and was runner up in World's Best Traditional Cuban Sandwich at the International Cuban Sandwich Festival in Tampa, Florida in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecubansandwichfestival.com/|title=Winners of 7th Annual Cuban Sandwich Festival|year=2018|website=The Cuban Sandwich Festival|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601141114/http://www.thecubansandwichfestival.com/|archivedate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nLas Iguanas hit the headlines in August 2015 after their controversial tips policy was revealed.  Staff had to pay back 3% of all sales (4.4% in London) to the company at the end of every shift out of their tips.  Some staff had claimed that this charge was taken even when they had received no tips for some tables forcing them to 'pay to work'. Las Iguanas denied that the charge was ever taken from staff wages. Since then they had an internal vote amongst all the staff to agree a new policy. \n\n100% of cash tips are now shared by the team. When tips or service charge are paid for by a credit card or debit card, the company take a 2.5% administration charge, before distributing the remainder to employees (passing on fees for opting to pay by credit or debit card to customers was banned in the UK in January 2018). Tips and service charges are in addition to the National Minimum Wage and [[National Living Wage]]. In practice, this means for every \u00a31 in tips given on a credit card, the company keeps 2.5p to cover credit card fees and administration costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iguanas.co.uk/ourpolicy|title=Las Iguanas|website=iguanas.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/aug/23/restaurant-tipping-policy-forces-waiters-to-pay-to-work|title=Restaurants\u2019 tipping policy \u2018forces waiters to pay to work\u2019|first=Lisa|last=Bachelor|date=22 August 2015|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Las Iguanas}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.iguanas.co.uk}} \n\n{{Establishments serving chicken}}\n{{UK Food}}\n\n[[Category:Restaurant franchises]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bristol]]\n[[Category:Fast casual restaurants]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Las Iguanas Ltd\n| logo = [[File:Las Iguanas logo.svg|250px|Las Iguanas Logo Black And White]]\n| type = Private company\n| founders =  Eren Ali and Ajith Jaya-Wickrema\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Julie McEwan (brand director)}}\n| industry = [[Types of restaurant#Casual dining|Casual dining]]\n| genre = Latin American\n| products = Latin american foods from brazil, mexico and beyond\n| foundation = 1991, [[Bristol]], England\n| location = Bristol, England\n| homepage = [http://www.iguanas.co.uk iguanas.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Las Iguanas''' is a [[Types of restaurant#Casual dining|casual dining restaurant]] chain originating from the UK with a Latin American theme.<ref name=\"\u201ciguanas.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/about |title=About Las Iguanas |publisher=Las Iguanas |accessdate=22 January 2015 }}</ref> Founded in 1991, it operates 57 outlets in the UK as of July 2019.<ref name=\"iguanas locations\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants |title=Las Iguanas Locations |publisher=Las Iguanas  |accessdate=16 June 2017 }}</ref> It specialises in Latin American food from Brazil, Mexico and beyond, cooked from scratch.\n\n== History ==\nThe first Las Iguanas opened on St Nicholas Street, [[Bristol]], in April 1991,<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/about|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref> offering a Latin American-themed menu. A further 53 restaurants have opened in the UK including [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], Manchester, London and Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Las Iguanas \u2013 Locations|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the group acquired its own Cacha\u00e7a sugar cane field and distillery on the Fazenda do Anil estate, outside [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Allegra Restaurant\">{{cite news|title=Allegra Restaurants Brand Portal \u2013 Las Iguanas \u2013 Overview|url=http://www.restaurantportal.co.uk/Brand-Profiles/Profiles/Las-Iguanas/1-Overview.aspx|accessdate=15 April 2015|publisher=Allegra Restaurants|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOne of the co-founders, Ajith Jaya-Wickrema, left Las Iguanas in August 2009 to start a Caribbean-themed restaurant chain, Turtle Bay.<ref>{{cite web|title= Las Iguanas founder leaves for \u2018other opportunities\u2019|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/People/Las-Iguanas-founder-leaves-for-other-opportunities|publisher=Big Hospitality|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> The first overseas branch of Las Iguanas was opened under franchise in [[Gibraltar]] in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iguanas.gi/|title=Las Iguanas Gibraltar|website=iguanas.gi}}</ref>\n\n== Food ==\n[[File:Xinxim.jpg|thumb|250px|An example of food served in Las Iguanas \u2013 Xinxim]]\nLas Iguanas menus include Latin American food such as nachos, burritos, xinxim, fajitas and tapas, along with steaks and burgers. They include vegetarian and vegan options such as veggie chilli, moqueca and empanadas, and gluten-free options. Las Iguanas is approved by the Vegetarian Society.<ref>{{cite web|title=Las Iguanas \u2013 Book Now|url=http://www.iguanas.co.uk/restaurants|publisher=Las Iguanas|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vegsocapproved.com/FDG/Details/73292|title=Vegsoc Approved|website=vegsocapproved.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Las iguanas deansgate.jpg|thumb|Las Iguanas Restaurant at [[Deansgate]], Manchester, England]]\n\n==Recognition==\nLas Iguanas made it on to the 2019 Sunday Times 100 Best Companies to work for in 26th place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.b.co.uk/the-lists/mid-companies/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822230453/https://www.b.co.uk/the-lists/mid-companies/|archive-date=22 August 2019|title=Best 100 Mid Companies|website=Best Companies}}</ref> The list celebrates UK companies with the highest levels of staff engagement. Las Iguanas also made the list in 2015 and 2013.<ref name=\"Sunday Times Top 100\">{{cite news|title=Las Iguanas celebrate Sunday Times Top 100 ranking|url=http://www.hospitalityandcateringnews.com/2015/01/las-iguanas-celebrate-sunday-times-top-100-ranking/|accessdate=15 April 2015|publisher=Hospitality & Catering News|date=5 January 2015}}</ref> Las Iguanas retained the Investors in People Gold award in 2015 and also holds IiP Champion status. The company held a Glassdoor.co.uk rating of 4.5 and a 92% approval rating of MD Mos Shamel in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Overview/Working-at-Las-Iguanas-EI_IE524326.11,22.htm|title=Working at Las Iguanas|website=Glassdoor}}</ref> Shamel stepped down from his role in July 2019, handing over to Julie McEwan who was promoted to brand director.<ref>http://www.propelinfo.com/pi-Newsletter-tue.php?datetime=20190723080000</ref> In December 2019 Las Iguanas was recognised as the top-rated hospitality business on the Glassdoor Best Places to Work 2020 list, ranking 11th overall.<ref>[https://www.glassdoor.co.uk/Award/Best-Places-to-Work-UK-LST_KQ0,22.htm </ref>\n\nLas Iguanas won best restaurant drinks offer at the Restaurant Magazine R200 Awards in October 2014.<ref name=\"Bills R200 Awards\">{{cite news|title=Bills Wins Operator of the Year at R200 Awards|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/Events-Awards/Bill-s-R200-Awards|accessdate=7 July 2015|publisher=BigHospitality|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt won the overall award at the National Burger Awards 2017 with the Buenos Aires Burger.<ref>http://www.nationalburgerawards.co.uk/</ref> It won Best Non-traditional Cuban Sandwich and was runner up in World's Best Traditional Cuban Sandwich at the International Cuban Sandwich Festival in Tampa, Florida in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecubansandwichfestival.com/|title=Winners of 7th Annual Cuban Sandwich Festival|year=2018|website=The Cuban Sandwich Festival|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180601141114/http://www.thecubansandwichfestival.com/|archivedate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nLas Iguanas hit the headlines in August 2015 after their controversial tips policy was revealed.  Staff had to pay back 3% of all sales (4.4% in London) to the company at the end of every shift out of their tips.  Some staff had claimed that this charge was taken even when they had received no tips for some tables forcing them to 'pay to work'. Las Iguanas denied that the charge was ever taken from staff wages. Since then they had an internal vote amongst all the staff to agree a new policy. \n\n100% of cash tips are now shared by the team. When tips or service charge are paid for by a credit card or debit card, the company take a 2.5% administration charge, before distributing the remainder to employees (passing on fees for opting to pay by credit or debit card to customers was banned in the UK in January 2018). Tips and service charges are in addition to the National Minimum Wage and [[National Living Wage]]. In practice, this means for every \u00a31 in tips given on a credit card, the company keeps 2.5p to cover credit card fees and administration costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iguanas.co.uk/ourpolicy|title=Las Iguanas|website=iguanas.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/aug/23/restaurant-tipping-policy-forces-waiters-to-pay-to-work|title=Restaurants\u2019 tipping policy \u2018forces waiters to pay to work\u2019|first=Lisa|last=Bachelor|date=22 August 2015|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Las Iguanas}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.iguanas.co.uk}} \n\n{{Establishments serving chicken}}\n{{UK Food}}\n\n[[Category:Restaurant franchises]]\n[[Category:Companies base