 2, 2018</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.thezieglergirls.com/about-maddie/}}\n* {{IMDb name|4675650}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dbdOJ_yDDac Maddie and Mackenzie Ziegler Dance Like Fall's Major Trends\"], dance video by ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine (2015)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RpfS-yBu1_U Ziegler learns a holiday routine] with [[The Rockettes]] in 1 hour for ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' (2015)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Re2zNxFPvc Ziegler and Travis Wall dance duet] on ''[[So You Think You Can Dance: The Next Generation (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' (2016)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ziegler, Maddie}}\n[[Category:2002 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Female models from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American child models]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Edit5678", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maddie_Ziegler"}
{"title_page": "Tito Jackson", "text_new": "{{about|the member of the Jackson family|the former Boston City Council member|Tito Jackson (politician)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tito Jackson\n| image              = Tito Jackson London 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Tito Jackson in 2017\n| birth_name         = Toriano Adaryll Jackson\n| alias              = {{hlist|Tito}}\n| birth_date         = {{birthdate and age|mf=yes|1953|10|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|instrumentalist}}\n| years_active       = 1963\u2013present<ref name=\"GQ\">{{cite web|author=Charlie Burton|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/jacksons-legacy-jackson-5|title=Inside the Jackson machine|date=2018-02-07|accessdate=2019-10-24}}</ref> \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Delores Martes<br>|1972|1988|reason=div.}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = [[3T|Taj Jackson<br>Taryll Jackson<br>TJ Jackson]]\n| parents            = {{Plain list|\n* [[Joe Jackson (manager)|Joe Jackson]]\n* [[Katherine Jackson]]\n}}\n| family             = [[Jackson family|Jackson]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| instrument = {{hlist|Guitar|vocals|keyboards|synthesizer|[[programming (music)|programming]]}}\n| genre = {{flat list |\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|Soul]]\n* [[Blues music|Blues]]\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n}}\n| label = {{hlist|[[Steeltown Records|Steeltown]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|[[Motown Records|Motown]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{flat list |\n* [[The Jackson 5]]\n* [[Michael Jackson]]\n* [[Jermaine Jackson]]\n}}\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|titojackson.com}}\n}}\n'''Toriano Adaryll \"Tito\" Jackson''' (born October 15, 1953) is an American singer-songwriter and guitarist. Jackson was an original member of [[The Jackson 5]] and [[The Jackson 5|The Jacksons]], who rose to fame in the late 1960s and 1970s with the [[Motown Records|Motown]] label, and later recorded as a solo artist on the [[Columbia/Epic Label Group|Epic]] label in the late 1970s and 1980s. Tito is the third child in the [[Jackson family]].\n\n==Early life==\nToriano Adaryll Jackson was born the third of ten children in a black working-class family who lived in a three-room house in [[Gary, Indiana]]. His father, [[Joe Jackson (manager)|Joseph]], was a steel mill worker.  His mother, [[Katherine Jackson|Katherine]], was a devout [[Jehovah's Witness]]. At ten years of age, he was caught playing his father's guitar after he broke a string.<ref>{{cite book | last = Jackson| first = La Toya  | author2 = Patricia Romanowski  | title = [[La Toya: Growing up in the Jackson Family]] | publisher = [[New American Library]]  | year = 1991 | pages =  | isbn = 0-451-17415-1 }}</ref> After fixing the string, Joe demanded that his son play for him. Once he was finished, Jackson's father bought him his own guitar. Shortly thereafter, Joseph convinced Tito, Jackie, and Jermaine to form a singing group, having been impressed with the vocals of Jackie and Jermaine.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Career==\n{{main|The Jackson 5}}\nAfter first performing in school functions and supermarkets, the brothers began participating in local talent shows when Jackson was twelve. By then, his younger brother [[Michael Jackson|Michael]], then seven, had become the official lead singer of the group. In 1965, they changed their name from the Jackson Brothers to the Jackson Five, and won several talent shows around the Gary area. After winning the Amateur Night competition for [[The Apollo Theater]] in August 1967, Joe Jackson began to work part-time at the steel mill to help his sons secure a recording contract. The group signed with [[Steeltown Records]] in Gary, Indiana, in November of that year. In January 1968, the Jackson Five's first single, \"[[Big Boy (song)|Big Boy]],\" was released on the Steeltown label.<ref>[http://www.45rpmrecords.com/IN/Steeltown.php ''Big Boy'']; 45 RPM Records online; accessed June 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1969, the Jackson 5 signed with Motown Records in Detroit, and scored several hit songs, including the number-one singles \"[[I Want You Back]],\" \"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]],\" \"[[The Love You Save]],\" and \"[[I'll Be There (The Jackson 5 song)|I'll Be There]].\" Although Tito sometimes added brief lead vocals on some songs, he and Marlon rarely sang background harmony with the other brothers until much later in their careers. Despite his talent as a guitar player, Motown refused to allow Tito to perform guitar on any of the Jackson 5 recording sessions, instead forcing all their guitar parts to be performed by session musicians. As a direct result, Tito's guitar work did not make its debut until he and the Jacksons left Motown for CBS Records in 1976. He also began writing songs with his brothers during this time. Throughout his tenure as a Jackson 5 and Jacksons member, Tito can be heard on many album recordings, such as \"Zippee Doo Da\" and \"Man Of War.\" Tito, along with Jackie, were the most consistently present members of the Jacksons, with Jermaine, Marlon, Michael, and Randy leaving at different times. After the end of the ''Victory Tour,'' Tito performed session work and as a record producer. After releasing ''[[2300 Jackson Street]],'' the Jacksons ceased recording work.\n\nAfter years managing his family group featuring his sons, [[3T]], Jackson returned to the national spotlight after reuniting with his brothers on Michael's 30th anniversary concert special at [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\n===Solo work and other projects===\n[[File:Tito Jackson 2009-07-19.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.00|Jackson performing at the [[Motown]] 50th anniversary in [[Detroit]], 2009]]\n\nJackson began a solo career in 2003 performing as a [[blues music]]ian in various clubs with his band, which included producer and guitarist [[Angelo Earl]], and a management team that included Ed Tate. In 2007, in the United Kingdom, Jackson appeared as a judge on the [[BBC]] celebrity singing competition ''[[Just the Two of Us (TV series)|Just the Two of Us]]'' for series two of the show. He replaced singer [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], who was a judge on series one. His co-judges were vocal coach [[CeCe Sammy]], musician [[Stewart Copeland]] and radio DJ [[Trevor Nelson]]. During the tenure of his brothers' reality series, ''[[The Jacksons: A Family Dynasty]]'' (2009), which was produced, released, and transmitted after his brother Michael had died, he served as one of the executive producers alongside his other brothers.\n\nIn 2016, Tito Jackson joined his brothers and sisters and scored his first solo hit on the Billboard charts with the single, \"Get It Baby,\" featuring [[Big Daddy Kane]] from his album ''[[Tito Time]]''<ref>''[http://titojackson.com/music/tito-jackson/83-tito-time Tito Time]''</ref> becoming the ninth and final Jackson family sibling to place a solo single on the charts.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7393543/jackson-family-siblings-billboard-charts-tito Billboard: All 9 Jackson Family siblings have now had Solo Hits on the Billboard Charts]</ref> The album was released in Japan late in 2016, and in the U.S on iTunes in April 2017. Since its launch, three singles have been released to radio in the US. \nThe first single, ''When the Magic Happens'', featuring Jocelyn Brown, was released on April 1, 2017. Jackson launched the album for the UK market in September 2017.\n\n[[File:3T in performance (Hannover, 1996).jpg|thumb|upright=1.00| [[Taryll Jackson|Taryll]], [[TJ Jackson|TJ]] and [[Taj Jackson]] ]]\n\n==Personal life==\nJackson married Delores \"Dee Dee\" Martes in June 1972 at the age of 18, and the couple divorced in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-08-26/local/me-39096_1_michael-jackson| title=Michael Jackson's Nephews File Lawsuit Over Mother's Death; Court: Delores Jackson's family accuses her boyfriend of drowning her in his pool last year and complains that Dist. Atty. Gil Garcetti won't prosecute him| last=Tamaki| first=Julie| date=August 26, 1995| website=Los Angeles Times| archive-url=| archive-date=| access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/michael_jackson/2009/06/27/2009-06-27_coroner_releases_michael_jacksons_body_shattered_family_gathers_to_plan_king_of_.html?page=1 | title=Nanny says Michael Jackson's stomach had to be pumped regularly | work=[[nydailynews.com]] | publisher=[[New York Daily News]] | date=June 28, 2008 | accessdate=2009-06-28 | first1=Nancy | last1=Dillon | first2=Larry | last2=McShane | first3=Rich | last3=Schapiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Fernandez| first1=Alexia| title=Tito Jackson's Sons Describe Day Their Mother Died as 'a Nightmare': 'It's Like a Kid's Worst Memory'| url=http://people.com/music/tito-jackson-opens-up-about-ex-wifes-death/| accessdate=16 September 2017| work=PEOPLE.com| publisher=Time Inc.| date=15 September 2017| language=en}}</ref> In 1994, Martes was found dead floating in a swimming pool. The death was originally ruled accidental; however, a Los Angeles businessman, Donald Bohana, was subsequently charged with murdering her and later found guilty of second-degree murder in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | author=| url=http://www.okmagazine.com/michael-jackson/michael-jacksons-nephew-discusses-court-proceedings |title=Michael Jackson's Nephew Discusses Court Proceedings |publisher=OK! Magazine |date=August 21, 2009 | accessdate=2013-09-29}}</ref> He was sentenced 15 years to life in prison.\n\nThe couple had three sons, who comprise the musical group [[3T]]:\n\n* [[Taj Jackson|Toriano Adaryll Jackson, Jr.]] (\"Taj\") (born August 4, 1973)\n* [[Taryll Adren Jackson]] (born August 8, 1975)\n* [[Tito Joe Jackson]] (\"TJ\") (born July 16, 1978).\n\nTito now lives in Wolverhampton, UK.\n\nJackson has seven grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web | author=|url=http://www.jackson-source.com/index.php/next-generation/96-tj |title=TJ| publisher=Jackson-source.com  |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.jackson-source.com/index.php/next-generation/95-taryll | title=Taryll|publisher=Jackson-source.com | accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://2paragraphs.com/2015/10/who-is-tj-jacksons-wife-frances-on-the-jacksons-the-next-generation/ |title=Who Is TJ Jackson's Wife Frances on The Jacksons: The Next Generation? |publisher=2paragraphs.com |date= |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{See also|The Jackson 5 discography}}\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/tito-jackson-mn0000603763|title=Tito Jackson|work=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums|US R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Tito Time]]''\n|\n* Released December 21, 2016\n* Label: [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Get It Baby\" <small>(Featuring [[Big Daddy Kane]])</small>\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2016\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Tito Time''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"When The Magic Happens\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"One Way Street\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"We Made It\"\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"font-size:90%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes items which were not released in that country or failed to chart.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{jackson5}}\n{{Jackson family}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Tito}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people who self-identify as being of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:Jackson family (show business)|Tito Jackson]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:The Jackson 5 members]]\n[[Category:American funk guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the member of the Jackson family|the former Boston City Council member|Tito Jackson (politician)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tito Jackson\n| image              = Tito Jackson London 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Tito Jackson in 2017\n| birth_name         = Toriano Adaryll Jackson\n| alias              = {{hlist|Tito}}\n| birth_date         = {{birthdate and age|mf=yes|1953|10|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gary, Indiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|instrumentalist}}\n| years_active       = 1965\u2013present<ref name=\"GQ\">{{cite web|author=Charlie Burton|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/jacksons-legacy-jackson-5|title=Inside the Jackson machine|date=2018-02-07|accessdate=2019-10-24}}</ref> \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Delores Martes<br>|1972|1988|reason=div.}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = [[3T|Taj Jackson<br>Taryll Jackson<br>TJ Jackson]]\n| parents            = {{Plain list|\n* [[Joe Jackson (manager)|Joe Jackson]]\n* [[Katherine Jackson]]\n}}\n| family             = [[Jackson family|Jackson]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| instrument = {{hlist|Guitar|vocals|keyboards|synthesizer|[[programming (music)|programming]]}}\n| genre = {{flat list |\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|Soul]]\n* [[Blues music|Blues]]\n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n}}\n| label = {{hlist|[[Steeltown Records|Steeltown]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|[[Motown Records|Motown]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{flat list |\n* [[The Jackson 5]]\n* [[Michael Jackson]]\n* [[Jermaine Jackson]]\n}}\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|titojackson.com}}\n}}\n'''Toriano Adaryll \"Tito\" Jackson''' (born October 15, 1953) is an American singer-songwriter and guitarist. Jackson was an original member of [[The Jackson 5]] and [[The Jackson 5|The Jacksons]], who rose to fame in the late 1960s and 1970s with the [[Motown Records|Motown]] label, and later recorded as a solo artist on the [[Columbia/Epic Label Group|Epic]] label in the late 1970s and 1980s. Tito is the third child in the [[Jackson family]].\n\n==Early life==\nToriano Adaryll Jackson was born the third of ten children in a black working-class family who lived in a three-room house in [[Gary, Indiana]]. His father, [[Joe Jackson (manager)|Joseph]], was a steel mill worker.  His mother, [[Katherine Jackson|Katherine]], was a devout [[Jehovah's Witness]]. At ten years of age, he was caught playing his father's guitar after he broke a string.<ref>{{cite book | last = Jackson| first = La Toya  | author2 = Patricia Romanowski  | title = [[La Toya: Growing up in the Jackson Family]] | publisher = [[New American Library]]  | year = 1991 | pages =  | isbn = 0-451-17415-1 }}</ref> After fixing the string, Joe demanded that his son play for him. Once he was finished, Jackson's father bought him his own guitar. Shortly thereafter, Joseph convinced Tito, Jackie, and Jermaine to form a singing group, having been impressed with the vocals of Jackie and Jermaine.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n==Career==\n{{main|The Jackson 5}}\nAfter first performing in school functions and supermarkets, the brothers began participating in local talent shows when Jackson was twelve. By then, his younger brother [[Michael Jackson|Michael]], then seven, had become the official lead singer of the group. In 1965, they changed their name from the Jackson Brothers to the Jackson Five, and won several talent shows around the Gary area. After winning the Amateur Night competition for [[The Apollo Theater]] in August 1967, Joe Jackson began to work part-time at the steel mill to help his sons secure a recording contract. The group signed with [[Steeltown Records]] in Gary, Indiana, in November of that year. In January 1968, the Jackson Five's first single, \"[[Big Boy (song)|Big Boy]],\" was released on the Steeltown label.<ref>[http://www.45rpmrecords.com/IN/Steeltown.php ''Big Boy'']; 45 RPM Records online; accessed June 2018</ref>\n\nIn 1969, the Jackson 5 signed with Motown Records in Detroit, and scored several hit songs, including the number-one singles \"[[I Want You Back]],\" \"[[ABC (The Jackson 5 song)|ABC]],\" \"[[The Love You Save]],\" and \"[[I'll Be There (The Jackson 5 song)|I'll Be There]].\" Although Tito sometimes added brief lead vocals on some songs, he and Marlon rarely sang background harmony with the other brothers until much later in their careers. Despite his talent as a guitar player, Motown refused to allow Tito to perform guitar on any of the Jackson 5 recording sessions, instead forcing all their guitar parts to be performed by session musicians. As a direct result, Tito's guitar work did not make its debut until he and the Jacksons left Motown for CBS Records in 1976. He also began writing songs with his brothers during this time. Throughout his tenure as a Jackson 5 and Jacksons member, Tito can be heard on many album recordings, such as \"Zippee Doo Da\" and \"Man Of War.\" Tito, along with Jackie, were the most consistently present members of the Jacksons, with Jermaine, Marlon, Michael, and Randy leaving at different times. After the end of the ''Victory Tour,'' Tito performed session work and as a record producer. After releasing ''[[2300 Jackson Street]],'' the Jacksons ceased recording work.\n\nAfter years managing his family group featuring his sons, [[3T]], Jackson returned to the national spotlight after reuniting with his brothers on Michael's 30th anniversary concert special at [[Madison Square Garden]].\n\n===Solo work and other projects===\n[[File:Tito Jackson 2009-07-19.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.00|Jackson performing at the [[Motown]] 50th anniversary in [[Detroit]], 2009]]\n\nJackson began a solo career in 2003 performing as a [[blues music]]ian in various clubs with his band, which included producer and guitarist [[Angelo Earl]], and a management team that included Ed Tate. In 2007, in the United Kingdom, Jackson appeared as a judge on the [[BBC]] celebrity singing competition ''[[Just the Two of Us (TV series)|Just the Two of Us]]'' for series two of the show. He replaced singer [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], who was a judge on series one. His co-judges were vocal coach [[CeCe Sammy]], musician [[Stewart Copeland]] and radio DJ [[Trevor Nelson]]. During the tenure of his brothers' reality series, ''[[The Jacksons: A Family Dynasty]]'' (2009), which was produced, released, and transmitted after his brother Michael had died, he served as one of the executive producers alongside his other brothers.\n\nIn 2016, Tito Jackson joined his brothers and sisters and scored his first solo hit on the Billboard charts with the single, \"Get It Baby,\" featuring [[Big Daddy Kane]] from his album ''[[Tito Time]]''<ref>''[http://titojackson.com/music/tito-jackson/83-tito-time Tito Time]''</ref> becoming the ninth and final Jackson family sibling to place a solo single on the charts.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7393543/jackson-family-siblings-billboard-charts-tito Billboard: All 9 Jackson Family siblings have now had Solo Hits on the Billboard Charts]</ref> The album was released in Japan late in 2016, and in the U.S on iTunes in April 2017. Since its launch, three singles have been released to radio in the US. \nThe first single, ''When the Magic Happens'', featuring Jocelyn Brown, was released on April 1, 2017. Jackson launched the album for the UK market in September 2017.\n\n[[File:3T in performance (Hannover, 1996).jpg|thumb|upright=1.00| [[Taryll Jackson|Taryll]], [[TJ Jackson|TJ]] and [[Taj Jackson]] ]]\n\n==Personal life==\nJackson married Delores \"Dee Dee\" Martes in June 1972 at the age of 18, and the couple divorced in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-08-26/local/me-39096_1_michael-jackson| title=Michael Jackson's Nephews File Lawsuit Over Mother's Death; Court: Delores Jackson's family accuses her boyfriend of drowning her in his pool last year and complains that Dist. Atty. Gil Garcetti won't prosecute him| last=Tamaki| first=Julie| date=August 26, 1995| website=Los Angeles Times| archive-url=| archive-date=| access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/michael_jackson/2009/06/27/2009-06-27_coroner_releases_michael_jacksons_body_shattered_family_gathers_to_plan_king_of_.html?page=1 | title=Nanny says Michael Jackson's stomach had to be pumped regularly | work=[[nydailynews.com]] | publisher=[[New York Daily News]] | date=June 28, 2008 | accessdate=2009-06-28 | first1=Nancy | last1=Dillon | first2=Larry | last2=McShane | first3=Rich | last3=Schapiro}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Fernandez| first1=Alexia| title=Tito Jackson's Sons Describe Day Their Mother Died as 'a Nightmare': 'It's Like a Kid's Worst Memory'| url=http://people.com/music/tito-jackson-opens-up-about-ex-wifes-death/| accessdate=16 September 2017| work=PEOPLE.com| publisher=Time Inc.| date=15 September 2017| language=en}}</ref> In 1994, Martes was found dead floating in a swimming pool. The death was originally ruled accidental; however, a Los Angeles businessman, Donald Bohana, was subsequently charged with murdering her and later found guilty of second-degree murder in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | author=| url=http://www.okmagazine.com/michael-jackson/michael-jacksons-nephew-discusses-court-proceedings |title=Michael Jackson's Nephew Discusses Court Proceedings |publisher=OK! Magazine |date=August 21, 2009 | accessdate=2013-09-29}}</ref> He was sentenced 15 years to life in prison.\n\nThe couple had three sons, who comprise the musical group [[3T]]:\n\n* [[Taj Jackson|Toriano Adaryll Jackson, Jr.]] (\"Taj\") (born August 4, 1973)\n* [[Taryll Adren Jackson]] (born August 8, 1975)\n* [[Tito Joe Jackson]] (\"TJ\") (born July 16, 1978).\n\nTito now lives in Wolverhampton, UK.\n\nJackson has seven grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web | author=|url=http://www.jackson-source.com/index.php/next-generation/96-tj |title=TJ| publisher=Jackson-source.com  |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.jackson-source.com/index.php/next-generation/95-taryll | title=Taryll|publisher=Jackson-source.com | accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://2paragraphs.com/2015/10/who-is-tj-jacksons-wife-frances-on-the-jacksons-the-next-generation/ |title=Who Is TJ Jackson's Wife Frances on The Jacksons: The Next Generation? |publisher=2paragraphs.com |date= |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{See also|The Jackson 5 discography}}\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/tito-jackson-mn0000603763|title=Tito Jackson|work=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums|US R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Tito Time]]''\n|\n* Released December 21, 2016\n* Label: [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Get It Baby\" <small>(Featuring [[Big Daddy Kane]])</small>\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2016\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Tito Time''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"When The Magic Happens\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"One Way Street\"\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"We Made It\"\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"font-size:90%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes items which were not released in that country or failed to chart.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{jackson5}}\n{{Jackson family}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Tito}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American people who self-identify as being of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:Jackson family (show business)|Tito Jackson]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:The Jackson 5 members]]\n[[Category:American funk guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n", "name_user": "74.70.104.93", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tito_Jackson"}
